[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Rio de Janeiro 9.b3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nf3
{ The most logical move and by far the most popular. White develops the knight attacking e5 and once he develops the light squared bishop he is ready to castle. It will be seen in 23 theoretical chapters @@StartBracket@@out of 29@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Spanish Opening, also called Ruy Lopez, will be the topic of first 8 theoretical chapters. }
3... Nf6
{ The more popular  3...a6  is another story. There are a lot of completely different variations in the Spanish/Ruy Lopez making this opening very rich in ideas. }
4. O-O
{ Allowing Black to take on e4 is the main move.   There is also  4.d3  which is called the Anti-Berlin and  4.Nc3  transposes to the Four Knights Game with 4.Bb5. }
4... Nxe4
{ Taking the pawn might look a bit risky at first, White should easily regain it. However, Black will easily catch up with the development in the meantime. }
5. d4 { The main move. White just tries to open the game. } 5... Be7
{ We are at the starting position of the Rio de Janeiro Variation of the Berlin Defense. The origin of the name is mysterious, since in databases you will find only one game in this line played in the Brazilian city more than 100 years after the variation's birth @@StartBracket@@Tal-Panno, 1987@@EndBracket@@. In fact, it is one of the oldest variations known in chess and was upheld by such household names as Steinitz, Anderssen, Lasker, Tarrasch, Pilsbury, Reti, Smyslov, Spassky and others. However, in the 21th century, following the trend set by Kasparov-Kramnik 2000 World Championship match it has given way to l'Hermit Variation: 5...Nd6, leading to the famous Berlin Endgame @@StartBracket@@also called 'Berlin Wall'@@EndBracket@@ Thanks to an overwhelming popularity of 5....Nd6 nowadays, it is very probable that your fifth move: 5... Be7 will already come as a surprise to a majority of White players. If you are already a mainstream Berlin player, it can serve as a great alternative line. However, this line is not only an excellent surprise weapon. After analysing it thoroughly, I am confident that it is solid enough to be used as a main weapon even against high-level opposition. }
6. Qe2 { An absolutely main move and the only really challenging one. } 6...
Nd6 7. Bxc6
{ There is no other move to regain the pawn but for the bishop pair White manages to spoil Black's structure a bit. }
7... bxc6 { 7...dxc6  8.dxe5  Nf5  9.Rd1  looks bad for Black. } 8. dxe5 Nb7
{ This is the main position of the Rio de Janeiro Variation, which has been established as White's best chance for an advantage. White has numerous tries here and before examining them, it is important to understand the general features of the position. In my view, the key to its understanding lies in realization that Black's light square bishop is the most important piece on the board. While temporarily buried on c8, it has the potential to become a powerful piece, if developed along the b1-h7 or h1-a8 diagonal. If Black deploys it comfortably, in conjunction with putting his knight on an excellent e6 square, his pieces will enjoy remarkable harmony and he will hardly ever be worse. On the contrary, he will acquire great chances of taking over the initiative. If, however, White succeeds in restricting its development, he will be able to develop play against Black's structural weaknesses and force him to passive defence.    Having understood this, it is easy to predict both sides' plans. Black will try to play ...d5 with further ...Bf5 or ...Bb7 and .. .c5 on the cards. White's main idea will be to deny his opponent this possibility and he has 3 main ways to do so: early Re1, intending exd6 after .. .d5, forcing an undesirable ...Bxd6 due to an attack on the e7 bishop; early Nd4, putting c6 under attack; or early c4, intending to take control of the d5 square with Nc3 and Rd1. However, I believe Black has enough resources to meet any of these plans and achieve a fair share of chances. Enough of this lengthy introduction, let's study concrete variations! }
9. b3
{ The bishop may seem fine on b2 but at the moment White does nothing to fight against ...d5 }
9... O-O 10. Bb2 d5 11. c4
{ The critical move. If White does not put pressure on d5, Black achieves very comfortable play. Surprisingly, it has been played only once. It was, however, the highest level encounter in the 9. b3 line- Sutovsky-Malakhov, 2010. }
11... Nc5 12. Rd1 Qe8
{ A powerful pawn sacrifice, which makes the whole 9. b3 line satisfactory for Black. }
13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Rxd5 Ba6 15. Qe3 { or  15.Qc2  Ne6 } 15... Ne6
{ White's win of a pawn has come with a cost of opening the position, which obviously favors Black's bishop pair. His light squared bishop reigns supreme over the board, ready to cooperate with the Queen along the h1-a8 diagonal. Black has full compensation and very enjoyable play. }
