1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nf3
{ The most logical move and by far the most popular. White develops the knight attacking e5 and once he develops the light squared bishop he is ready to castle. It will be seen in 23 theoretical chapters @@StartBracket@@out of 29@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Spanish Opening, also called Ruy Lopez, will be the topic of first 8 theoretical chapters. }
3... Nf6
{ The more popular  3...a6  is another story. There are a lot of completely different variations in the Spanish/Ruy Lopez making this opening very rich in ideas. }
4. O-O
{ Allowing Black to take on e4 is the main move.   There is also  4.d3  which is called the Anti-Berlin and  4.Nc3  transposes to the Four Knights Game with 4.Bb5. }
4... Nxe4
{ Taking the pawn might look a bit risky at first, White should easily regain it. However, Black will easily catch up with the development in the meantime. }
5. Re1
{ This move has a very drawish reputation, and rightly so. Black faces few theoretical problems. That's the only big alternative to  5.d4  . }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1
{ The most popular and best move. According to classical principles White shouldn't block the d-pawn with his bishop. We will also cover  7.Bd3  but if Black doesn't fall for any cheap tricks it's not dangerous. }
7... Nxe5
{ I recommend not to allow  7...O-O  8.Nf3   or  7...Nf5  8.Nf3  , because with more pieces on the board White has better chances to acquire a slight edge. }
8. Rxe5 O-O 9. Nc3
{ A slightly more cunning concept than 9.d4. White at least tries to exchange the knight for Black's bishop, claiming a small long-term edge thanks to the bishop pair. }
9... Ne8
{ Getting ready for Nd5.   We don't want to give White a bishop pair so easily although  9...Bf6  10.Re1  Re8  11.Nd5  is playable. }
10. Nd5 Bd6 11. Re1 c6
{ It felt Black's play was slow but we are regaining some time. } 12. Ne3 Be7
{ 12...Bc7  13.Nf5  d5  14.Ne7+  Kh8  15.Nxc8  Rxc8  is the main line and Black must be fine here as well. However, I see no reason to concede the bishop pair and give White a claim to a small advantage. }
13. c4 Nc7 { We are just getting ready for ...d5. } 14. d4 d5 15. cxd5 Bb4
{ Black exchanges his theoretically good bishop to be able to recapture on d5 with the queen. All the next moves follow naturally. }
16. Bd2 Bxd2 17. Qxd2 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ White has slightly more active pieces but he is left with an isolated pawn. }
