1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nf3
{ The most logical move and by far the most popular. White develops the knight attacking e5 and once he develops the light squared bishop he is ready to castle. It will be seen in 23 theoretical chapters @@StartBracket@@out of 29@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Spanish Opening, also called Ruy Lopez, will be the topic of first 8 theoretical chapters. }
3... Nf6
{ The more popular  3...a6  is another story. There are a lot of completely different variations in the Spanish/Ruy Lopez making this opening very rich in ideas. }
4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to the futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5
{ An active place for our bishop. We will try to play in a similar fashion as we play against the Italian. We have 3 theoretical chapters starting from here. We will mainly focus on  5.O-O  ,  5.c3  and  5.Bxc6  . }
5. c3
{ This is considered a more accurate move than  5.O-O  ,  because it prevents ...Nd4. However, it gives Black an attractive possibility of an immediate strike in the centre. }
5... d5
{ Of course  5...O-O  and  5...d6  are viable alternatives, but the text is the most active and direct way of solving Black's opening problems.  I offer a similar approach of aiming at ...d5 instead of ...d6 against the Giuoco Piano. }
6. Nxe5
{ This move has not been the most popular, as Black has no problems demonstrating full compensation for the pawn. }
6... O-O 7. Bxc6
{ After  7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.Bxc6  there is  8...Bxf2+!  @@StartBracket@@see more in the theoretical chapter@@EndBracket@@. }
7... bxc6 8. d4 Bb6
{ 8...Bd6?!  allows  9.Nxc6  Qe8  10.e5!  when White can count on a slight edge. }
9. O-O Nxe4
{ Taking with the pawn has been more popular, but the text looks healthier, as Black retains more compact structure and avoids the Bg5 pin. }
10. Nxc6
{ The only real way to challenge Black is to accept the pawn sacrifice. } 10...
Qd6 11. Nb4 a5 12. Nd3 c5
{ Opening the position in order to increase the power of the bishops. } *

