1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nf3
{ The most logical move and by far the most popular. White develops the knight attacking e5 and once he develops the light squared bishop he is ready to castle. It will be seen in 23 theoretical chapters @@StartBracket@@out of 29@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Spanish Opening, also called Ruy Lopez, will be the topic of first 8 theoretical chapters. }
3... Nf6
{ The more popular  3...a6  is another story. There are a lot of completely different variations in the Spanish/Ruy Lopez making this opening very rich in ideas. }
4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to the futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5
{ An active place for our bishop. We will try to play in a similar fashion as we play against the Italian. We have 3 theoretical chapters starting from here. We will mainly focus on  5.O-O  ,  5.c3  and  5.Bxc6  . }
5. Bxc6
{ This move, which is highly popular on the high level, is hardly an attempt to gain an opening advantage. Instead, White wants to avoid more forcing lines, which often lead to quick simplification and play a slow, positional game. }
5... dxc6 6. Nbd2
{ This is not merely a different move order than  6.O-O  or  6.h3  .  By not committing himself on the kingside, White keeps an option of building an aggressive setup with Nc4, Qe2, h4-h5, Bd2 and O-O-O after the usual ...Nd7 and ...O-O. Of course, Black has his ways to counter this idea, but he has to react in a very nuanced way and be constantly careful about White's threats on the kingside. This is why I recommend a different, much simpler and safer approach for Black here. }
6... Be6 { Stopping Nc4 but  6...Nd7  is also OK. } 7. O-O
{ The most popular move. Note that  7.Nxe5  fails to  7...Qd4  . } 7... Nd7 8.
Nb3 Bb6 9. Ng5
{ White has to go after the bishop if he wants to pose Black any problems. }
9... Bxb3
{ We are not afraid of opening the a-file despite the fact we often consider queenside castle. Actually White's structure with doubled pawns is less mobile.   Here  9...Nf8  is not a mistake but might be a little bit inaccurate as White has a tiny little something after  10.Qh5  . }
10. axb3 f6 11. Nf3 Qe7
{ We just prepare a long castle but of course  11...Nc5  or  11...Nf8  followed by ...Ne6 played by many grandmasters is totally fine. }
12. Nd2 a6
{ We are not only securing our bishop but note that there is hardly a way for White to open anything on the queenside @@StartBracket@@b4-b5 will never happen@@EndBracket@@. }
13. Nc4 Ba7 14. Qh5+
{ A disruptive move, provoking a weakening in order to stop Black from castling short. However, the long castle is more promising anyway. }
14... g6 15. Qe2 O-O-O
{ Black's king feels very well on the queenside, where it cannot be easily attacked. }
