[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Scotch Game 9.Nd2 #02"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nf3
{ The most logical move and by far the most popular. White develops the knight attacking e5 and once he develops the light squared bishop he is ready to castle. It will be seen in 23 theoretical chapters @@StartBracket@@out of 29@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Game had always remained in the shadow of the Ruy Lopez and the Italian Game, until Garry Kasparov started playing it successfully in the 1990s. Since then, many players have decided to follow the world champion's example and nowadays it is a popular opening on both professional and amateur level. We have 4 chapters covering this topic. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 { The main and most reliable move. } 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5
Qe7 { Black blocks his bishop, but forces White to do the same. } 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
c4
{ Absolutely the main move but we obviously cover all the alternatives in this repertoire. }
8... Nb6
{ 8...Ba6 is the main line, but I recommend to play the text move, because it is at least as good and requires less memorization. }
9. Nd2 Qe6 { Black prepares ...Bb4 and ...Ba6. } 10. b3
{ White strengthens the c4 pawn and prepares to meet ...Bb4 with Bb2. } 10...
a5
{ The key idea of the variation. The a-pawn march essentially solves all Black's problems. }
11. Bb2 { 11.Qe3  a4  12.Bb2  Bb4  transposes to our main line. } 11... a4
{ 11...Bb4  is dubious because  12.a3  Bxd2+  13.Qxd2  is just better for White who got a bishop pair for nothing.  Somehow Black can't easily break through. This was played in the 16th game of the World Championship match Kasparov-Karpov in 1990. Kasparov went on to win that game and later the match by one point. }
12. g3
{ The bishop looks nice on the long diagonal, but at the same time the defence of the c4 pawn is weakened. }
12... Bb4
{ There is no reason to hurry with exchanging on b3-sometimes the ...a3 resource can prove useful. }
13. Bg2 O-O 14. O-O d5
{ As we see in 12.Qe3 line where White develops the bishop more modestly we undermine e5 pawn. Here the c4 pawn is a potential target. }
15. Nf3
{ This has been White's most popular choice in the position, but it allows Black to take over the initiative. }
15... a3 { It turns out that the white bishop lacks good retreat squares. } 16.
Bd4 c5
{ Going for it! This is much more ambitious than  16...Ba6  which allows  17.Bxb6  cxb6  18.Nd4 }
17. cxd5 Qxd5
{ The key moment. White has a few options, but neither of them fully solves his problems. It's important to see we couldn't play  17...Nxd5  due to  18.Ng5  . Objectively Black is better and we analyse it further in the theoretical section. }
*

