1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nf3
{ The most logical move and by far the most popular. White develops the knight attacking e5 and once he develops the light squared bishop he is ready to castle. It will be seen in 23 theoretical chapters @@StartBracket@@out of 29@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ This is called Four Knights Game - I guess you can see why :@@EndBracket@@ Now White has a lot of different moves but the main move is  4.Bb5  and  4.d4  is the Scotch variation and  4.Bc4  is the Italian variation. }
4. Nxe5
{ The so-called Halloween Gambit, which is hardly an opening suited for a serious game. The sacrifice is obviously unsound and Black should be winning quite easily. }
4... Nxe5 5. d4 Ng6 6. e5 Ng8
{ It looks ugly but we don't want to give our piece back. We only suffer for one move which is a low price for a piece. }
7. Bc4 d5 { Sacrificing a pawn to fasten the piece development. } 8. Bxd5 N8e7
{ Black has objectively a winning advantage but of course there is still some play left. }
