1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nf3
{ The most logical move and by far the most popular. White develops the knight attacking e5 and once he develops the light squared bishop he is ready to castle. It will be seen in 23 theoretical chapters @@StartBracket@@out of 29@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ This is called Four Knights Game - I guess you can see why :@@EndBracket@@ Now White has a lot of different moves but the main move is 4.Bb5 and 4.d4 is the Scotch variation and 4.Bc4 is the Italian variation. }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4
{ The Scotch Variation of the Four Knights, which, as the name suggests, is often reached via the Scotch move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  . In recent years, it has gained in popularity as an alternative to  5.Nxc6  . }
5... Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Taking towards the centre. Our pawns are doubled but we will push ...d5 next. }
7. Bd3 d5 8. exd5 { By far the most popular. } 8... O-O
{ Black usually plays  8...cxd5  which is not bad but we have another idea in mind. }
9. O-O Bg4
{ A fresh idea, which occured in high-level practice in 2018. It allows Black to equalize in a dynamic way, without need of delving into the intricacies of various move orders after the automatic  9...cxd5  . }
10. f3
{ This seems to be critical. It's so far the most popular and it's also a top engine's recommendation. It weakens the g1-a7 diagonal  (we will make a use of that)  but it's a tempo move. The play is very concrete.     We also cover  10.Ne2  and  10.Be2  in the theoretical section. }
10... Bh5
{ Whatever White does Black should be able to keep the dynamic equality. } *

