1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nf3
{ The most logical move and by far the most popular. White develops the knight attacking e5 and once he develops the light squared bishop he is ready to castle. It will be seen in 23 theoretical chapters @@StartBracket@@out of 29@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ This is called Four Knights Game - I guess you can see why :@@EndBracket@@   Now White has a lot of different moves but the main move is  4.Bb5  and  4.d4  is the Scotch variation and  4.Bc4  is the Italian variation. }
4. Bb5 Nd4
{ The recent correspondence and over the board praxis has established this move to be very promising, yielding Black great results. As we will see, White can easily end up in trouble if he does not proceed cautiously. }
5. Bc4 { We also deal with  5.Ba4  as well as  5.Nxd4  or  5.O-O } 5... Bc5 6.
Nxe5 Qe7
{ The key move, not being afraid of any capture on f7 @@StartBracket@@which are bad@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Nf3 { The most popular move. } 7... d5
{ Just like against  7.Nd3  this is a key resource. Black sacrifices even more material but gets enormous activity. }
8. Bxd5 Bg4 9. d3 O-O-O
{ Finishing the development and preparing forcing operations. } 10. Be3 Nxd5
{ It's time for the action! Otherwise White's bishop would move away. } 11.
Nxd5 Rxd5 12. exd5 Re8
{ This silent move justifies Black's whole concept of play. Black plans ...Bxf3 followed by ...Qh4. Both sides needs to be accurate but with the best play it can end in a forced draw. }
*

