[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Italian Four Knights Game"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nf3
{ The most logical move and by far the most popular. White develops the knight attacking e5 and once he develops the light squared bishop he is ready to castle. It will be seen in 23 theoretical chapters @@StartBracket@@out of 29@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ This is called Four Knights Game - I guess you can see why :@@EndBracket@@ Now White has a lot of different moves but the main move is 4.Bb5 and 4.d4 is the Scotch variation and 4.Bc4 is the Italian variation. }
4. Bc4
{ Black should be happy to see this move, which gives him an opportunity to immediately take over the initiative with a typical tactic. }
4... Nxe4
{ This trick was known in the 19th century. For example in 1886 it was featured in the game Dirk Van Foreest - Arnold Van Foreest @@StartBracket@@yes, these are the ancestors of Lucas and Jorden!@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nxe4 d5 6. Bd3 { The only sensible move. } 6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 Bd6
{ Giving extra support to the e5 pawn. Our plan would be to prepare ... f5. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 Nb4
{ This strong move was discovered by correspondence players.   9...f5  is desirable but it fails to  10.Bxc6  bxc6  11.Nxe5  With the text Black prepares 10...f5 simultaneously preventing 11. Bxc6 and 11.Bd5+.   But the more natural  9...Re8  and  9...Nd4  are enough for equality. }
*

