1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nf3
{ The most logical move and by far the most popular. White develops the knight attacking e5 and once he develops the light squared bishop he is ready to castle. It will be seen in 23 theoretical chapters @@StartBracket@@out of 29@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the oldest openings in chess. It was developed in the 16th and 17th centuries by famous Italian masters Damiano, Polerio and Greco. It has always been frequently seen in beginners' and amateurs' games but its popularity among strong players gradually ceased in favor of the Ruy Lopez, which was considered a better try for an advantage until very recently. However, things have changed dramatically in recent years. Due to the futility of their attempts against the Berlin Defence, top players have started seeking ways to pose Black problems in the long-forgotten Italian. As a result of the trend set by Carlsen, Anand, Caruana, Karjakin, Vachier- Lagrave, Giri and other strong players it has suddenly become more popular than the Ruy Lopez and its theory has grown enormously. Unlike just a few years ago, Black is nowadays required to know the nuances of different lines and move orders to obtain a good position out of the opening. We have 4 theoretical chapters covering the Italian and there are also some gambit tries possible from here. }
3... Bc5
{ 3...Nf6  is fine but it's a completely different story. There is for example  4.Ng5  d5  5.exd5  Na5  6.Bb5+  c6  7.dxc6  bxc6  8.Be2  with very complex play. }
4. c3
{ This is usually played with the intention of 5.d4 or 5. d3 with the idea to delay castle @@StartBracket@@otherwise it transposes to 4.0-0@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Nf6 5. d4
{ Going for the d4 break immediately is the old way of playing the Italian. Nowadays it is seen mostly at lower levels, because it has long been known not to give White any realistic hopes for an advantage. }
5... exd4 6. e5 { A modern treatment of the 5.d4 line. } 6... d5
{ A key counter attacking resource in this type of position. Without this move Black would be clearly worse. }
7. Bb5 Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6
{ Modern grandmasters clearly prefer this move, but of course  8...Bb4  is playable.  We are keeping some pressure on the d4 pawn but sometimes this bishop can become very bad so you need to be aware of this. }
9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be3 f5
{ 10...Bg4  is much more popular, but I think this continuation is at least as promising for Black.  Our idea is to simply push ...f4 and if White takes en passant he exchanges his strong e5 pawn. }
