1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nf3
{ The most logical move and by far the most popular. White develops the knight attacking e5 and once he develops the light squared bishop he is ready to castle. It will be seen in 23 theoretical chapters @@StartBracket@@out of 29@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the oldest openings in chess. It was developed in the 16th and 17th centuries by famous Italian masters Damiano, Polerio and Greco. It has always been frequently seen in beginners' and amateurs' games but its popularity among strong players gradually ceased in favor of the Ruy Lopez, which was considered a better try for an advantage until very recently. However, things have changed dramatically in recent years. Due to the futility of their attempts against the Berlin Defence, top players have started seeking ways to pose Black problems in the long-forgotten Italian. As a result of the trend set by Carlsen, Anand, Caruana, Karjakin, Vachier- Lagrave, Giri and other strong players it has suddenly become more popular than the Ruy Lopez and its theory has grown enormously. Unlike just a few years ago, Black is nowadays required to know the nuances of different lines and move orders to obtain a good position out of the opening. We have 4 theoretical chapters covering the Italian and there are also some gambit tries possible from here. }
3... Bc5
{ 3...Nf6  is fine but it's a completely different story. There is for example  4.Ng5  d5  5.exd5  Na5  6.Bb5+  c6  7.dxc6  bxc6  8.Be2  with very complex play. }
4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. c3
{ That's the main move. In the theoretical section we will see in details what are possible differences if White postpones this move and plays for example 6.Nbd2 or some 6.h3 first. There are also 6.Bg5 and 6.Re1. }
6... d5
{ The most active approach, reminiscent of the variation I recommend against 4.d3 anti-Berlin main line. }
7. exd5 Nxd5
{ We have reached one of the most important structures in this repertoire. White mainly plays against the e5-pawn and sometimes grabs space on the queenside. Black, on the other hand seeks counterplay against the d3-pawn and on the kingside, where he has the pawn majority. Typical continuations include ...Nb6, ...Bg4, ...Bd6 or ...f6 @@StartBracket@@after ...Nb6@@EndBracket@@. }
8. a4
{ The most challenging move, favored by elite players. The idea is quite cunning. After  8...Bg4  ,  White wants to stop the typical ...Nb6  resource by  9.a5! }
8... a5
{ Possible is  8...Nb6  9.Bb5  Ne7!  introduced by Wesley So.  White's light-squared bishop is such an important piece, that it is worth sacrificing a pawn to eliminate it. It's not a move one could come up with over the board. We just recommend a simpler approach. }
9. Re1 { The most natural move targeting the e5 pawn. } 9... Nb6 10. Bb5 Bd6
{ This is our typical move, while  10...Bg4  11.h3  Bh5  loses to  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.Rxe5 }
11. Nbd2 Bg4
{ This logical move wasn't considered by Karsten Muller and Georgios Souleidis in 'Winning with the Slow @@StartBracket@@but Venomous!@@EndBracket@@ Italian' @@StartBracket@@New In Chess 2016@@EndBracket@@.   They mention only  11...Na7  and  11...Bf5  which are playable but we prefer this natural move, it's a standard setup for us in this system. }
12. Ne4 Na7
{ Going after the light squared bishop. Now, White is obliged to take immediate action if he wants to fight for the advantage. Note that with the inclusion of a4 and ...a5 we can't play   12...f5  because  13.Nxd6  cxd6  14.Qb3+  Kh8  15.Ng5  and now the desired  15...Qf6  runs into  16.Bxc6  and the loose knight on  b6  drops. }
13. h3 Bh5 14. d4
{ The only challenging move after which there are a lot of exchanges. We are going to reach an endgame which we analyzed carefully and the conclusion is it's fine for us. }
14... exd4 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. Qxd4 Bxf3 { It's all forced. } 17. Qxd6 cxd6 18.
gxf3 Nxb5 19. axb5 a4
{ Fixing the b2 pawn. The arising endgame was assessed as favourable for White by Martyn Kravtsiv in the second volume of 'The Italian Renaissance' @@StartBracket@@Quality Chess 2020@@EndBracket@@. However, our extensive analysis leads to the conclusion that it's equal and both sides need to be quite precise here. We analyse this endgame in details in the theoretical section. }
