[Black "Ponziani Opening #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nf3
{ The most logical move and by far the most popular. White develops the knight attacking e5 and once he develops the light squared bishop he is ready to castle. It will be seen in 23 theoretical chapters @@StartBracket@@out of 29@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nc6 3. c3
{ This is the Ponziani Opening, one of the oldest chess openings. White just wants to build a strong centre with d4, but of course we will try to stop it. }
3... d5
{ A logical continuation fighting for the centre. As we will see, some of the lines are quite sharp and forcing but these usually are objectively very good for us. }
4. Qa4
{ The main move. Later we will also consider  4.Bb5  ,  4.exd5  and  4.d3  The first two give Black some advantage. }
4... f6 { That looks ugly but there was no convenient way to protect e5. } 5.
Bb5
{ White is playing only for tricks. Better is the passive  5.d3  but there is not much to remember there. }
5... Ne7 6. exd5 Qxd5 7. d4 e4 8. c4
{ That's probably bad but the objectively stronger  8.Ng1  doesn't make much sense. }
8... Qh5
{ By analogy with the main line, this retreat sets White difficult problems }
9. Nfd2 Qg6
{ Covering e4, attacking g2 and preparing ...Bh3 in case White castles. } 10.
g3 a6 { Preparing to sac the exchange for an attack. } 11. Nc3 axb5 12. Qxa8
Nxd4 13. O-O b4 14. Ncxe4 Kf7
{ White's king is seriously weakened and his queen is out of play. Black is planning some ...h5-h4 or ... f5. }
*

