[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. f4
{ The King's Gambit was the most popular opening of the Romantic Era of chess. Nowadays it's not a very serious try, White has even problems to hold equality. However, there are a lot of options and some of the lines are really sharp and crazy. We dedicate 3 theoretical chapters to this opening. }
2... exf4
{ Now we have 3.Nf3, 3.Bc4 and there are also other 3rd move alternatives which aren't dangerous. In the quickstarter let's just have a look at the first two options. }
3. Bc4 Nc6
{ This move, according to John Shaw, an author of a massive book on the King's Gambit, is the refutation of the Bishop's Gambit. By 'refutation' he doesn't mean that Black wins, but that he achieves a better position in all variations. I think he is right in principle, but many of the specific lines he included in his book can be improved upon. }
4. Nf3
{ It's difficult to say that already this natural move is dubious but in fact this is the case. Black has a relatively simple way to obtain a really big advantage. }
4... g5 5. O-O { 5.Nc3?  g4!  should be close to winning. } 5... Bg7 6. d4 d6
7. c3 h6 8. h4
{ White hopes for  8...g4?  9.Bxf4!  gxf3  10.Qxf3  with serious compensation for the piece. But Black is not obliged to comply.   We should add  8.g3  enters some wild complications but at the end it just doesn't work for White. }
8... Qf6 { The ...Qg6-h5 maneuver promises Black a big advantage } *

