[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. f4
{ The King's Gambit was the most popular opening of the Romantic Era of chess. Nowadays it's not a very serious try, White has even problems to hold equality. However, there are a lot of options and some of the lines are really sharp and crazy. We dedicate 3 theoretical chapters to this opening. }
2... exf4
{ Now we have  3.Nf3  ,  3.Bc4  and there are also other 3rd move alternatives which aren't dangerous. In the quickstarter let's just have a look at the first two options. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Schallop Defence, which is the fifth most popular of Black's replies. The basis for this recommendation is simple. Compared to  3...g5  or  3...d6  Black does not need to learn many variations here and still achieves an excellent position in all of the lines. }
4. e5
{ A critical choice. There are also  4.d3  d5   and  4.Nc3  d5  but these are relatively easier to learn. }
4... Nh5
{ The knight may seem awkward on h5, but plays an important role defending the f4 pawn, and, as we will see, after ...g5 it can be transferred via g7 to very good squares, namely e6 or f5. }
5. Be2 g5 6. O-O h6
{ An important move, played in order to always be able to recapture with the pawn in case of Nxg5.   6...Rg8  is not bad but it doesn't actually transpose to one  of 5.d4 and 6. Be2 lines because after  7.d4  d5  White can take en passant and in the line mentioned above that's not the case. }
7. d4 d6
{ More accurate than  7...d5  , which would allow  8.c4  ,  where White would achieve a better version of the lines arising after 5.d4 d5. Now however, Black is ready to complete his development and I wasn't able to find any way for White to achieve compensation for the pawn. }
8. Re1 Be7 9. exd6 cxd6
{ as usual in the King's Gambit the position is a bit messy but after all Black is a pawn up and it's not just a random pawn. The pawn on f4 restricts White's pieces. }
*

