{ White has to play very energetically not to end up a pawn down for nothing. }
6... g5 7. g4 { The only move keeping White afloat. } 7... Ng7
{ The pawn is poisoned for now:  7...Bxg4?  8.Rg1  and White takes over the initiative. }
8. Nc3 dxc4
{ We would prefer to make this move after the white bishop moves, but the pressure on d5 forces us to take immediately. }
9. Bxc4 Bxg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. h4
{ Again, White stays in the game only by playing a very accurate sequence. }
11... Nc6 { Attacking the weak d4-point. } 12. Nd5 Be7 13. hxg5 Bg4
{ The bishop was unstable on h5. Now the position is still a bit messy but White has overextended and Black is better. You will find more details in the theoretical chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Bc4
{ The Bishop's Opening has recently been gaining in popularity, mainly as a means of avoiding the Petroff Defence. }
2... Nf6 3. d3 c6
{ I believe Black should take the opportunity to grab space in the centre. This way, he can fight for more than equality. }
4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 a5 { Softening up the bishop on b3. } 6. a4 Bb4+
{ This provokes 7. c3 and Black is arguing that this extra move is actually counterproductive as he can't develop the knight to c3.   6...Bd6  is playable but  7.exd5  cxd5  8.Bg5  Be6  9.Nc3  is maybe equal but somehow easier for White. }
7. c3
{ 7.Nc3  d4  loses a piece and moves like  7.Nbd2  or  7.Bd2  don't pose any problems. Black has a good development and nice centre. No further knowledge is required in this case. }
7... Bd6 8. exd5 cxd5 9. Bg5 Be6 10. Na3
{ Thanks to 6... Bb4+ as we can see, White can't put more pressure on d5 with Nc3. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nb5 Bb8
{ The bishop might look strange on b8 but it doesn't even block the rook which can be developed via 6th rank. White has less space so his idea is to push d4 and after ...e4 undermine Black's centre with c4. He can play immediately   12.d4  or  12.O-O  and Re1, Nd2 and only then d4. Either way Black will get a good play as we will see in the theoretical chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "2.Nc3 & 3.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nc3
{ White can opt for three different setups with this move: 1@@EndBracket@@ Some kind of delayed Bishop's Opening with Bc4 2@@EndBracket@@ The Glek Opening with g3 3@@EndBracket@@ Vienna Gambit with f4. }
2... Nc6
{ 2...Nf6  is much more popular but we want to have ...f5 move against the Glek Opening. }
3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3
{ The only independent try. Much more popular  4.Nf3  just transposes to Four Knights with 4.Bc4. }
4... Na5 { Just going for the important bishop. } 5. Nge2
{ The most popular, but in the theoretical section we will also look at  5.Bb3  and a tricky  5.Qf3 }
5... Bc5
{ The bishop on c4 is not running away so we don't have to take it yet. } 6.
O-O O-O 7. Ng3 Nxc4
{ Before playing ...d6 let's just exchange on c4.   7...d6  8.Na4  Bd4  9.c3  Bb6  10.Bb5  allows White to preserve his bishop. }
8. dxc4 d6 9. Qd3 Be6
{ We will continue with ...a5, ...Nd7 and ...f6. Our position is rock-solid. White doesn't have any pawn breaks except f4 which in fact isn't threatening at all. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Glek Opening"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nc3
{ White can opt for three different setups with this move: 1@@EndBracket@@ Some kind of delayed Bishop's Opening with Bc4 2@@EndBracket@@ The Glek Opening with g3 3@@EndBracket@@ Vienna Gambit with f4. }
2... Nc6
{ 2...Nf6 is much more popular but we want to have ...f5 move against the Glek Opening. }
3. g3
{ The Glek Opening, which is not a particularly threatening variation. White's setup generally includes Bg2, d3, Nge2, etc. Black has various acceptable ways of developing his forces, but the one including quick f5 is especially promising, as shown by the following lines: }
3... Bc5 4. Bg2 d6 { Getting ready for ...f5. } 5. Nge2 f5 { As planned. } 6.
d3 Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. Na4
{ Going after the bishop has been almost the only move played by White. It's difficult to suggest anything else really. }
8... fxe4 9. Nxc5 dxc5 10. dxe4 b6
{ With an edge. White's pieces are passively placed, whereas Black's are ready for active play, e.g. ...Ba6 @@StartBracket@@b7@@EndBracket@@, ...Qe8, ...Rd8, ...Nd4 @@StartBracket@@b4@@EndBracket@@. The bishop pair offers White no real benefits here, as his bishops are too restricted. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Vienna Game"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. Nc3
{ White can opt for three different setups with this move: 1@@EndBracket@@ Some kind of delayed Bishop's Opening with Bc4 2@@EndBracket@@ The Glek Opening with g3 3@@EndBracket@@ Vienna Gambit with f4. }
2... Nc6
{ 2...Nf6 is much more popular but we want to have ...f5 move against the Glek Opening. }
3. f4
{ This looks like a version of the King's Gambit but it's actually called the Vienna Gambit. It's probably objectively a dodgy line and Black can come out on top. }
3... exf4 4. Nf3 g5 { We just play like in the King's Gambit. } 5. g3 Bg7 6. d4
d6 7. d5 { 7.gxf4  g4  is just very bad for White. } 7... Ne5 8. gxf4
{ Now White regains the pawn but in the process ends up in a weakened position. }
8... gxf4 9. Bxf4 Bg4
{ White has overextended and Black is better. You will learn more later but already that's enough to memorize. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Centre Game"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ The starting point of this repertoire. From the very beginning of chess history 1. e4 e5 has been established as the most principled and sound way to face White's most popular first move. Also, learning the open games is the key to understanding chess. Active play, concrete fight for the centre and maneuvering in flexible structures are exactly what strong players should excel at. }
2. d4
{ This will be the main topic of the final theoretical chapter. We will also cover some funky stuff like going for the Scholar's Mate with  2.Qh5  or the Bongcloud Attack with  2.Ke2 }
2... exd4 3. Qxd4
{ This is called the Centre Game. White loses an important tempo in the opening and develops his pieces awkwardly. Black can successfully fight for more than equality.   There is also  3.c3  @@StartBracket@@Danish Gambit@@EndBracket@@ which we will not accept and meet with  3...d5  . }
3... Nc6 4. Qe3
{ There is also  4.Qc4  covered in the theoretical section. We should just complete quickly our development one way or the other. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 { Just developing actively. } 6. Bd2 O-O 7. O-O-O
{ That was White's idea. He wants to attack us on the kingside by pawnstorming us with f3, g4, h4 etc. That might be very dangerous but he isn't too well developed. }
7... Re8
{ White already feels the heat on e4, there is also ... d5 in the air. White usually sacrifices the pawn. }
8. Qg3
{ White gets out of the pin and if he manages to play f3 his position is actually quite nice. We have to accept the sacrifice. }
8... Nxe4 9. Nxe4 Rxe4
{ White may have some compensation but it won't be enough for a full pawn. } *

