1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Be7
{ We are at the starting position of the Rio de Janeiro Variation of the Berlin Defense. The origin of the name is mysterious, since in databases you will find only one game in this line played in the Brazilian city more than 100 years after the variation's birth Tal-Panno, 1987. In fact, it is one of the oldest variations known in chess and was upheld by such household names as Steinitz, Anderssen, Lasker, Tarrasch, Pilsburry, Reti, Smyslov, Spassky and others. However, in the 21th century, following the trend set by Kasparov-Kramnik 2000 World Championship match it has given way to l'Hermit Variation: 5...Nd6, leading to the famous Berlin Endgame also called 'Berlin Wall' Thanks to an overwhelming popularity of 5...Nd6 nowadays, it is very probable that your fifth move: 5... Be7 will already come as a surprise to a majority of White players. If you are already a mainstream Berlin player, it can serve as a great alternative line. However, this line is not only an excellent surprise weapon. After analysing it thoroughly, I am confident that it is solid enough to be used as a main weapon even against high-level opposition. }
6. dxe5 O-O 7. Qe2 d5 8. c4
{ The most direct attempt, which provokes a long forcing line. } 8... a6 9.
cxd5
{ Requires some serious play from Black, so remembering this line should have your high priority. }
9... axb5
{ A move known in the world of correspondence chess. In all OTB games Black played 9...Qxd5? but he is simply lost after 10.Bc4 Nd4 11.Nxd4 Qxd4 12.Rd1 Qxe5 13. Rd5. }
10. dxc6 Qd5
{ Playing actively. This is a very concrete line which proves Black is fine. }
11. Re1 Nc5 { Unfortunately  11...Bf5  12.cxb7  Qxb7  13.Nd4  is not as good. }
12. Nc3 Qxc6 13. Nd4
{ Our queen is getting pushed back but nothing bad is happening. } 13... Qd7
14. Ndxb5
{ White has got the pawn, but Black's bishops will provide him great compensation. }
14... c6 15. Rd1 Qg4 16. f3
{ 16.Nd4  Qxe2  17.Ncxe2  Re8=  Black plans the simple ...Bf8. His bishop pair clearly gives him a full compensation. }
16... Qh5 17. Nd6
{ 17.Nd4  Na4!  This knight trade offers Black free play and great compensation. }
17... Nb3 { This typical tactic justifies Black's whole previous play. } 18.
Nxc8
{ 18.Rb1  Nxc1  19.Rbxc1  Bg5=  ...Bf4 is going to equalize completely, but 20.g4 cannot be really taken seriously. }
18... Rfxc8 19. Rb1 Nxc1 20. Rbxc1
{ This position can be counterintuitive. It seems White is a sound pawn up, but it turns out Black is ready to challenge this belief. }
20... Re8 { Black targets e5 and in fact has a deep idea in mind. } 21. Re1
{ Played in order to protect the e5-pawn. Other moves aren't dangerous. } 21...
Bg5 { Anyway. } 22. f4 Qxe2 23. Nxe2 Bd8 24. a3
{ 24.Nc3  f6  25.e6  f5=  Black is ready for ...Bf6 and White will have a hard time trying to hang on to the extra pawn. }
24... f6 25. exf6 Bxf6 26. Rc2 Rad8
{ Black's activity completely compensates for the pawn deficit. } *

