Qd2 { A counterintuitive, but best way of meeting the pin. } 15... Rf5
{ This move, along with 13...Bb4, constitutes the core of Black's counterplay. At the moment we hit e5 provoking f4, but the main goal of this move is to give some room to our queen on f8 or h4 with ...Rh5. It should be added, there are even no OTB games starting from this position. }
16. a3 { A critical move. } 16... Be7 17. f4 c5
{ This was the original recommendation before the course was published. This looks logical, with ...d6 next, we just need to open some lines. However, a closer look leads to the conclusion Black is in troubles. }
18. Ne4 d6 19. Rad1 Qf8
{ Stepping off any capture on c5 while d6 is defended indirectly, but now comes a strong move. }
20. g4
{ This is much better than a greedy  20.Qa5  Rb6  21.Qxa7  where Black has some compensation. }
20... Bb7 { The only move.  20...Rf7  21.exd6  is lost. } 21. gxf5 Bxe4 22. f6
gxf6 23. Bxc5
{ Initially the engine @@StartBracket@@even Stockfish 12@@EndBracket@@ believes Black is OK. Given a bit of time it turns out to be hardly a playable position. }
*

