6. Qe2 { An absolutely main move and the only really challenging one. } 6...
Nd6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. dxe5 Nb7
{ This is the main position of the Rio de Janeiro Variation, which has been established as White's best chance for an advantage. White has numerous tries here and before examining them, it is important to understand the general features of the position. In my view, the key to its understanding lies in realization that Black's light square bishop is the most important piece on the board. While temporarily buried on c8, it has the potential to become a powerful piece, if developed along the b1-h7 or h1-a8 diagonal. If Black deploys it comfortably, in conjunction with putting his knight on an excellent e6 square, his pieces will enjoy remarkable harmony and he will hardly ever be worse. On the contrary, he will acquire great chances of taking over the initiative. If, however, White succeeds in restricting its development, he will be able to develop play against Black's structural weaknesses and force him to passive defence.    Having understood this, it is easy to predict both sides' plans. Black will try to play ...d5 with further ...Bf5 or ...Bb7 and .. .c5 on the cards. White's main idea will be to deny his opponent this possibility and he has 3 main ways to do so: early Re1, intending exd6 after .. .d5, forcing an undesirable ...Bxd6 due to an attack on the e7 bishop; early Nd4, putting c6 under attack; or early c4, intending to take control of the d5 square with Nc3 and Rd1. However, I believe Black has enough resources to meet any of these plans and achieve a fair share of chances. Enough of this lengthy introduction, let's study concrete variations! }
9. Nc3
{ The most popular move and the starting point of our chapter covering the main line of Rio de Janeiro Variation. }
9... O-O 10. Re1
{ White's most popular way of playing. He intends to meet ... d5 with exd6!, making the desirable ...cxd6 recapture impossible because of the e7 bishop being under attack. 10.Nd4 transposes to 9.Nd4. }
10... Nc5 { Black starts by maneuvering the knight to an optimal position. }
11. Be3 Ne6 12. Nd4
{ This is the main move. It's a very direct approach. White again stops the ...d5 break and a certain ingenuity is required from Black. }
12... Rb8
{ A key move. The idea is quite common in the Open Games, e.g. the Scotch. White will find it hard to meet the attack on the b2 pawn without making concessions. }
13. b3 Bb4 { The kind of nasty pin that is always annoying. } 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15.
Qd2 { A counterintuitive, but best way of meeting the pin. } 15... Rf5
{ This move, along with 13...Bb4, constitutes the core of Black's counterplay. At the moment we hit e5 provoking f4, but the main goal of this move is to give some room to our queen on f8 or h4 with ...Rh5. It should be added, there are even no OTB games starting from this position. }
16. a3 { A critical move. } 16... Be7 17. f4 a5
{ A strong novelty which rejuvenates the line. Now a7 is not hanging and we get a bit of space on the queenside. As it is a novelty that's a completely new territory and there are no games. We did a match @@StartBracket@@8 games, 5 minutes per game@@EndBracket@@ between Stockfish 12 and itself and all the games finished with a draw. }
18. Ne4 d5 { If it works then such an active move should be played. } 19. Nc5
Rb5 { Forcing White's next move so that we could exchange more pawns. } 20. b4
d4
{ If not for this move White would keep a bind and we'd suffer. Now we are forcing the endgame where we will be able to nullify White's microscopic edge. }
21. Qxd4
{ 21.Bxd4  is easy to handle so we won't even make it as a trainable.  21...Bxc5  22.bxc5  Rxc5  regaining the pawn and despite our worse structure we have a potential to have a better bishop. In those types of positions the activity is more important than static factors.  23.Qf2  Rc4  24.Be3  c5  - the game is equal but I'd start worrying as White. }
21... Qxd4 22. Bxd4 axb4 { It's all forced. } 23. axb4 Rxb4 24. Be3 Bxc5
{ Going for the opposite coloured bishops endgame.   Unfortunately  24...Rc4  25.Nb3  isn't great especially that  25...Rxc2  26.Nd4  is a fork. }
25. Bxc5 Rc4 26. Be3 Rc3
{ A classy move keeping White's rook busy protecting the bishop while pawn on c2 is not going anywhere. If White is not careful and we manage to activate our bishop there is a chance we could even take over the initiative. We are at move 26 and it's a drawish position but we'll provide a few more moves.   Note that  26...Rxc2  27.Red1  Rf8  28.Ra7  h5  29.Rxc7  should be OK for us but we need to realise that we have to get rid of our  c6  pawn.  29...Rb2  30.h3  Rb7  31.Rxc6  Rb2  should be easy to hold. }
27. g4
{ 27.Ra7  h5  28.Rxc7  Ba6  is one example where it is White who needs to start thinking about a draw. }
27... Rf8 28. Ra7 Rf7 29. Re2 { White can repeat with  29.Ra8 } 29... c5
{ The engine gives around 0.00. } *

