Qd2 { A counterintuitive, but best way of meeting the pin. } 15... Rf5
{ This move, along with 13...Bb4, constitutes the core of Black's counterplay. At the moment we hit e5 provoking f4, but the main goal of this move is to give some room to our queen on f8 or h4 with ...Rh5. It should be added, there are even no OTB games starting from this position. }
16. a3 { A critical move. } 16... Be7 17. f4 a5
{ A strong novelty which rejuvenates the line. Now a7 is not hanging and we get a bit of space on the queenside. As it is a novelty that's a completely new territory and there are no games. We did a match @@StartBracket@@8 games, 5 minutes per game@@EndBracket@@ between Stockfish 12 and itself and all the games finished with a draw. }
18. Ne2
{ This is less natural than 18.Ne4 but it's stronger according to Stockfish 12. }
18... Ra8 { Let's just protect the pawn if we don't have a good active move. }
19. Ng3 Rf7 20. Ne4
{ This was a very sophisticated maneuver. White spent three moves instead of one to bring the knight to e4 but he pushed our rooks to passive positions.   The crucial difference is that now  20...d5  21.Nc5  allows White to keep a nice bind as we don't have ...Rb5. }
20... h6
{ Stopping Ng5.   20...Qf8  21.Ng5  Bxg5  22.fxg5  was played in some games of the aforementioned engine match and Black manages to hold.  So allowing Ng5 is not bad, but it seems White has more chances here than after 20...h6. }
21. Red1
{ It may seem more logical to play with the other rook but don't forget about a3 pawn.   If White starts with  21.Qc3  we can also play  21...Qf8  when  22.Red1  transposes. }
21... Qf8
{ A typical move. We take c5 under control @@StartBracket@@...c5 with ...Bb7 would be dangerous for White@@EndBracket@@ and also in some lines we can win the pawn on a3. }
22. Qc3 { White protects a3 indirectly and fights for c5 square. } 22... d6
{ We need to open the game sooner or later. Yes, c6 will drop but as we will see we have enough activity.   Note that  22...Bxa3  doesn't work due to  23.Rxa3  Qxa3  24.Bc5  trapping the queen. }
23. Qxc6 Ra6 24. Qb5 { 24.Qc3  allows  24...Bb7 } 24... d5 25. Nf2 c6
{ Pushing back white's queen as  25...Bxa3  26.Rxa3!  Qxa3  27.Bc5  hitting the queen and threatening Qe8+ wins for White. }
26. Qd3 Bxa3
{ Finally we restore material balance. Black is OK. Also playing a pawn down with  26...c5  seems interesting. }
