6. Qe2 { An absolutely main move and the only really challenging one. } 6...
Nd6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. dxe5 Nb7
{ This is the main position of the Rio de Janeiro Variation, which has been established as White's best chance for an advantage. White has numerous tries here and before examining them, it is important to understand the general features of the position. In my view, the key to its understanding lies in realization that Black's light square bishop is the most important piece on the board. While temporarily buried on c8, it has the potential to become a powerful piece, if developed along the b1-h7 or h1-a8 diagonal. If Black deploys it comfortably, in conjunction with putting his knight on an excellent e6 square, his pieces will enjoy remarkable harmony and he will hardly ever be worse. On the contrary, he will acquire great chances of taking over the initiative. If, however, White succeeds in restricting its development, he will be able to develop play against Black's structural weaknesses and force him to passive defence.    Having understood this, it is easy to predict both sides' plans. Black will try to play ...d5 with further ...Bf5 or ...Bb7 and .. .c5 on the cards. White's main idea will be to deny his opponent this possibility and he has 3 main ways to do so: early Re1, intending exd6 after .. .d5, forcing an undesirable ...Bxd6 due to an attack on the e7 bishop; early Nd4, putting c6 under attack; or early c4, intending to take control of the d5 square with Nc3 and Rd1. However, I believe Black has enough resources to meet any of these plans and achieve a fair share of chances. Enough of this lengthy introduction, let's study concrete variations! }
9. Nc3
{ The most popular move and the starting point of our chapter covering the main line of Rio de Janeiro Variation. }
9... O-O 10. Re1
{ White's most popular way of playing. He intends to meet ... d5 with exd6!, making the desirable ...cxd6 recapture impossible because of the e7 bishop being under attack. 10.Nd4 transposes to 9.Nd4. }
10... Nc5 { Black starts by maneuvering the knight to an optimal position. }
11. Be3 Ne6 12. Qc4
{ This is a novelty but it's the first line of Stockfish 12. White is trying to get only a small advantage but it could be very unpleasant. For the moment Black's main idea of ...d5 is stopped, but Black will be able to force this so the idea is in fact much deeper. We will talk about this in a few moves. }
12... Rb8 13. b3 d5 { Black achieves his goal so where are the problems? } 14.
exd6 { 14.Qxc6 d4 wins for Black. There is no rook hanging on a8. } 14... cxd6
{ Now both c6 and a7 are under attack but as we will see this is not what bothers us. }
15. Rad1
{ A powerful move. Instead of taking a pawn but White focuses his forces in the centre while Black's pawns remain vulnerable. Compared to Khalifman's 12.Rad1 somehow Black was forced to play ...Rb8 weakening a7 and this makes a difference. However, that's not something a human could easily come up with because taking on a7 immediately was not as problematic. That's just extremely deep. }
15... Rb7
{ Somehow we don't have better moves. For example  15...Qc7  16.Nd4  Nxd4  17.Nd5!  works very well for White.   Now we are defending  a7  and  c6  as  16.Qxc6  Rc7  wins. Despite having a bishop pair we were unable to activate our pieces and central pawns thus we are under some pressure. White doesn't have much but it's a bit uncomfortable. Still, if you get this on the board it means you are meeting a very high level of opening expertise. Against so well prepared opponents sometimes we have to accept such positions. You can have a look at some sample lines we provided. }
16. Nd4
{ The only line to keep the initiative for White.   The direct attempt doesn't bring much  16.Ne5  Bd7  17.Nxd7  Qxd7  18.Ne2  d5  19.Qd3  a5  Black has enough play.  20.a4  Bb4  21.Bd2  Bxd2  22.Qxd2  Rb4  nice rook activation  23.Nc1  Qc7  and Black is fine.   Also  16.Ne2  seems dangerous at first but after  16...Qc7  17.Ned4  Nxd4  18.Nxd4  c5  Black gets good play. It's always good if we can play very directly  19.Ne2  Be6  20.Qd3  d5  with a good game. }
16... Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Qc7 18. Qd3 { Sidestepping ...d5. } 18... d5 19. Qe3 Bd6
20. h3 Bf5
{ Black's position looks fine but White keeps some edge because the knight is very strong here. }
21. Na4 { Getting ready to occupy c5. } 21... Qd8
{ Not  21...Bxc2  in view of  22.Bxg7!  Now Black may think about ...h6 and ...Qg5. Objectively White has a slight pull but from a practical perspective it's also not easy to keep it. }
