1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4
{ In this chapter we will focus on 5. Re1 and 5.Qe2. } 5. Qe2
{ Another minimalistic move, which is often used by White players if they want to force a quick draw. }
5... Ng5
{ Instead of the usual  5...Nd6  - see here, I offer this novel approach, which allows Black to get off the beaten track and fight for more than equality. }
6. Bxc6
{ White wants to take on e5 with the queen but he gives up the bishop pair. }
6... dxc6 7. Qxe5+
{ 7.Nxe5  Ne6  is less than nothing for White, it's not clear how to continue the development. }
7... Ne6 8. Re1 Be7 9. Nc3 O-O
{ As usual, Black's bishop pair provides enough compensation for the worse pawn structure. }
