[White "5. Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defence - 5.Re1 and 5.Qe2"]
[Black "Berlin Defence 5.Qe2 Ng5 #03"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4
{ In this chapter we will focus on 5. Re1 and 5.Qe2. } 5. Qe2
{ Another minimalistic move, which is often used by White players if they want to force a quick draw. }
5... Ng5
{ Instead of the usual  5...Nd6  , I offer this novel approach, which allows Black to get off the beaten track and fight for more than equality. }
6. Nxg5 Qxg5 7. d4
{ At first sight the position looks dangerous but Black has concrete resources which should give him a good play. }
7... Qe7 8. dxe5 Nd4 { We would be struggling without this move. } 9. Qd3 Qxe5
{ Black asks White to show his compensation for the pawn, which might not prove easy.     For the safe alternative  9...Nxb5  see here }
10. Nc3 Ne6 11. f4
{ Pretty much forced, as Black was planning 11...c6 with inadequate compensation for White. }
11... Qd4+ 12. Be3 Qxd3 13. Bxd3 f6
{ Not a natural move but fortunately not the only choice so don't worry. It's the engine's choice and it's a deep prophylaxis against f5 and Bc4 when f7 is under pressure.   We have reached a curious position. At first glance, White seems to enjoy great play for the pawn, with the minor pieces already developed and the rooks ready to centralize. But under deeper investigation it becomes clear that his pieces lack targets to attack. Meanwhile, Black's plan is simple: gradually develop while not allowing white pieces to penetrate. If he succeeds, his advantage of a central pawn will become a decisive factor. A possible line is: }
14. Rfe1 Kd8 15. f5 Nc5 16. Bc4 Na6
{ A typical computer move and a strong one. Black calmly maneuvers his knight to c6 and White is unable to make use of his huge lead in development, eg. }
17. Ne4 Be7 { 17...Nb4?  18.Ng5! } 18. Rad1 { 18.c3  Nb8  =/+ } 18... Nb4 19.
Rd2 Nc6 20. Bf4 Rb8
{ A prophylactic move to defend b7 in anticipation of Nc5 after ...d6. Black is already better! Of course this is only a sample line and the whole 9...Qxe5 idea needs practical testing. In case you feel uncomfortable holding into the pawn and trying to withstand White's activity, you can retort to the safe 9... Nxb5 alternative. }
*

