{ In this chapter we will focus on 5. Re1 and 5.Qe2. } 5. Re1
{ This move has a very drawish reputation, and rightly so. Black faces few theoretical problems. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bd3
{ White hopes for a quick attack but he pays the price of blocking the d-pawn. Black should be able to repel White's aggression and obtain a very good position. }
7... Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. Nc3 c6 { Stopping Nd5. } 10. b3
{ White finds a way to develop the bishop but Black has time to regroup and grab the center. }
10... Ne8 { We are preparing ...d5. } 11. Bb2 d5 12. Qh5
{ A very primitive attacking attempt. } 12... Nf6 13. Qh4 Be6 14. Rg5
{ White threatens a devastating Nxd5 but we can easily parry this threat. }
14... g6 15. Qh6
{ This crude attacking attempt was refuted as early as 1898 in the game Janowski-Burn! }
15... d4 16. Ne2 Ng4 17. Rxg4 Bxg4
{ White gets only a pawn in return for the exchange. Janowski's last trick was }
18. Nxd4 Bg5 19. Nf5 { but it loses to the simple } 19... Bf6 *

