1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4
{ In this chapter we will focus on 5. Re1 and 5.Qe2. } 5. Re1
{ This move has a very drawish reputation, and rightly so. Black faces few theoretical problems. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bd3
{ White hopes for a quick attack but he pays the price of blocking the d-pawn. Black should be able to repel White's aggression and obtain a very good position. }
7... Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. Nc3 c6 { Stopping Nd5. } 10. b3
{ White finds a way to develop the bishop but Black has time to regroup and grab the center. }
10... Ne8 { We are preparing ...d5. } 11. Bb2 d5 12. Qf3
{ A natural queen development, White controls some squares on the kingside but as we will see Black's queen will also join the action on this side of the board. }
12... Bd6 13. Re2
{ This is an inaccurate retreat, because the e2-square is needed for the knight. }
13... Qh4 { Posing White concrete problems. } 14. h3
{ 14.g3  is bad in view of  14...Bg4  or  14...Qh3  with  ...Bg4  next. The rook is vulnerable on  e2  giving us important tempo. }
14... Nc7
{ Black transfers the knight to the excellent e6 square, from where it can jump to g5, causing White a headache. }
15. Ree1
{ There is nothing better than to admit the mistake and vacate the e2-square for the knight. }
15... f5
{ ...Ne6-g5 is a very serious threat. White is in trouble.   The immediate  15...Ne6  is not accurate as it allows White to almost equalize with  16.Qg4 }
