[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4
{ In this chapter we will focus on 5. Re1 and 5.Qe2. } 5. Re1
{ This move has a very drawish reputation, and rightly so. Black faces few theoretical problems. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1
{ The most popular and best move. According to classical principles White shouldn't block the d-pawn with his bishop. }
7... Nxe5
{ I recommend not to allow  7...O-O  8.Nf3   or  7...Nf5  8.Nf3  , because with more pieces on the board White has better chances to acquire a slight edge. }
8. Rxe5 O-O 9. Nc3
{ A slightly more cunning concept than 9.d4. White at least tries to exchange the knight for Black's bishop, claiming a small long-term edge thanks to the bishop pair. }
9... Ne8 10. Nd5 Bd6 11. Re1 c6 12. Ne3 Be7
{ 12...Bc7  13.Nf5  d5  14.Ne7+  Kh8  15.Nxc8  Rxc8  is the main line and Black must be fine here as well. However, I see no reason to concede the bishop pair and give White a claim to a small advantage. }
13. c4 Nc7 14. d4 d5 15. cxd5 Bb4
{ Black exchanges his theoretically good bishop to be able to recapture on d5 with the queen. All the next moves follow naturally. }
16. Bd2 Bxd2 17. Qxd2 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ White has slightly more active pieces but he is left with an isolated pawn. }
19. Re5 Qd6 20. Bc4 Bd7
{ Black is solid. He is always ready for some ...Re8 and he can also push pawns on the queenside. A sample line goes: }
21. Rae1 b5 22. Bb3 a5 23. a3
{ 23.a4  bxa4  24.Bxa4  Be6=  Rerouting the bishop to  d5  . } 23... a4 24. Ba2
Rae8 25. Qe3 Rxe5 26. dxe5 Qe7
{ Further exchanges are bound to occur, with complete equality. } *

