[White "5. Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defence - 5.Re1 and 5.Qe2"]
[Black "Berlin Defence 5.Re1 with 7.Bf1 and 9.d4 #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4
{ In this chapter we will focus on 5. Re1 and 5.Qe2. } 5. Re1
{ This move has a very drawish reputation, and rightly so. Black faces few theoretical problems. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1
{ The most popular and best move. According to classical principles White shouldn't block the d-pawn with his bishop. }
7... Nxe5
{ @@StartBracket@@I recommend not to allow 7...0-0 8.Nf3 or 7...Nf5 8. Nf3, because with more pieces on the board White has better chances to acquire a slight edge.@@EndBracket@@ }
8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re2
{ This strange-looking move has been popularized by Carlsen, who used it against Karjakin in their 2016 World Championship Match. The idea is that  10...Re8?!  is questionable now, because White can play  11.Bf4!  and in case of  11...Rxe2  , recapture with the queen, with a big lead in development. }
10... Nf5
{ A natural move which could be played also after 10.Re1.   Karjakin however played  10...b6  which is not bad but White got a little pull. }
11. c3 d5
{ Now the rook on e2 obstructs the development of the bishop on f1, so White can't claim even a tiny edge. }
