[White "5. Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defence - 5.Re1 and 5.Qe2"]
[Black "Berlin Defence 5.Re1 with 7.Bf1 and 9.d4 #04"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4
{ In this chapter we will focus on  5.Re1  and  5.Qe2  . } 5. Re1
{ This move has a very drawish reputation, and rightly so. Black faces few theoretical problems. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1
{ The most popular and best move. According to classical principles White shouldn't block the d-pawn with his bishop. }
7... Nxe5
{ I recommend not to allow  7...O-O  8.Nf3   or  7...Nf5  8.Nf3  , because with more pieces on the board White has better chances to acquire a slight edge. }
8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Bd3
{ A surprising exchange sacrifice first played in the correspondence game Rosenstock-Bischof, 1997 and brought back to life by strong OTB players in recent years. }
10... Bxe5
{ There is nothing wrong with accepting the challenge, neither in objective nor practical terms. }
11. dxe5 Ne8 12. Nc3
{ The point of the sacrifice is that ...d5 is now met by Nxd5. White wants to attack with Qh5 followed by a dark-squared invasion. Fortunately, Black has plenty of defensive and deflective resources. }
12... d6 13. Qh5 g6 14. Qh6 Be6
{ Black can't neglect solid development.  14...dxe5??  would be terrible because after  15.Bg5!  White's pieces attack too quickly and Black is completely lost. }
15. Bg5 Qd7 16. Ne4 f5
{ This great resource guarantees Black satisfactory play. He doesn't allow his king to get caged. Now it becomes a bit tricky for White to retain compensation. }
17. exf6 Bf5
{ 17...Bd5  , as in Predke-Kovalev, Khanty-Mansiysk 2016 is enough for equality, but here Black can fight for more. It is not apparent how White could achieve fully equal play. }
*

