1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4
{ In this chapter we will focus on 5. Re1 and 5.Qe2. } 5. Re1
{ This move has a very drawish reputation, and rightly so. Black faces few theoretical problems. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1
{ The most popular and best move. According to classical principles White shouldn't block the d-pawn with his bishop. }
7... Nxe5
{ I recommend not to allow  7...O-O  8.Nf3   or  7...Nf5  8.Nf3  , because with more pieces on the board White has better chances to acquire a slight edge. }
8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re1 Re8
{ A simple and logical move but the more popular  10...Nf5  11.c3  d5  is not bad either. It's just a question of taste. }
11. c3 { A recent trend but it doesn't pose Black too many problems. } 11...
Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Ne8 { Just preparing ...d5. } 13. d5 c6
{ Striking in the centre is the most straightforward way to equalize. } 14. Nd2
cxd5 15. Nf3
{ Although this temporary pawn sacrifice was tried by Giri against Caruana at the 2018 Olympiad, the idea is hardly impressive. White will ultimately have to exchange many pieces in order to regain the pawn, which almost guarantees a draw. The game followed: }
15... d6 16. Be3 Nc7 17. Qd2 Bd7
{ There are many playable moves but this is actually quite accurate. Black puts the bishop to c6 and moves the knight to e6 and controls d4. It may seem ugly but just have a look how effective it was. }
18. g3 Bc6 19. Bg2 Ne6 20. Rd1 Qa5 21. a3 h6 22. Nd4 Nxd4 23. Bxd4 Bxd4 24.
Qxd4 Re8 25. Bxd5 Qxd5 26. Qxd5 Bxd5 27. Rxd5 Re2
{ Draw was soon agreed in Giri-Caruana, Batumi @@StartBracket@@ol@@EndBracket@@ 2018 }
