1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4
{ In this chapter we will focus on 5. Re1 and 5.Qe2. } 5. Re1
{ This move has a very drawish reputation, and rightly so. Black faces few theoretical problems. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1
{ The most popular and best move. According to classical principles White shouldn't block the d-pawn with his bishop. }
7... Nxe5
{ I recommend not to allow  7...O-O  8.Nf3   or  7...Nf5  8.Nf3  , because with more pieces on the board White has better chances to acquire a slight edge. }
8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re1 Re8
{ A simple and logical move but the more popular  10...Nf5  11.c3  d5  is not bad either. It's just a question of taste. }
11. c3 { A recent trend but it doesn't pose Black too many problems. } 11...
Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Ne8 { Just preparing ...d5. } 13. d5 c6
{ Striking in the centre is the most straightforward way to equalize. } 14. Be3
{ This slightly improves over the Giri-Caruana game. As we will see White has a better way to develop the Knight than via d2-f3. }
14... cxd5 { A principled reaction accepting a pawn. } 15. Qd2 Nc7 16. Na3 d6
17. Nc2
{ Compared to the Giri-Caruana game, maybe the knight is a tiny bit better here than on f3 because it can not only jump to d4 but also to b4. In addition, if White wants to play g3 and Bg2 the diagonal won't be blocked. Still, it just doesn't look too dangerous. We have easy development. }
17... Bf5 18. Nb4 Be4
{ If  19.f3  now, Black has the intermezzo  19...a5!  White has a certain compensation for the pawn, but no more. He should ultimately win the pawn back, but then the position is likely to simplify to a draw. }
