{ This move has a very drawish reputation, and rightly so. Black faces few theoretical problems. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1
{ The most popular and best move. According to classical principles White shouldn't block the d-pawn with his bishop. }
7... Nxe5
{ I recommend not to allow  7...O-O  8.Nf3   or  7...Nf5  8.Nf3  , because with more pieces on the board White has better chances to acquire a slight edge. }
8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re1 Re8
{ A simple and logical move but the more popular  10...Nf5  11.c3  d5  is not bad either. It's just a question of taste. }
11. Nc3
{ The only sharp try available to White, which requires knowledge of concrete forcing lines. }
11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Bxd4
{ We win a very important central pawn but White has full compensation. Both sides need to make a few more accurate moves. }
13. Bf4 Ne8 14. Nd5 d6 15. Bg5
{ A clever way of forcing a weakening ...f6 move but it takes some time. }
15... f6 16. Be3 Be5
{ A little more accurate than taking on b2 immediately. Black provokes f4, which is a weakening move. }
17. Bc4 Kh8
{ Just stepping out of the pin to a safe location. White should try to force the issue now. Otherwise Black just goes ...c6, ... d5 and consolidates the extra pawn. }
18. f4 Bxb2 19. Rb1 Ba3 20. Qa5
{ White has a compensation for the sacrificed material. } 20... Bc5 21. Bxc5
dxc5 22. Qxc5 Nd6
{ Black still kept the extra pawn but we can give it back and finish the development. }
23. Qxc7 Bf5
{ White regained the pawn, but Black consolidated and the position is equal. }
*

