1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d4
{ A relatively rare way of omitting the main Berlin lines. As we will see, the play is likely to transpose to one of the subvariations of the classical ...a6 Ruy Lopez. }
4... exd4 5. e5 Ne4
{ It's important to remember that the knight is placed better on e4 and d5 because it has access to the always useful c5-square. }
6. O-O a6
{ The simplest way to achieve good play is to chase White's Spanish bishop. }
7. Ba4 Nc5 8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. Nxd4 Ne6
{ is a worse version of the 7. Bxc6, 9. Re1 line for White. The rook is still on f1. }
