[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d4
{ A relatively rare way of omitting the main Berlin lines. As we will see, the play is likely to transpose to one of the subvariations of the classical ...a6 Ruy Lopez. }
4... exd4 5. O-O a6 6. Ba4 Be7
{ Now we enter the territory of the 6. d4 line in the classical ...a6 Ruy Lopez. The line is still occasionally tried by players of varying levels, but it has already been established long ago that Black is doing great. }
7. e5 Ne4 8. Nxd4 O-O 9. Nf5
{ This is White's main idea. It would give him some hopes for an edge, if not for a clever operation available to Black now: }
9... d5
{ None of the series of exchanges that White has to choose from now poses any harm to Black. }
10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. Re1
{ White indirectly defends the e5-pawn, which should not trouble us. We can play around with this pawn, putting the bishop on f5 and transferring the knight to e6. }
12... Bf5 13. f3 Nc5 14. b3
{ A logical try to disrupt Black's harmonious piece deployment. } 14... Ne6 15.
Ba3 c5 16. Qxd5 Qh4 { Black hits too many weak points at once. } 17. Nc3 Rfd8
18. Qc4 Qd4+ 19. Kh1 Bxc2
{ White will need to fight for survival in a tough position. } *

