[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Ruy Lopez: Anti-Berlin - 4.d3 with 5.0-0 & others"]
[Black "Anti-Berlin 4.d3 & 5.0-0 #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completetely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5
{ In this chapter we will focus on 5.Nc3, 5.Nbd2 and 5.O-O while 5.c3 and 5.Bxc6 are covered later. }
5. O-O Nd4
{ I like this move, taking advantage of the lack of c3 move much more than the passive   5...d6   This knight exchange is advantageous to Black and I see no reason why White would be the one playing for the edge here. In fact, we will see that Black can take over the initiative quite easily if White is not cautious.   Note that  5...O-O  just loses a pawn to  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5 }
6. Nxd4 Bxd4 7. c3 Bb6 8. Bg5
{ A move that Black should be very happy to see. The bishop is going to end up hopelessly stranded on g3. Black can exploit this by expanding on the kingside. }
8... h6 9. Bh4 c6 10. Bc4 g5 11. Bg3 d6 12. Nd2 Bg4
{ Developing the bishop with tempo. } 13. Qb3
{ After other moves 13... h5 followed by 14...h4 would be already close to decisive. }
13... O-O { Black is fine, our plan is ...Nh5-f4. A sample line goes: } 14. h3
Bh5 15. Qc2 Bg6 { Making room for ...Nh5. } 16. Bb3 Nh5
{ A typical plan: the knight goes to the excellent f4 square. } 17. Bh2 Nf4 18.
Nc4 Bc7 19. Rad1 h5
{ Black is simply better. He enjoys straightforward play on the kingside and in the centre, while White is passive and has nothing to show in return. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
