{ In this chapter we will focus on 5.Nc3, 5.Nbd2 and 5.O-O while 5.c3 and 5.Bxc6 are covered later. }
5. O-O Nd4
{ I like this move, taking advantage of the lack of c3 move much more than the passive 5.... d6. This knight exchange is advantageous to Black and I see no reason why White would be the one playing for the edge here. In fact, we will see that Black can take over the initiative quite easily if White is not cautious. Note that 5...0-0 just loses a pawn to 6.Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nxe5. }
6. Nxd4 Bxd4 7. c3 Bb6 8. d4
{ May lead to quick simplifications but we have a nice little novelty. } 8...
a6
{ The main move is  8...O-O  and after  9.dxe5  Nxe4  10.Nd2  d5!  11.Nxe4  dxe4  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  the position is drawish. }
9. Ba4 O-O 10. dxe5 Nxe4
{ The position is equal but it is White who needs to be careful and not fall for a nice trap. }
11. Nd2 { This is wrong.  11.Bf4  d5  is just around equal. } 11... Nxf2 12.
Rxf2 Qh4
{ Note that White's queen can't help to protect f2 because the bishop on a4 hangs. }
13. g3 Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 Qxh2+ { Black is winning. } *

