[White "6. Ruy Lopez: Anti-Berlin - 4.d3 with 5.0-0 & others"]
[Black "Anti-Berlin 4.d3 & 5.0-0 #07"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completetely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5
{ In this chapter we will focus on 5.Nc3, 5.Nbd2 and 5.O-O while 5.c3 and 5.Bxc6 are covered later. }
5. O-O Nd4
{ I like this move, taking advantage of the lack of c3 move much more than the passive 5.... d6. This knight exchange is advantageous to Black and I see no reason why White would be the one playing for the edge here. In fact, we will see that Black can take over the initiative quite easily if White is not cautious. Note that 5...0-0 just loses a pawn to 6.Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nxe5. }
6. Nxd4 Bxd4 7. c3 Bb6 8. Na3
{ White plans to play Nc4 to chase away the bishop from the optimal diagonal. }
8... c6 9. Ba4 d6 10. Nc4 Bc7 11. Bb3 h6
{ It is useful to prevent Bg5 before castling here. } 12. Ne3 O-O 13. Qf3 a5
{ Played in order to 'soften up' the b3 bishop. } 14. a4 Be6
{ Now White has to trade or retreat. } 15. Bxe6 fxe6
{ In my view, Black is on the more comfortable side of equality, with ideas of pressing White on the kingside with Qe8-g6, Nh5, Rf7, Raf8, Bb6 etc. and in the centre with a timely d6-d5. }
