1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5 5. c3
{ A starting point of this chapter. This is considered a more accurate move than 5.0-0, because it prevents ...Nd4. However, it gives Black an attractive possibility of an immediate strike in the centre. }
5... d5
{ Of course 5...O-O and 5...d6 are viable alternatives, but the text is the most active and direct way of solving Black's opening problems. I offer a similar approach of aiming at ... d5 instead of ...d6 against the Giuoco Piano. }
6. Nxe5
{ This move has not been the most popular, as Black has no problems demonstrating full compensation for the pawn. }
6... O-O 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. d4 Bb6
{ 8...Bd6?!  allows  9.Nxc6  Qe8  10.e5!  when White can count on a slight edge. }
9. O-O Nxe4
{ Taking with the pawn has been more popular, but the text looks healthier, as Black retains more compact structure and avoids the Bg5 pin. }
10. Nxc6
{ The only real way to challenge Black is to accept the pawn sacrifice. } 10...
Qd6 11. Ne5 { leads to a funny perpetual check: } 11... Ba6 12. Re1 Qxe5
{ This is the best but if you don't want to make a quick draw as Black you can go  12...c5  with playable position. }
13. dxe5 Nxf2 14. Qxd5 Nh3+ 15. Kh1 Nf2+ *

