1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5 5. c3
{ A starting point of this chapter. This is considered a more accurate move than 5.0-0, because it prevents ...Nd4. However, it gives Black an attractive possibility of an immediate strike in the centre. }
5... d5
{ Of course 5...O-O and 5...d6 are viable alternatives, but the text is the most active and direct way of solving Black's opening problems. I offer a similar approach of aiming at ... d5 instead of ...d6 against the Giuoco Piano. }
6. Nbd2 dxe4
{ Black could do without this move for a while, but that would only give White an additional possibility of exd5, Bc4, b3, Ne4 etc. }
7. dxe4 O-O 8. O-O Qe7 9. Qe2 a5
{ It's not like we were particularly afraid of b4 but if White didn't play let's just stop it and improve our position on the queenside. }
10. a4 Nb8
{ The key maneuver to remember. It originates from correspondence chess and was used over the board by Grischuk against Navara and Ivanchuk in 2017. Black achieves comfortable play by rerouting the knight to the more desirable d7 square. }
11. Bd3
{ Now Black has two perfectly viable alternatives to choose from,  11...h6  and  11...Rd8 }
11... Rd8 12. Nc4 Nbd7 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 g5
{ This is probably slightly more precise than Grischuk's  14...b6  played in his blitz game against Ivanchuk. }
