[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Ruy Lopez: Anti-Berlin - 4.d3 with 5.c3"]
[Black "Anti-Berlin 4.d3 & 5.c3 & 6.exd5 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5 5. c3
{ A starting point of this chapter. This is considered a more accurate move than 5.0-0, because it prevents ...Nd4. However, it gives Black an attractive possibility of an immediate strike in the centre. }
5... d5
{ Of course 5...O-O and 5...d6 are viable alternatives, but the text is the most active and direct way of solving Black's opening problems. I offer a similar approach of aiming at ... d5 instead of ...d6 against the Giuoco Piano. }
6. exd5 Qxd5 7. Bc4 { A must, as Bxf2 was threatened. } 7... Qd8
{ 7...Qd6 has been played almost exclusively, but I find the text move much more practical, as Black does not have to worry about all the potential attacks against the queen @@StartBracket@@Nbd2-e4/c4, b4, a4, Ba3 etc.@@EndBracket@@ and can continue with harmonious development. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Nbd2 a5 { Not allowing White to gain space on the queenside. }
10. Qe2 Bd6 11. Ne4
{ There is not much to remember after  11.a4  h6  and you can see how such game can proceed in Wang-Jakovenko. }
11... h6 12. Nfd2
{ A critical maneuver, intending to place another knight on e4 and create threats on the kingside. However, Black has an excellent response at his disposal. }
12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Re8
{ A deliberate provocation. In case White does nothing drastic, Black will be obviously fine after ...Be6. But more ambitious play is going to backfire for White. }
14. Qh5 Be6 15. Bxh6 { White falls for the trap. } 15... gxh6 16. Qxh6 Bxc4 17.
Nf6+ { White wins a queen but loses too much material in the process. } 17...
Qxf6 18. Qxf6 Bxd3 19. Qg5+ Bg6 20. Rad1 Kg7
{ This position was reached in 4 computer games. All of them were won by Black. Black's minor pieces are well coordinated and White struggles to create any play. }
*

