[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5 5. Bxc6
{ A starting point of this chapter. This move, which is highly popular on the high level, is hardly an attempt to gain an opening advantage. Instead, White wants to avoid more forcing lines, which often lead to quick simplification and play a slow, positional game. }
5... dxc6 6. b3
{ A good example of play against this rare move was demonstrated by Kramnik: }
6... Bg4 7. h3 { Black has an amusing idea: } 7... Qd4 8. Nxd4 Bxd1 9. Nf5
{ Otherwise, after 9.c3 Black would retreat the bishop and be happy with the bishop pair advantage. }
9... Bxc2 10. Nxg7+ Kd7
{ The best square. White has no way to disturb Black's King here. } 11. Bg5 Ne8
12. Nxe8 Kxe8 13. Ke2 Bxb1 { The bishop has to be exchanged sooner or later. }
14. Raxb1 Rg8 15. Bh4 h5
{ Black has the worse structure, but White's bishop is shut out of play. } *

