[White "8. Ruy Lopez: Anti-Berlin - 4.d3 with 5.Bxc6"]
[Black "Anti-Berlin 4.d3 & 5.Bxc6 & 6.h3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5 5. Bxc6
{ A starting point of this chapter. This move, which is highly popular on the high level, is hardly an attempt to gain an opening advantage. Instead, White wants to avoid more forcing lines, which often lead to quick simplification and play a slow, positional game. }
5... dxc6 6. h3 Nd7
{ The Knight temporarily blocks the bishop but we will maneuver it to e6 or g6. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2 Re8 9. Nc4 b5
{ This idea has not been tried too often by Black players, but I find it attractive. Black permanently deprives white knights of the c4 square and prepares further pawn expansion on the queenside. }
10. Ne3 Nb6 11. Bd2 a5
{ Black wants to slowly put his queenside pawn mass into motion, ideally achieving the c5-c4 break and getting rid of the doubled pawns. On the kingside, the standard ...Bf8, ... f6, ...g6, ...Bg7, ...Be6 is an effective setup, but refraining from f6 in order not to allow Nh4 and keep the ...Qf6 option is also a good idea. }
*

