[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5 5. Bxc6
{ A starting point of this chapter. This move, which is highly popular on the high level, is hardly an attempt to gain an opening advantage. Instead, White wants to avoid more forcing lines, which often lead to quick simplification and play a slow, positional game. }
5... dxc6 6. Nbd2
{ This is not merely a different move order than 6.0-0 or 6.h3. By not committing himself on the kingside, White keeps an option of building an aggressive setup with Nc4, Qe2, h4-h5, Bd2 and 0-0-0 after the usual ...Nd7 and ...0-0. Of course, Black has his ways to counter this idea, but he has to react in a very nuanced way and be constantly careful about White's threats on the kingside. This is why I recommend a different, much simpler and safer approach for Black here. }
6... Be6 { @@StartBracket@@Stopping Nc4 but 6...Nd7 is also OK.@@EndBracket@@ }
7. Qe2 { The play is very similar to 7.0-0. } 7... Nd7 8. Nb3 Bb6 9. Ng5
{ White has to go after the bishop if he wants to pose Black any problems. }
9... Bxb3
{ Of course  9...Nf8  is totally fine @@StartBracket@@even played by Magnus!@@EndBracket@@ but we are not afraid of opening the a-file despite the fact we often consider queenside castle. Actually White's structure with doubled pawns is less mobile. }
10. axb3 f6 11. Nf3 Qe7
{ A new move. We just prepare a long castle but of course  11...Nc5  or  11...Nf8  with ...Ne6 played by many grandmasters is totally fine. }
12. Nd2 a6
{ We are not only securing our bishop but note that there is hardly a way for White to open anything on the queenside @@StartBracket@@b4-b5 will never happen@@EndBracket@@. Here are a few more sample moves: }
13. Nc4 Ba7 14. O-O O-O-O *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Ruy Lopez: Anti-Berlin - 4.d3 with 5.Bxc6"]
[Black "Anti-Berlin 4.d3 & 5.Bxc6 & 6.Nbd2 #04"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5 5. Bxc6
{ A starting point of this chapter. This move, which is highly popular on the high level, is hardly an attempt to gain an opening advantage. Instead, White wants to avoid more forcing lines, which often lead to quick simplification and play a slow, positional game. }
5... dxc6 6. Nbd2
{ This is not merely a different move order than 6.0-0 or 6.h3. By not committing himself on the kingside, White keeps an option of building an aggressive setup with Nc4, Qe2, h4-h5, Bd2 and 0-0-0 after the usual ...Nd7 and ...0-0. Of course, Black has his ways to counter this idea, but he has to react in a very nuanced way and be constantly careful about White's threats on the kingside. This is why I recommend a different, much simpler and safer approach for Black here. }
6... Be6 { @@StartBracket@@Stopping Nc4 but 6...Nd7 is also OK.@@EndBracket@@ }
7. O-O { The most popular move. } 7... Nd7 8. Nb3 Bb6 9. Ng5
{ White has to go after the bishop if he wants to pose Black any problems. }
9... Bxb3
{ We are not afraid of opening the a-file despite the fact we often consider queenside castle. Actually White's structure with doubled pawns is less mobile.   Here  9...Nf8  is not a mistake but might be a little bit inaccurate as White has a tiny little something after  10.Qh5  . }
10. axb3 f6 11. Nf3 Qe7
{ We just prepare a long castle but of course  11...Nc5  or  11...Nf8  with ...Ne6 played by many grandmasters is totally fine. }
12. Nd2 a6
{ We are not only securing our bishop but note that there is hardly a way for White to open anything on the queenside @@StartBracket@@b4-b5 will never happen@@EndBracket@@. }
13. Nc4 Ba7 14. Qh5+
{ A disruptive move, provoking a weakening in order to stop Black from castling short. However, the long castle is more promising anyway. }
14... g6 15. Qe2 O-O-O
{ Black's king feels very well on the queenside, where it cannot be easily attacked. The most natural continuation is: }
16. Be3 Bxe3 17. Qxe3 Kb8 18. f4 exf4 19. Rxf4 Rhf8 { with equal play. } *

