[White "8. Ruy Lopez: Anti-Berlin - 4.d3 with 5.Bxc6"]
[Black "Anti-Berlin 4.d3 & 5.Bxc6 & 6.0-0 #02"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to the futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5 5. Bxc6
{ A starting point of this chapter. This move, which is highly popular on the high level, is hardly an attempt to gain an opening advantage. Instead, White wants to avoid more forcing lines, which often lead to quick simplification and play a slow, positional game. }
5... dxc6 6. O-O Nd7 7. c3
{ This is Joshua Doknjas' recommendation from 'The Ruy Lopez,' which has been favoured by a couple of high-class players. White builds a solid centre with d4 and places his pieces in a straightforward fashion. }
7... O-O 8. d4 Bd6 9. Bg5
{ To cause some disruption in Black's camp and then place the bishop on g3 is White's main idea. }
9... f6 10. Bh4 a5
{ A very effective way of fighting for space. Black's pieces may seem passive, but they are ready to spring into action at the right moment. }
11. a4 exd4 12. cxd4 Nb6
{ White has the pawn centre, but Black enjoys harmonious piece play. His bishops are especially strong. The a5-a4 inclusion is clearly in Black's favour, because the a4-pawn can become the target of an attack, and the b3 and b3 squares are weakened. }
*

