1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ The so-called anti-Berlin, which was long considered completely harmless but has been gaining more and more popularity in recent years due to futility of White's attempts in the Berlin Endgame. }
4... Bc5 5. Bxc6
{ A starting point of this chapter. This move, which is highly popular on the high level, is hardly an attempt to gain an opening advantage. Instead, White wants to avoid more forcing lines, which often lead to quick simplification and play a slow, positional game. }
5... dxc6 6. O-O Nd7
{ The Knight temporarily blocks the bishop but we will maneuver it to e6 or g6. }
7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Nc4 Re8 9. Be3 Bd6
{ Many other moves are possible, but this is the most straightforward one. Black's idea is to play ... Nf8-g6, stopping White's typical ideas on the kingside: Nh4-f5 and f4-f5. White has failed to demonstrate any downsides to this idea in practical play. }
10. h3 Nf8 11. d4 { does not change much compared to 10.d4 } 11... exd4 12.
Qxd4 c5 13. Qd3 b6
{ The arising d6 weakness will be offset by the e4 weakness. A sample line goes: }
14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Qxd6 cxd6 16. Rfd1 Bb7 17. Rxd6 Bxe4 18. Ne1 Rad8
{ The game was completely equal in Anand-Carlsen, Zurich 2014. } *

