[White "9. Scotch Game - Intro & 8.g3"]
[Black "Scotch Game 6.Qe2 #02"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Game had always remained in the shadow of the Ruy Lopez and the Italian Game, until Garry Kasparov started playing it successfully in the 1990s. Since then, many players have decided to follow the world champion's example and nowadays it is a popular opening on both professional and amateur level. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 { The main and most reliable move. } 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. Qe2
{ This idea had remained practically unknown, until Andreikin used it to defeat Kramnik in 2015 Candidates Tournament. Many players tried it in 2015 and 2016, but Black quickly found many good ways to counter it. Nowadays it is basically deemed unpromising for White. }
6... Bc5
{ If you want to try to force a draw you can play  6...d5  - see the alternative line }
7. e5
{ Practically forced, otherwise Black just castles and what is the queen doing on e2? }
7... Nd5 8. c4 Nb6 9. Qg4
{ The point of White's play. The g7 is hanging and Black is forced to weaken himself. However, Black is well developed so it shouldn't be a problem. }
9... g6 10. Bg5 Be7
{ Now White has two moves,  10.h4  and  10.Bh6  but in both cases Black responds in the same way. }
11. Bh6 d5 12. Qf3 Bg5 { We are exchanging the only White's active piece. } 13.
Bg7 Rg8 14. Bf6 Bxf6 15. exf6 Bf5
{ Of course we don't take on c4, we don't want to open the game too much with our king in the middle. Our position is a bit ruined but we will not only get a pawn on f6 but there is also a good development so it's hard for White to make use of our weaknesses. }
