1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Game had always remained in the shadow of the Ruy Lopez and the Italian Game, until Garry Kasparov started playing it successfully in the 1990s. Since then, many players have decided to follow the world champion's example and nowadays it is a popular opening on both professional and amateur level. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 { The main and most reliable move. } 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. Bd3
d5 7. e5 { This active move is just bad. } 7... Ng4 8. O-O Bc5 9. Bf4
{ 9.Qe2  Qe7  10.Bf4  g5  is similar. Black should win a pawn. } 9... g5
{ A powerful blow. White won't be able to consolidate. } 10. Bg3
{ This already loses, but after  10.Bd2  O-O  11.Nc3  Nxe5  with  ...Nxd3  next Black was just pawn up for no compensation in Vachier-Lagrave - Anand, Paris @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2018. }
10... h5 11. Be2 h4 12. Bxg4 hxg3 13. hxg3 Ke7
{ Not the only move but the best one. Black is winning with ...Qg8-h7. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Scotch Game - Intro & 8.g3"]
[Black "Scotch Game 6.Bd3 #02"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Game had always remained in the shadow of the Ruy Lopez and the Italian Game, until Garry Kasparov started playing it successfully in the 1990s. Since then, many players have decided to follow the world champion's example and nowadays it is a popular opening on both professional and amateur level. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 { The main and most reliable move. } 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. Bd3
d5 7. Qe2 dxe4 8. Nc3
{ White hopes to exploit the better structure but he concedes Black too much of a free development.  8.Bxe4  Nxe4  9.Qxe4+  Qe7  leaves Black with a bishop pair. }
8... Bb4 9. Bxe4 O-O 10. Bxc6
{ White grabs a pawn but it's clear Black has a nice compensation. } 10... Rb8
11. O-O Qd6 12. Bb5 { 12.Bf3  Ba6  wins the exchange and the game. } 12... Ng4
{ We need to create threats before White consolidates. } 13. g3 Bxc3 14. bxc3
Ne5
{ There are certain weaknesses in White's camp and now the line is pretty much forced. }
15. Bf4 Rxb5 16. Qxb5 Nf3+ 17. Kg2 Qe6 { Threatning ... Qe4 } 18. Rfd1
{ White prepares Qd5.   If  18.Kxf3  Bd7  19.Qe5  Qc6+  20.Ke3  Re8  Black has a huge advantage. }
18... c6
{ A key move. I know the line is extremely long but it's really all forced and of course you can always pause it if it's too much for you. }
19. Qa4 Nh4+ 20. gxh4 Qg4+ 21. Kf1 Qf3 22. Rd3 { Again, the only move. } 22...
Qh1+ 23. Ke2 Qxa1 24. Qa5 Qh1 { Black certainly keeps pressing. } *

