[White "9. Scotch Game - Intro & 8.g3"]
[Black "Scotch Game 6.e5 & 8.g3 #06"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Game had always remained in the shadow of the Ruy Lopez and the Italian Game, until Garry Kasparov started playing it successfully in the 1990s. Since then, many players have decided to follow the world champion's example and nowadays it is a popular opening on both professional and amateur level. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 { The main and most reliable move. } 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5
Qe7 { Black blocks his bishop, but forces White to do the same. } 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
g3 { An old move which is considered to be dodgy nowadays. } 8... g6
{ A typical way to develop the bishop. } 9. c4 Ba6
{ Usually after 9.c4 Black has two options ...Ba6 and ... Nb6. Usually both moves are fine but in this repertoire we favour ...Nb6 move. This is the only exception as we have a chance to put enormous pressure with a rapid development @@StartBracket@@...Bg7, ...0-0-0, ... Rhe8@@EndBracket@@. }
10. b3
{ The play transposes to the old main line of the 8...Ba6 variation, which has been established as very satisfactory for Black. }
10... Bg7 11. Bb2 O-O-O
{ Putting the king on the queenside is a slight improvement over the more common  11...O-O  , because the king will be more needed on the queenside in the endgame that follows. }
12. Bg2 Rhe8 13. O-O Bxe5
{ Entering the forced sequence where White will get two pieces for a rook and a pawn but as we will see things are fine for Black. }
14. Qxe5 Qxe5 15. Bxe5 Rxe5 16. cxd5 Bxf1 17. Kxf1 cxd5 18. Nc3 c6 19. Rc1 Kb8
{ @@StartBracket@@More accurate than 19...Kb7, which runs into 20.b4.@@EndBracket@@ }
20. b4 Rde8
{ @@StartBracket@@20... a5 immediately is less accurate due to 21.bxa5 d4 22.Ne2 d3 23. Nf4 and Black doesn't have the ...d2 and ...Re1+ resource.@@EndBracket@@ }
21. Bf3 a5
{ @@StartBracket@@The point of putting the king on b8 is that now White doesn't have 22.b5 because of 22...d4 and there is no 23.bxc6+.@@EndBracket@@ While entire idea behind playing ...a5 is to exchange pawns so that White is left with a weak pawn on the queenside. }
22. a3 axb4 23. axb4 Rc8
{ A smart computer move, intending to activate the rook via the 7th rank, without declaring the position of the king yet. }
24. Na4
{ The most natural reply. Otherwise Black would follow with ...Rc7-a7 or b7. }
24... Kc7
{ Black takes the opportunity to centralize his king. He is ready to attack the b4 pawn in the near future, which should force White to to exchange it with b5-bxc6. Then Black's two connected passed pawns will give him serious winning chances. }
