1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Game had always remained in the shadow of the Ruy Lopez and the Italian Game, until Garry Kasparov started playing it successfully in the 1990s. Since then, many players have decided to follow the world champion's example and nowadays it is a popular opening on both professional and amateur level. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ Black blocks his bishop, but forces White to do the same. } 7. Qe2 Nd5
{ Here absolutely the main move is 8.c4 but in this chapter we will have a look at 8. h4 and 8.Nd2. While 8.g3 was already covered in the previous one. }
8. Nd2 g6 9. c4
{ The most popular move but White is objectively worse here although the lines are a bit complicated. }
9... Nf4
{ Once the f4 square is available, Black should use it! We are fighting for more than equality.    Milos Pavlovic in his book 'The Modernized Scotch Game' @@StartBracket@@Thinkers Publishing 2019@@EndBracket@@ considers only  9...Ba6  when  10.Nf3  Qb4  11.Kd1  is another story and probably less good for us. }
10. Qe3 Bh6
{ It looks as if something has gone wrong for White, but he has a cunning idea in mind. By the way, the less complicated option is  10...Ne6  , with a good position, if you don't want to memorize too much lines. }
11. Kd1 { Stepping out of ...Nxg2+ } 11... O-O
{ Going for it! Now White can win some material and the game is really becoming wild. If you want to be a strong player you shouldn't be afraid to play principled moves if you can get the advantage. Still, you can have a look at  11...d5  provided in this chapter as an alternative. }
12. g3 Nh3 { There was no way back. } 13. Qxh6 Nxf2+ 14. Ke1 Nxh1 15. Qe3 f6
{ Better than  15...d6  , because Black captures towards the centre, opens the f-file for the rook, and the c6-pawn is not hanging. }
16. Bg2 Nxg3 17. hxg3 fxe5
{ Black has a rook and two pawns for two minor pieces and in addition White's king is not very safe, which gives Black a slight plus. }
