[White "11. Scotch Game - 8.c4 Nb6 9.Nd2 and 9.b3"]
[Black "Scotch Game 9.Nd2 & 10.b3 #06"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Game had always remained in the shadow of the Ruy Lopez and the Italian Game, until Garry Kasparov started playing it successfully in the 1990s. Since then, many players have decided to follow the world champion's example and nowadays it is a popular opening on both professional and amateur level. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ Black blocks his bishop, but forces White to do the same. } 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4
{ Absolutely the main move but we covered all the alternatives in the previous chapters. }
8... Nb6
{ 8...Ba6 is the main line, but I recommend to play the text move, because it is at least as good and requires less memorization. Now the most popular is 9. Nc3 which will be covered in the next chapter. Here we will focus on 9. Nd2 and have a brief look at 9.b3. }
9. Nd2 Qe6 { Black prepares ...Bb4 and ... Ba6. } 10. b3
{ White strengthens the c4 pawn and prepares to meet ...Bb4 with Bb2. } 10...
a5
{ The key idea of the variation. The a-pawn march essentially solves all Black's problems. }
11. Bb2 { 11.Qe3 a4 12.Bb2 Bb4 transposes to our main line. } 11... a4
{ 11...Bb4 is dubious because 12.a3 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 is just better for White who got a bishop pair for nothing. Somehow Black can't easily break through. This was played in the 16th game of the World Championship match Kasparov-Karpov in 1990. Kasparov went on to win that game and later the match by one point. }
12. Qe3 { White just wants to develop the bishop and castle. } 12... Bb4 13.
Be2
{ This is what Kasparov admitted he was planning to play, although he never got a chance. Still, modern engines neutralize this line easily. }
13... d6 14. O-O
{ The only ambitious choice, since 14.exd6 is obviously harmless. } 14... dxe5
{ We just win a pawn as White can't recapture because the knight on d2 hangs. }
15. Ne4 O-O
{ 15...Nd7  is also possible, but more passive. I prefer to retain activity than to preserve the bishop pair at all costs. }
16. Nc5 Bxc5 17. Qxc5 Nd7 18. Qe3 f5
{ Black plans to develop with ...c5 and ...Bb7. Possible f4 can be always met by ...e4, creating a protected passed pawn. White has full compensation for the pawn, but not more. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Scotch Game - 8.c4 Nb6 9.Nd2 and 9.b3"]
[Black "Scotch Game 9.Nd2 & 10.b3 #07"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Game had always remained in the shadow of the Ruy Lopez and the Italian Game, until Garry Kasparov started playing it successfully in the 1990s. Since then, many players have decided to follow the world champion's example and nowadays it is a popular opening on both professional and amateur level. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ Black blocks his bishop, but forces White to do the same. } 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4
{ Absolutely the main move but we covered all the alternatives in the previous chapters. }
8... Nb6
{ 8...Ba6 is the main line, but I recommend to play the text move, because it is at least as good and requires less memorization. Now the most popular is 9. Nc3 which will be covered in the next chapter. Here we will focus on 9. Nd2 and have a brief look at 9.b3. }
9. Nd2 Qe6 { Black prepares ...Bb4 and ... Ba6. } 10. b3
{ White strengthens the c4 pawn and prepares to meet ...Bb4 with Bb2. } 10...
a5
{ The key idea of the variation. The a-pawn march essentially solves all Black's problems. }
11. Bb2 { 11.Qe3 a4 12.Bb2 Bb4 transposes to our main line. } 11... a4
{ 11...Bb4 is dubious because 12.a3 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 is just better for White who got a bishop pair for nothing. Somehow Black can't easily break through. This was played in the 16th game of the World Championship match Kasparov-Karpov in 1990. Kasparov went on to win that game and later the match by one point. }
12. g3
{ The bishop looks nice on the long diagonal, but at the same time the defence of the c4 pawn is weakened. }
12... Bb4
{ There is no reason to hurry with exchanging on b3-sometimes the ...a3 resource can prove useful. }
13. Bg2 O-O 14. O-O d5
{ As we see in 12.Qe3 line where White develops the bishop more modestly we undermine e5 pawn. Here the c4 pawn is a potential target. }
15. Nf3
{ This has been White's most popular choice in the position, but it allows Black to take over the initiative. }
15... a3 { It turns out that the white bishop lacks good retreat squares. } 16.
Bc1 dxc4
{ We just destroy the queenside while the complications are favourable for us. }
17. Nd4 Qg4
{ The crucial move. In the endgame the a3-pawn will prove to be a very strong asset. }
18. Qxg4 Bxg4 19. Nxc6 Bc3 20. Rb1 Be6
{ Black supports his strong 'c' and 'a' pawns instead of immediately cashing in with 20...Be2. }
21. b4 Rfe8
{ With ...Bf5 or ... Bd5 coming, Black is obviously better. There is no way for White to use the apparent weakness of the a8-rook.   Don't forget that  21...Rae8  would drop the pawn  22.Bxa3 }
*

