{ Black blocks his bishop, but forces White to do the same. } 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4
{ Absolutely the main move but we covered all the alternatives in the previous chapters. }
8... Nb6
{ 8...Ba6 is the main line, but I recommend to play the text move, because it is at least as good and requires less memorization. Now the most popular is 9. Nc3 which will be covered in the next chapter. Here we will focus on 9. Nd2 and have a brief look at 9.b3. }
9. Nd2 Qe6 { Black prepares ...Bb4 and ... Ba6. } 10. b3
{ White strengthens the c4 pawn and prepares to meet ...Bb4 with Bb2. } 10...
a5
{ The key idea of the variation. The a-pawn march essentially solves all Black's problems. }
11. Bb2 { 11.Qe3 a4 12.Bb2 Bb4 transposes to our main line. } 11... a4
{ 11...Bb4 is dubious because 12.a3 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 is just better for White who got a bishop pair for nothing. Somehow Black can't easily break through. This was played in the 16th game of the World Championship match Kasparov-Karpov in 1990. Kasparov went on to win that game and later the match by one point. }
12. g3
{ The bishop looks nice on the long diagonal, but at the same time the defence of the c4 pawn is weakened. }
12... Bb4
{ There is no reason to hurry with exchanging on b3-sometimes the .. .a3 resource can prove useful. }
13. Bg2 O-O 14. O-O d5
{ As we see in 12.Qe3 line where White develops the bishop more modestly we undermine e5 pawn. Here the c4 pawn is a potential target. }
15. Nf3
{ This has been White's most popular choice in the position, but it allows Black to take over the initiative. }
15... a3 { It turns out that the white bishop lacks good retreat squares. } 16.
Bd4 c5
{ Going for it! This is much more ambitious than  16...Ba6  which allows  17.Bxb6  cxb6  18.Nd4 }
17. Be3
{ This is too slow. White doesn't take the opportunity to drag Black's queen to the long diagonal. }
17... Ba6 18. Qc2
{ This position was reached in Nielsen-Dautov, 1991. Now Black was too hasty with  18...dxc4  He should defend against Ng5 first. }
18... h6 19. cxd5
{ In case of  19.Nd2  Rad8  White is in even more serious trouble. } 19... Nxd5
20. Bxc5 Bxf1 21. Nd4 Qxe5 22. Rxf1 Ne3
{ An elegant way to clarify the position. Without this trick we wouldn't get any advantage. }
23. fxe3 Bxc5 24. Bxa8 Qxe3+ 25. Kh1 Qxd4
{ Black is a healthy pawn up with good winning chances. } *

