15. Nf3
{ This has been White's most popular choice in the position, but it allows Black to take over the initiative. }
15... a3 { It turns out that the white bishop lacks good retreat squares. } 16.
Bd4 c5
{ @@StartBracket@@Going for it! This is much more ambitious than 16...Ba6 which allows 17.Bxb6 cxb6 18.Nd4. @@EndBracket@@ }
17. cxd5 Qxd5
{ The key moment. White has a few options, but neither of them fully solves his problems.   It's important to see we couldn't play  17...Nxd5  due to  18.Ng5 }
18. Be3 Ba6 { this doesn't win the game, but gives Black the better chances. }
19. Qc2 Bxf1 20. Rxf1 Rad8 21. Ng5
{ If not for this move, White would be simply lost. } 21... Qd3 22. Qxd3 Rxd3
23. Be4 Rd7
{ The most precise. You are not worse after other moves but we are playing for the advantage. }
24. Bxh7+ Kh8
{ White doesn't have full compensation for the exchange.  25.Bf5  with tempo is not dangerous in view of  25...Re7  In general, Black plans ...c4 to activate the knight. The a3 pawn is an important long-term trump. }
