{ The key moment. White has a few options, but neither of them fully solves his problems. @@StartBracket@@It's important to see we couldn't play 17... Nxd5 due to 18.Ng5.@@EndBracket@@ }
18. Rfd1 { The poorest choice. } 18... Ba6
{ Of course  18...cxd4  fails due to  19.Nxd4  Qc5  20.Rac1  and White will mop up a lot of material. }
19. Qe3 Rad8 { The d4-bishop is lethally pinned. } 20. e6 fxe6
{ The bishop will not go away. It would be bad to take it immediately  20...cxd4  due to  21.Rxd4  Qc5  22.Rxb4!  Qxb4  23.e7  with equality. }
21. Ng5 cxd4 { Now it's all forced. } 22. Bxd5 dxe3 23. Bxe6+ Kh8 24. Nf7+ Rxf7
25. Rxd8+ Rf8 26. Rxf8+ Bxf8 27. fxe3
{ The endgame is probably simply won for Black, because the a3 pawn is a huge asset. }
