{ @@StartBracket@@Going for it! This is much more ambitious than 16...Ba6 which allows 17.Bxb6 cxb6 18.Nd4. @@EndBracket@@ }
17. cxd5 Qxd5
{ The key moment. White has a few options, but neither of them fully solves his problems. @@StartBracket@@It's important to see we couldn't play 17... Nxd5 due to 18.Ng5.@@EndBracket@@ }
18. Qe3 { The most stubborn move. } 18... cxd4
{ Compared to 18.Rfd1, now Black can take the bishop. } 19. Nxd4 Qd7 20. Bc6
{ Played in order to later put the knight on c6. } 20... Qh3
{ An important move. Now once White takes on a8 his light squares will be seriously weakened. }
21. Bxa8 { 21.Bg2  Qh6  enters the better endgame. } 21... Nxa8 22. Nc6 Bb7
{ Without this our bishop on b4 would be gone. } 23. Rac1 Re8
{ Note that the natural  23...Nb6  would be a mistake due to  24.Qd4!  Even though the knight is temporarily shut out of play on  a8  , the two pieces are still stronger than the rook. Black's long term plan is to try and win the a2-pawn, when the  a3  passer should decide the game. }
