{ The bishop looks nice on the long diagonal, but at the same time the defence of the c4 pawn is weakened. }
12... Bb4
{ There is no reason to hurry with exchanging on b3-sometimes the .. .a3 resource can prove useful. }
13. Bg2 O-O 14. O-O d5
{ As we see in 12.Qe3 line where White develops the bishop more modestly we undermine e5 pawn. Here the c4 pawn is a potential target. }
15. Rfc1
{ The best move at White's disposal, preparing to meet ...a3 with Bc3. } 15...
Qg4
{ My novelty. Other moves like  15...axb3  and  15...Ba6  are fine, but I find this move even more attractive, as it disrupts the coordination of White's pieces. }
16. f3 { This move blocks both White's bishop and knight. } 16... Bc5+
{ It looks counterintuitive to put the bishop in front of White's rook. The reason for this check becomes clear in the 18.cxd5 line. }
17. Kh1 Qh5
{ Black is completely fine based on two tactical points. The first one is obvious. The other one is quite spectacular: }
18. cxd5 { Is our position falling apart? } 18... a3
{ Thanks to 16...Bc5+ there is no 19.Bd4 now. } 19. Bc3 Nxd5 20. Qc4 Ba7 21.
Qxc6 Be6
{ With much better placed pieces, Black has more than enough compensation for the pawn. }
*

