1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Game had always remained in the shadow of the Ruy Lopez and the Italian Game, until Garry Kasparov started playing it successfully in the 1990s. Since then, many players have decided to follow the world champion's example and nowadays it is a popular opening on both professional and amateur level. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ Black blocks his bishop, but forces White to do the same. } 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4
{ Absolutely the main move but we covered all the alternatives in the previous chapters. }
8... Nb6
{ 8...Ba6 is the main line, but I recommend to play the text move, because it is at least as good and requires less memorization. Now the most popular is 9. Nc3 which will be covered in the next chapter. Here we will focus on 9. Nd2 and have a brief look at 9.b3. }
9. Nd2 Qe6 { Black prepares ...Bb4 and ... Ba6. } 10. b3
{ White strengthens the c4 pawn and prepares to meet ...Bb4 with Bb2. } 10...
a5
{ The key idea of the variation. The a-pawn march essentially solves all Black's problems. }
11. Bb2 { 11.Qe3 a4 12.Bb2 Bb4 transposes to our main line. } 11... a4
{ 11...Bb4 is dubious because 12.a3 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 is just better for White who got a bishop pair for nothing. Somehow Black can't easily break through. This was played in the 16th game of the World Championship match Kasparov-Karpov in 1990. Kasparov went on to win that game and later the match by one point. }
