{ The best move at White's disposal, preparing to meet ...a3 with Bc3. } 15...
Qg4
{ @@StartBracket@@My novelty. Other moves like 15...axb3 and 15...Ba6 are fine, but I find this move even more attractive, as it disrupts the coordination of White's pieces.@@EndBracket@@ }
16. f3 { This move blocks both White's bishop and knight. } 16... Bc5+
{ It looks counterintuitive to put the bishop in front of White's rook. The reason for this check becomes clear in the 18.cxd5 line. }
17. Kh1 Qh5
{ Black is completely fine based on two tactical points. The first one is obvious. The other one is quite spectacular: }
18. e6 { This looks clever, and White could easily miss the refutation: } 18...
Bxe6 19. cxd5 Qxd5 20. f4 { It looks like White is winning, but... } 20... Rfe8
{ Black is better, the point being: } 21. Be5 Bd4 22. Bxd5 Bxd5+ 23. Nf3 axb3
{ White is so pinned that our bishop on d4 is untouchable. Now our pawn becomes extremely dangerous while we still keep an option to take on a1 or to play ...f6. }
24. axb3 Bxa1 { The monstrous bishop on d5 guarantees Black fantastic play. } *

