[White "12. Scotch Game - 8.c4 Nb6 9.Nc3"]
[Black "Scotch 9.Nc3 & 10.Bd2 #02"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Game had always remained in the shadow of the Ruy Lopez and the Italian Game, until Garry Kasparov started playing it successfully in the 1990s. Since then, many players have decided to follow the world champion's example and nowadays it is a popular opening on both professional and amateur level. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ Black blocks his bishop, but forces White to do the same. } 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4
Nb6
{ @@StartBracket@@8...Ba6 is the main line, but I recommend to play the text move, because it is at least as good and requires less memorization.@@EndBracket@@ }
9. Nc3
{ This is the most straightforward continuation and the starting point of this chapter @@StartBracket@@all the alternatives were covered in the previous chapters@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Qe6 10. Bd2 { Playing for a quick long castle. } 10... Ba6 11. b3 Ba3
{ Stopping the above-mentioned plan. } 12. f4 O-O 13. Qf3 d6
{ 13...f6  is also fine. } 14. Bd3 Rad8
{ 14...dxe5  gives White an attractive possibility of  15.f5! } 15. O-O dxe5
{ Only now we take the pawn since White has no time for  16.f5  due to  16...Qd6 }
16. Rad1 f5
{ Forcing 17.fxe5 and taking the important e4-square under control. } 17. fxe5
Qxe5
{ The position is around equal. We have an extra pawn but it's not so special. We should be aiming for improving our bishops with ...Bc8 and ...Bb4 or ...Bd6. Sample line goes: }
18. Ne2 Bd6 19. Bf4 Qc5+ 20. Kh1 Rde8
{ White is probably able to regain one of Black's weak pawns, but it shouldn't give him more than equality. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Scotch Game - 8.c4 Nb6 9.Nc3"]
[Black "Scotch 9.Nc3 & 10.Qe4 #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Game had always remained in the shadow of the Ruy Lopez and the Italian Game, until Garry Kasparov started playing it successfully in the 1990s. Since then, many players have decided to follow the world champion's example and nowadays it is a popular opening on both professional and amateur level. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ Black blocks his bishop, but forces White to do the same. } 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4
Nb6
{ @@StartBracket@@8...Ba6 is the main line, but I recommend to play the text move, because it is at least as good and requires less memorization.@@EndBracket@@ }
9. Nc3
{ This is the most straightforward continuation and the starting point of this chapter @@StartBracket@@all the alternatives were covered in the previous chapters@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Qe6 10. Qe4 { By far the most popular choice. } 10... d5
{ The most straightforward way to equalize. } 11. exd6 Qxe4+
{ It is important to exchange the queens immediately in order not to allow White to retake on  e4  with the bishop after  11...cxd6  12.Bd3   This accurate move wasn't considered in any books/DVDs known to us. Not only some older books like Vladimir Barsky - 'The Scotch Game for White'  (Chess Stars 2009)  or Yelena Dembo & Richard Palliser - 'The Scotch Game'  (Everymanchess 2011)  , but also Parimarjan Negi's Chessbase DVD - 'The Modern Scotch Opening' and John Shaw - 'Playing 1.e4. Caro-Kann, 1...e5 and Minor Lines'  (Quality Chess 2016)  cover only automatic but dubious 11...cxd6. }
12. Nxe4 cxd6
{ All White's attempts from this position fail to pose Black any problems. }
13. b3 d5
{ When b3 is on the board ... d5 followed by ... a5-a4 is usually good. } 14.
cxd5 Nxd5 15. Bc4 Bf5 16. Ng3 Bb4+
{ When we can develop with a tempo we should always consider it. } 17. Bd2
Bxd2+ 18. Kxd2 Be6
{ We have three pawn islands, but the strong d5 outpost compensates for them }
*

