{ Again forcing b3.   However I should mention that possible is  13...Be7  14.O-O-O  Bf5  15.f3  O-O  with equality but note that  14...O-O  would imprecise due to  15.Bb4  or  15.Bg5 }
14. b3 d5 15. cxd5 Bxd5 { 15...Nxd5  would be dubious in view of  16.Rc1 } 16.
Nc3 Be6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Scotch Game - 8.c4 Nb6 9.Nc3"]
[Black "Scotch 9.Nc3 & 10.Qe4 #04"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Game had always remained in the shadow of the Ruy Lopez and the Italian Game, until Garry Kasparov started playing it successfully in the 1990s. Since then, many players have decided to follow the world champion's example and nowadays it is a popular opening on both professional and amateur level. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ Black blocks his bishop, but forces White to do the same. } 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4
Nb6
{ @@StartBracket@@8...Ba6 is the main line, but I recommend to play the text move, because it is at least as good and requires less memorization.@@EndBracket@@ }
9. Nc3
{ This is the most straightforward continuation and the starting point of this chapter @@StartBracket@@all the alternatives were covered in the previous chapters@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Qe6 10. Qe4 { By far the most popular choice. } 10... d5
{ The most straightforward way to equalize. } 11. exd6 Qxe4+
{ It is important to exchange the queens immediately in order not to allow White to retake on  e4  with the bishop after  11...cxd6  12.Bd3   This accurate move wasn't considered on Parimarjan Negi's Chessbase DVD - 'The Modern Scotch Opening'. Also some older books like Vladimir Barsky - 'The Scotch Game for White' @@StartBracket@@Chess Stars 2009@@EndBracket@@ or Yelena Dembo & Richard Palliser - 'The Scotch Game' @@StartBracket@@Everymanchess 2011@@EndBracket@@ covers only automatic but dubious 11... cxd6. }
12. Nxe4 cxd6
{ All White's attempts from this position fail to pose Black any problems. }
13. Bf4 d5 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Nd6+
{ This looks logical, counting on 15...Bxd6. But Black has a strong response at his disposal.   After the polite  15.Bd2  Black can develop his pieces in many ways. A good example is:  15...Rb8  16.O-O-O  Be7  17.Bc4  h6  18.f3  Be6  19.Rhe1  O-O  20.Bb3  Rb6  21.Kb1  Rfb8  22.Re2  Ng6=  Maffei-Laube, ICCF 2010. }
15... Kd7
{ A strong pawn sacrifice. Of course,  15...Ke7  would be completely unattractive. }
16. Nxf7 Bb4+ 17. Bd2 Re8+ 18. Kd1 Rb8
{ Defending and attacking at the same time. } 19. b3 h6
{ Black has full compensation for the pawn based on better development and threats against White's lone knight. The critical line runs as follows: }
20. Bc4 Bxd2 21. Kxd2 Re7
{ It is important to note that  21...Ke6  is wrong because of  22.Ne5! } 22.
Nh8 Re6
{ Black has no problems and it is White who needs to find accurate moves to equalize. A sample line goes: }
23. f4 Rf6 24. f5 Kd6 25. g4 Bxf5 26. gxf5 Rxh8 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Scotch Four Knights Game - 4.d4"]
[Black "Scotch Four Knights 8.e5 #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4
{ The Scotch Variation of the Four Knights, which, as the name suggests, is often reached via the Scotch move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  . In recent years, it has gained in popularity as an alternative to  5.Nxc6  . }
5... Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Taking towards the centre. Our pawns are doubled but we will push ...d5 next. }
7. Bd3 d5 8. e5 { A dubious move, which quickly leads to overextension. } 8...
Ng4 9. Bf4 f6
{ Breaking open the overextended centre. White faces serious problems. } 10. h3
Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Qe7
{ 11...fxe5  12.Qh5  is less good but you should be happy with the opening anyway. With our move we have a  d8  square for the King and also we want to regain a piece without even giving a central pawn - Black is much better now, the most critical line is: }
12. Qh5+ Kd8 { Black will regain the piece with interest. } 13. f4 g6
{ The best, but Black is also better after other moves so you are not obliged to remember it. }
14. Bxg6 fxe5 15. O-O
{ 15.fxe5  runs into  15...Qg7!  and once the Bishop moves we have  ...Qg3+  and everything will fall, especially  g2  and then our Rook and Bishop can quickly join the action as well. }
15... Rf8 16. Qxh7 exf4
{ The bishop pair is the most important factor of the position, giving Black a big advantage. }
*

