[Black "Scotch Four Knights 8.e5 #02"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4
{ The Scotch Variation of the Four Knights, which, as the name suggests, is often reached via the Scotch move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  . In recent years, it has gained in popularity as an alternative to  5.Nxc6  . }
5... Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Taking towards the centre. Our pawns are doubled but we will push ...d5 next. }
7. Bd3 d5 8. e5 { A dubious move, which quickly leads to overextension. } 8...
Ng4 9. Bf4 f6
{ Breaking open the overextended centre. White faces serious problems. } 10. e6
Bxe6 11. h3 Ne5 12. Bxe5 fxe5 13. Qh5+ Bf7
{ Also  13...Kf8  14.Qxe5  Qd6  is great. } 14. Qxe5+ Qe7
{ Black's advantage is self-evident. Nice bishops, better central control, more space and White's pieces are restricted. Also after queen's exchange  (which is White's best now)  our king finds a shelter on d7 or d6 and the rooks quickly come to play. }
