[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Scotch Four Knights Game - 4.d4"]
[Black "Scotch Four Knights 10.Ne2 #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4
{ The Scotch Variation of the Four Knights, which, as the name suggests, is often reached via the Scotch move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  . In recent years, it has gained in popularity as an alternative to  5.Nxc6  . }
5... Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Taking towards the centre. Our pawns are doubled but we will push ...d5 next. }
7. Bd3 d5 8. exd5 { By far the most popular. } 8... O-O
{ Black usually plays 8...cxd5 which is not bad but we have another idea in mind. }
9. O-O Bg4
{ A fresh idea, which occured in high-level practice in 2018. It allows Black to equalize in a dynamic way, without need of delving into the intricacies of various move orders after the automatic  9...cxd5 }
10. Ne2
{ This timid continuation is recommended by Christoph Sielecki in his popular 'Keep It Simple 1.e4' repertoire. }
10... cxd5 11. h3 Bh5 12. c4
{ A typical move to leave Black with an isolated pawn. } 12... dxc4 13. Bxc4
Bd6 14. Re1
{ This is the end of Sielecki's line, but a very important possibility has to be mentioned here: }
14... Re8 15. Be3 Rxe3 { Not the only move but the nice one. } 16. fxe3 Qe7
{ Black should in fact soon regain the exchange. } 17. Qd2
{ 17.Qd4  Rd8  18.Nf4  Bc5  19.Qc3  Bb4  is a clean equalizer. } 17... Rd8
{ Threatening both ...Bh2+ and ...Bb4. } 18. Nd4 Bb4 19. Qf2 Bxe1 20. Rxe1 Qd6
{ Now White no longer has the structural edge and the position is just equal. }
*

