10. f3
{ This seems to be critical. It's so far the most popular and it's also a top engine's recommendation. It weakens the g1-a7 diagonal  (we will make a use of that)  but it's a tempo move. The play is very concrete. }
10... Bh5 11. g4 Bg6 12. Bxg6 hxg6 13. dxc6 Bxc3
{ Ruining White's pawns which would be easy to pick up. } 14. bxc3 Qe7
{ There are many possible moves for White now, but I believe it is not necessary to delve too deeply into further variations. Black's play is very straightforward in any case. With so many weak squares in his camp, it is White who should be more careful here. A possible line is: }
15. Qd4 Rfd8 16. Qc4 Rd5
{ Planning ...Rc5. The position is equal, but definitely easier for Black to play.   An important trick to notice is that  17.g5  doesn't win a piece due to  17...Qe6!  threatening  ...Rg5+  when Black is better. }
