9. O-O Bg4
{ A fresh idea, which occured in high-level practice in 2018. It allows Black to equalize in a dynamic way, without need of delving into the intricacies of various move orders after the automatic 9... cxd5. }
10. f3
{ This seems to be critical. It's so far the most popular and it's also a top engine's recommendation. It weakens the g1-a7 diagonal  (we will make a use of that)  but it's a tempo move. The play is very concrete. }
10... Bh5 11. Bg5 cxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Bxf6 Qc5+
{ Of course not  13...gxf6??  14.Bxh7+!  This is where we benefit from inducing the  f3  weakening. }
14. Kh1 gxf6 15. a3 { White wins his piece back } 15... a5
{ A novelty. Now once White takes we will improve our structure on the queenside with ...axb4. It may look like we have problems on the kingside but we will soon move our bishop to g6, making our configuration very solid.     If Black wanted he could take two pawns for a piece with  15...Ba5  16.b4  Bxb4  17.axb4  Qxb4  (as everybody played)  , however White will have enough activity to compensate for the missing pawn. }
