{ The Scotch Variation of the Four Knights, which, as the name suggests, is often reached via the Scotch move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  . In recent years, it has gained in popularity as an alternative to  5.Nxc6  . }
5... Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Taking towards the centre. Our pawns are doubled but we will push ...d5 next. }
7. Bd3 d5 8. exd5 { By far the most popular. } 8... O-O
{ Black usually plays 8...cxd5 which is not bad but we have another idea in mind. }
9. O-O Bg4
{ A fresh idea, which occured in high-level practice in 2018. It allows Black to equalize in a dynamic way, without need of delving into the intricacies of various move orders after the automatic 9... cxd5. }
10. f3
{ This seems to be critical. It's so far the most popular and it's also a top engine's recommendation. It weakens the g1-a7 diagonal  (we will make a use of that)  but it's a tempo move. The play is very concrete. }
10... Bh5 11. Bg5 cxd5 12. Bxf6
{ The only line that requires precision from Black. } 12... Qxf6 13. Nxd5 Qxb2
14. Rb1 Bc5+ { Again, thanks to inducing f3 we have a check. } 15. Kh1 Qe5
{ 15...Qxa2?  would be a serious mistake due to  16.Rb5!  Qa3  17.Qd2!  threatening  Ra5  17...c6  18.Ne7+  Bxe7  19.Rxh5  and Black has no way to defend the h-pawn  19...h6  20.Rxh6! }
16. f4
{ This leads to White taking a pawn. Otherwise Black, with his two bishops, could take over the initiative. }
16... Bxd1 17. fxe5 Bg4
{ Not  17...Bh5  because of  18.Rb5!  Bb6  19.e6!  and the bishop on  h5  is hanging. }
18. Rf4 { This was played in Nihal-Vidit, 2018. Now I suggest: } 18... Rab8 19.
Ra1 { Otherwise Black would play 19...Be6 and take on a2. } 19... Bc8 20. Rc4
Bb6
{ If  21.Nxc7  , then  21...Rd8  and White will not be able to keep the pawn for long. }
