1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4
{ The recent correspondence and over the board praxis has established this move to be very promising, yielding Black great results. As we will see, White can easily end up in trouble if he does not proceed cautiously. }
5. Bc4
{ In the next chapter we will deal with 5.Ba4 as well as 5.Nxd4 or 5.O-O. }
5... Bc5 6. Nxe5 Qe7 { The key move, not being afraid of any capture on f7. }
7. Nd3
{ White hopes to win time by attacking the bishop but Black has a dynamic response at his disposal. }
7... d5 { Blasting open the centre. Black gets incredibly quick development. }
8. Bxd5 { After extensive analysis it turns out to be unplayable for White. }
8... Bb6
{ Stepping out of Nxc5. I like this ambitious move. Black does not hurry to regain the material, recognising that he can play for more using White's clumsy piece placement. }
9. Bc4 O-O
{ The natural-looking  9...Nxe4  fails to  10.O-O  and 11.Re1.   9...Bg4  is always a move to consider but we will complete development first before playing this move. }
10. Nf4
{ This is the engine's suggestion at first but after some time it realizes White is busted here.     10.Bb3  is even worse and it's seen in the game Ebeling-Sepp  . }
10... Bg4 11. f3 Nh5
{ That's the key move we have already seen in 9. Nf4 variation. The difference is we castled instead of playing ...c6. }
12. fxg4 Nxf4 13. O-O Nf3+
{ Unlike in the 9.Nf4 variation where we have ...c6 instead of ...O-O played we don't have a rook on h8 so ...h5 doesn't make much sense but there is another way to break through. }
14. Kh1 Nxh2 15. g3 { White had to stop ...Qh4. } 15... Nxf1 16. Qxf1 Ng6
{ Black has an exchange for a pawn and look at White's position. } *

