{ It's important to note that compared to 8.Bxd5 as seen earlier we shouldn't play slow   8...Bb6  because after  9.O-O  we are missing the ...Bg4 resource as the knights are exchanged. }
10. Nxc5 { 10.c3  cxd5  11.Nxc5  Qxc5  12.cxd4  Qxd4  transposes. } 10... cxd5
11. c3 Qxc5 12. cxd4 Qxd4 13. exd5
{ 13.d3  dxe4  etc. leads to immediate liquidation. } 13... O-O
{ We will regain one pawn, but we will still be a pawn down. However we have a very nice grip on the light squares. If White doesn't want to play d3 and lose a pawn - how is he going to develop his bishop? Sample line goes: }
14. O-O Bg4 15. Qb3 Be2 16. Re1 Rae8 17. d3 Bf3 18. Bf4
{ At first it appears that after  18.Rxe8  Rxe8  19.gxf3  White has managed to win the bishop after all, but after  19...Re1+  20.Kg2  Re2  White has nothing better than to return the piece with  21.Be3  to prevent mate. }
18... Qxf4 19. gxf3 Qxf3
{ The game should end in a perpetual check now or a after a few moves.     20.Qxb7  Qg4+  etc. }
