1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4
{ The recent correspondence and over the board praxis has established this move to be very promising, yielding Black great results. As we will see, White can easily end up in trouble if he does not proceed cautiously. }
5. Bc4
{ In the next chapter we will deal with 5.Ba4 as well as 5.Nxd4 or 5.O-O. }
5... Bc5 6. Nxe5 Qe7 { The key move, not being afraid of any capture on f7. }
7. Nf3 { The most popular move. } 7... d5
{ Just like against 7.Nd3 this is a key resource. Black sacrifices even more material but gets enormous activity. }
8. Nxd5 Qxe4+ 9. Ne3 Bg4 { White is pinned everywhere. } 10. Be2 Nxe2 11. Qxe2
O-O-O
{ It is visible at the first glance that Black has great compensation for the pawn. }
12. d3 Qe6 13. Ng5 { This leads to a long forcing variation: } 13... Qc6
{ Playable is  13...Qd7  14.Nxg4  Nxg4  15.O-O  Rhe8  with sufficient compensation, but after the text it is White who needs to be more careful. }
14. Nxg4 Qxg2 15. Nxf6 Qxh1+ 16. Qf1 Qc6
{ 16...Qxf1+  is bad, because Black will end up a pawn down in the endgame, but  16...Qxh2  is possible. }
17. Qh3+ Kb8 18. Nfe4 Rhe8
{ Preparing ...f6 and ...Rxe4 and it's important to see that the f7 pawn can't be taken -   19.Nxf7  Rxe4  is game over.  The position is equal but White is still under some pressure. Sample line goes: }
19. Bd2 f6 20. Nf3 Rxe4+ 21. dxe4 Qxe4+ 22. Kf1 Rxd2 23. Nxd2 Qh1+ 24. Ke2 Qxa1
{ The smoke has cleared and the game should end in a draw, e.g. } 25. Qd3 b6
26. Qd8+ Kb7 27. Qd5+ Kb8 *

