1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4
{ The recent correspondence and over the board praxis has established this move to be very promising, yielding Black great results. As we will see, White can easily end up in trouble if he does not proceed cautiously. }
5. Bc4
{ In the next chapter we will deal with 5.Ba4 as well as 5.Nxd4 or 5.O-O. }
5... Bc5 6. Nxe5 Qe7 { The key move, not being afraid of any capture on f7. }
7. Nf3 { The most popular move. } 7... d5
{ Just like against 7.Nd3 this is a key resource. Black sacrifices even more material but gets enormous activity. }
8. Bxd5 Bg4 9. d3 O-O-O
{ Finishing the development and preparing forcing operations. } 10. Be3 Nxd5
{ It's time for the action! Otherwise White's bishop would move away. } 11.
Nxd5 Rxd5 { An unexpected sacrifice! } 12. exd5 Re8
{ This silent move justifies Black's whole concept of play. } 13. O-O
{ Not a bad move but White will need to defend accurately. } 13... Bxf3
{ Doubling the pawns, which give Black promising attacking chances. } 14. gxf3
Bd6 { Preparing ...Qh4 } 15. f4 Qh4 16. c3
{ White doesn't have time for such a move. } 16... g5
{ Or  16...Qh3  17.cxd4  g5 } 17. cxd4 Qh3
{ Not  17...gxf4  18.Qf3  fxe3  19.h3!  with an edge for White. } 18. Kh1 gxf4
19. f3 fxe3 20. Qe2 Qh5
{ Planning ...Qxd5, ...f5 etc. White is in miserable shape. } *

