1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4
{ The recent correspondence and over the board praxis has established this move to be very promising, yielding Black great results. As we will see, White can easily end up in trouble if he does not proceed cautiously. }
5. Nxd4
{ This move may lead to quick simplifications, which are likely to end in a draw. Unfortunately we can't always spice things up as Black. }
5... exd4 6. e5 dxc3 7. exf6 Qxf6
{ Don't be greedy with  7...cxd2  8.Bxd2  Qxf6  as that's already probably lost.  9.O-O  Be7  10.Bc3  with a devastating attack. }
8. dxc3 Bc5 { The game plays itself. } 9. O-O
{ After this move you should know only one trick. } 9... O-O 10. Bxd7
{ Not the best but the only move to analyse. Obviously there is nothing to remember after for example  10.Qh5  d6  . }
10... Bxd7
{ White actually won a pawn. We couldn't win a piece by  10...Rd8  due to  11.Qh5  However, now Black should be happy. We get enormous compensation. }
11. Qxd7 Rae8 { Threatening   12.--  Qxf2  13.Rxf2  Re1  mate! } 12. Qd3 Re5
{ White's doubled extra pawn is not worth much while we have great piece activity. }
