1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4
{ The recent correspondence and over the board praxis has established this move to be very promising, yielding Black great results. As we will see, White can easily end up in trouble if he does not proceed cautiously. }
5. O-O c6 6. Bd3 { As e4 is overprotected White wants to take on d4. } 6...
Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 d6
{ 7...Bc5  suggests itself, but allows  8.Qg3!  The bishop will be well placed on g7, though. }
8. Be2
{ This prepares Qg3 and f4 while the bishop prevents ...Nh5. This is recommended by Alexander Khalifman and Sergei Soloviov in 'Squeezing 1.e4 e5: a Solid Strategic Approach'  (chess-stars 2019)  . }
8... g6
{ Black achieves an extremely good version of some kind of the King's Indian. }
9. d3 Nh5
{ With very simple play in prospect: ...Bg7, ...0-0, ...f5.   Not  9...Bg7?  10.Qg3!  with f4.  It may seem White is already developed while Black moves his knight for the second time but White's pieces are not ready for any action. Black will easily complete the development.  This simple move wasn't mentioned by Alexander Khalifman and Sergei Soloviov. }
*

