[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Four Knights Game - 4.Bb5 Nd4 5.Ba4 & 5.others"]
[Black "Four Knights 4.Bb5 Nd4 5.Ba4 #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4
{ The recent correspondence and over the board praxis has established this move to be very promising, yielding Black great results. As we will see, White can easily end up in trouble if he does not proceed cautiously. }
5. Ba4 c6
{ A little but very powerful move. Black may play some ...b5, ...a5 chasing the bishop but the main point is revealed when White accepts the gambit and takes on e5.   The two times more popular  5...Bc5  is playable but  6.Nxe5  O-O  7.Nd3  Bb6  8.e5  Ne8  9.Nd5  doesn't seem to be so convincing for Black. }
6. O-O { This natural move doesn't meet demands of the position. } 6... a5
{ Black begins chasing the bishop, facing White with very difficult problems. This is a very strong move but it was played only once in OTB games. }
7. Nxd4 { This move greatly aggravates White's problems. } 7... exd4 8. e5 dxc3
9. exf6 d5
{ This is stronger than  9...Qxf6  ,  because Black threatens ...b5. } 10. fxg7
Bxg7 11. bxc3 O-O
{ Black should be wary and not fall for  11...b5?  12.Ba3!  , when White suddenly gets a big compensation for the piece.  Here Black completes the development while White's bishop on a4 is completely out of the game. Sample line goes: }
12. a3 Re8 13. Bb3 a4 14. Ba2 Qh4
{ Having 'buried alive' the a2 bishop, Black can start a decisive kingside attack. White is basically busted here. }
*

