[White "15. Four Knights Game - 4.Bb5 Nd4 5.Ba4 & 5.others"]
[Black "Four Knights 4.Bb5 Nd4 5.Ba4 #07"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4
{ The recent correspondence and over the board praxis has established this move to be very promising, yielding Black great results. As we will see, White can easily end up in trouble if he does not proceed cautiously. }
5. Ba4 c6
{ A little but very powerful move. Black may play some ...b5, ...a5 chasing the bishop but the main point is revealed when White accepts the gambit and takes on e5.   The two times more popular  5...Bc5  is playable but  6.Nxe5  O-O  7.Nd3  Bb6  8.e5  Ne8  9.Nd5  doesn't seem to be so convincing for Black. }
6. Nxe5
{ Of course, the only serious way to try and justify the loss of tempo with Bb5-a4 is to take the pawn. However, Black can now develop a powerful initiative with accurate play. }
6... d6
{ Somehow having ...Bg4 on the cards is extremely important now and this move wouldn't be possible if ...c6 wouldn't block the a4-e8 diagonal. As we are going to see, Black has a very pleasant compensation. }
7. Nd3 a5
{ A move like  7...Be7  would be fine, but we can fight for an advantage. We could play  7...b5  8.Bb3  a5  where Black has a good game, but again and again we prefer playing  ...a5  first which limits White's options. }
8. a3 b5 9. Bb3 d5 { Not giving White the time to breathe. } 10. e5 Bg4
{ It looks like we will be losing the knight, but it is only a temporary sacrifice to gain a powerful initiative }
11. f3 Bf5 12. exf6 Qxf6 { How to prevent ...Nxb3 followed by ...Bxd3? } 13.
Nf2 a4 { Black regains the piece with a very significant edge. } *

