{ Somehow having ...Bg4 on the cards is extremely important now and this move wouldn't be possible if ...c6 wouldn't block the a4-e8 diagonal. As we are going to see, Black has a very pleasant compensation. }
7. Nf3 Bg4 8. d3 Bh5
{ A cunning move, which is yet to be tested in over-the-board play. So far only  8...d5  and  8...Nd7  have been played and Simon Williams mentions only these moves on his ChessBase DVD 'Rocket Repertoire: The Four Knights'.  Black's basic idea is ...Nxf3+, when after the recapture the bishop would need to retreat to h5 anyway. By playing ...Bh5 first, he maintains a high degree of flexibility and 'passes the ball to' White, for whom it is not easy to find a useful move.   One example of the usefulness of the bishop on h5 is the variation   8...b5  9.Be3!  Nxf3+  10.gxf3  and the bishop is hanging. }
9. Rg1
{ White is not only getting ready for gxf3 opening the g-file but he is thinking about playing g4! }
9... b5
{ Usually we play ...a5 first but in this case White threatens g4 so we need to make a move with a tempo. }
10. Nxd4 { This temporary queen sacrifice is probably White's best choice. }
10... Bxd1 11. Nxc6 Qd7 12. Bxb5 a6
{ The only move, in other case White would retake the queen for only one piece. }
13. Ne5 { 13.Ba4?  Bxc2!  is the point. } 13... Qxb5 14. Nxb5 axb5 15. Nxf7
Kxf7 16. Kxd1
{ The endgame is objectively balanced, although Black's practical task seems easier. An example of precise play by both sides is: }
16... d5 17. f3 Bd6 18. g3 b4 19. a4 bxa3 20. bxa3 dxe4 21. fxe4 Rhc8 22. a4
Ng4 23. Rg2 Be5 24. Ra2 Bd4 25. Ke2 Ke6 26. a5 Ra6 27. Bd2 Bb6 28. h3 Nf6 29.
Kf3 Rca8 30. c3 Rxa5 { Draw was agreed in Hild-Toma, email 2017 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Four Knights Game - 4.Bb5 Nd4 5.Ba4 & 5.others"]
[Black "Four Knights 4.Bb5 Nd4 5.Ba4 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4
{ The recent correspondence and over the board praxis has established this move to be very promising, yielding Black great results. As we will see, White can easily end up in trouble if he does not proceed cautiously. }
5. Ba4 c6
{ A little but very powerful move. Black may play some ...b5, ...a5 chasing the bishop but the main point is revealed when White accepts the gambit and takes on e5.   The two times more popular  5...Bc5  is playable but  6.Nxe5  O-O  7.Nd3  Bb6  8.e5  Ne8  9.Nd5  doesn't seem to be so convincing for Black. }
6. Nxe5
{ Of course, the only serious way to try and justify the loss of tempo with Bb5-a4 is to take the pawn. However, Black can now develop a powerful initiative with accurate play. }
6... d6
{ Somehow having ...Bg4 on the cards is extremely important now and this move wouldn't be possible if ...c6 wouldn't block the a4-e8 diagonal. As we are going to see, Black has a very pleasant compensation. }
7. Nf3 Bg4 8. d3 Bh5
{ A cunning move, which is yet to be tested in over-the-board play. So far only  8...d5  and  8...Nd7  have been played and Simon Williams mentions only these moves on his ChessBase DVD 'Rocket Repertoire: The Four Knights'.  Black's basic idea is ...Nxf3+, when after the recapture the bishop would need to retreat to h5 anyway. By playing ...Bh5 first, he maintains a high degree of flexibility and 'passes the ball to' White, for whom it is not easy to find a useful move.   One example of the usefulness of the bishop on h5 is the variation   8...b5  9.Be3!  Nxf3+  10.gxf3  and the bishop is hanging. }
9. Rg1
{ White is not only getting ready for gxf3 opening the g-file but he is thinking about playing g4! }
9... b5
{ Usually we play ...a5 first but in this case White threatens g4 so we need to make a move with a tempo. }
10. Bb3 { A natural move, but in fact Black gets an edge after it. } 10... a5
{ Simple play is often the best. The light-squared bishop's placement proves to be a nuisance for White. }
11. g4
{ An interesting move, which, however, doesn't alter the evaluation. White could also start with a more spectacular looking  11.Bxf7  Kxf7  12.g4  which would transpose. }
11... Bxg4 12. Bxf7+
{ The whole point of dragging the bishop to  b3  is revealed after  12.Rxg4  we have  12...Nxb3 }
12... Kxf7 13. Rxg4 Nxc2+
{ Without this move White's idea would be quite good, as after  13....Nxg4  14.Nxd4  both  g4  and  c6  are hanging. }
14. Qxc2 Nxg4
{ The onus is on White to demonstrate full compensation for the exchange. } *

