{ White is not only getting ready for gxf3 opening the g-file but he is thinking about playing g4! }
9... b5
{ Usually we play ...a5 first but in this case White threatens g4 so we need to make a move with a tempo. }
10. Bb3 { A natural move, but in fact Black gets an edge after it. } 10... a5
{ Simple play is often the best. The light-squared bishop's placement proves to be a nuisance for White. }
11. a3 d5 { Grabbing the centre. } 12. exd5
{ 12.Ba2?!  is much too slow. After  12...Bc5  Black has agreat initiative. }
12... Nxb3 13. cxb3 Nxd5
{ Black's compensation for the pawn is more than adequate; he has scored excellent results in correspondence play, e.g. }
14. g4 Bg6 15. h4 Qe7+ 16. Kf1 O-O-O 17. d4 h5 18. Nxd5 Rxd5 19. Be3 f6 20. g5
Bf5 { with a huge advantage. } *

