1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ In this chapter we will focus on 4.Bc4 but we will also have a look at some lesser known moves, even 4.a3 and 4.a4. }
4. h3
{ This is more clever than 4.a3, because it keeps the bishop away from the g4-square. Nevertheless, it is not problematic for Black at all. }
4... d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. d4
{ 9.Re1  Bf5  10.d4  exd4  11.cxd4  h6  transposes. } 9... exd4 10. cxd4
{ Here  10.Bg5  f6  11.Bh4  is less convincing because after  11...g5  12.Bg3  Bxg3  it is impossible to recapture with the h-pawn. }
10... h6 11. Re1 Bf5 { The bishop is also perfectly fine on f5, e.g. } 12. Rb1
Re8 13. Be3 Qc8 14. Rb3 a6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. c4 Bf8
{ with less space, but the bishop pair. } *

