1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ In this chapter we will focus on 4.Bc4 but we will also have a look at some lesser known moves, even 4.a3 and 4.a4. }
4. Bc4
{ Black should be happy to see this move, which gives him an opportunity to immediately take over the initiative with a typical tactic. }
4... Nxe4
{ This trick was known in the 19th century. For example in 1886 it was featured in the game Dirk Van Foreest - Arnold Van Foreest @@StartBracket@@yes, these are the ancestors of Lucas and Jorden!@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nxe4 d5 6. Bd3 { The only sensible move. } 6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 Bd6
{ Giving extra support to the e5 pawn. Our plan would be to prepare ...f5. } 8.
O-O O-O 9. Re1 Nb4
{ This strong move was discovered by correspondence players.   9...f5  is desirable but it fails to  10.Bxc6  bxc6  11.Nxe5  . With the text Black prepares 10...f5 simultaneously preventing 11. Bxc6 and 11.Bd5+.   But the more natural  9...Re8  and  9...Nd4  are enough for equality. }
10. d4 f5 11. Bg5
{ I believe White has to play this move in order to maintain the equilibrium. }
11... Qe8 12. dxe5 { Entering a forced sequence. } 12... fxe4 13. exd6 Qg6 14.
d7 { The only move. } 14... Bxd7 15. Ne5 Qxg5 16. Nxd7 Rad8
{ At it seems that White is trouble due to the pin and it might not be easy for him to find the way out in practical play. }
17. c3
{ After this natural move, Black achieves nearly winning advantage with a very precise sequence. }
17... Nc6
{ @@StartBracket@@17...Nd3 looks tempting but then we no longer pin the knight so White has 18.Nxf8 with equality.@@EndBracket@@ }
18. Qb3+ Rf7 19. Qxb7 Qd5 { 19...e3?!  is countered by  20.f4! } 20. Rad1 Qc4
{ The key move, which point will become clear in the 21.b3 variation. This is very difficult and if you want to play the best moves you have to find it.   We are already at move 20 so it feels this is not a practical line but note that first of all we are playing for the win as Black, if you don't remember or don't work it out over the board and play  20...Qf5  it's an equal game. Also it's clear your opponent will have no idea about all this because if he knew he wouldn't voluntarily go for such a line where White is much worse at the end. }
21. b3 Qe6
{ Once we took away b3 square from the White queen we can go here. The point will become clear. }
22. Nc5 Rxd1 23. Rxd1 Qf5 { A key double attack. } 24. Nxe4 Qxe4 25. Rd8+ Rf8
{ The purpose of 20...Qc4 reveals itself. Had not Black induced 21.b3, White would have won by 26.Hb3+! }
26. Rxf8+ Kxf8 *

