{ In this chapter we will focus on the most straightforward 5.d4. In the next one we will cover 5.d3 while 4.0-0 will be seen in later chapters. }
4... Nf6 5. d4
{ Going for the d4 break immediately is the old way of playing the Italian. Nowadays it is seen mostly at lower levels, because it has long been known not to give White any realistic hopes for an advantage. }
5... exd4 6. e5 { A modern treatment of the 5.d4 line. } 6... d5 7. Be2
{ This seemingly innocuous move gains in popularity lately. White players like to experiment with different things, even if it objectively doesn't give any advantage it may have a surprise value. }
7... d3 { Played in order to obtain a favourable structure. } 8. exf6 dxe2 9.
Qxe2+ { All forced. } 9... Kf8
{ It's not a great situation for our king but we should be able to either find a safe place or change queens. }
10. b4
{ 10.Bg5  Qe8  would be similar to this line   while after  10.fxg7+  Kxg7  we will continue with ...Re8 and our king is quite safe, it can move to h8 if needed. }
10... Bd6 11. Bg5
{ similar is  11.b5  Na5  12.Bg5  Qe8  played in Jobava vs Timman, Hoogeveen match, 2014. }
11... Qe8 { Let's just trade queens and get into the endgame. } 12. Qxe8+ Kxe8
13. fxg7 Rg8 14. Bf6
{ The g7 pawn may look strong but we can win it.   14.O-O  Rxg7  is just fine, White has the better structure, but it is offset by Black's bishop pair. }
14... Be7 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 { Black fully equalizes after taking on g7. } *

