[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the oldest openings in chess. It was developed in the 16th and 17th centuries by famous Italian masters Damiano, Polerio and Greco. It has always been frequently seen in beginners' and amateurs' games but its popularity among strong players gradually ceased in favor of the Ruy Lopez, which was considered a better try for an advantage until very recently. However, things have changed dramatically in recent years. Due to the futility of their attempts against the Berlin Defence, top players have started seeking ways to pose Black problems in the long-forgotten Italian. As a result of the trend set by Carlsen, Anand, Caruana, Karjakin, Vachier- Lagrave, Giri and other strong players it has suddenly become more popular than the Ruy Lopez and its theory has grown enormously. Unlike just a few years ago, Black is nowadays required to know the nuances of different lines and move orders to obtain a good position out of the opening. }
3... Bc5 4. c3
{ In this chapter we will focus on the most straightforward 5.d4. In the next one we will cover 5.d3 while 4.0-0 will be seen in later chapters. }
4... Nf6 5. d4
{ Going for the d4 break immediately is the old way of playing the Italian. Nowadays it is seen mostly at lower levels, because it has long been known not to give White any realistic hopes for an advantage. }
5... exd4 6. e5 { A modern treatment of the 5.d4 line. } 6... d5
{ A key counter attacking resource in this type of position. Without this move Black would be clearly worse. }
7. Bb5 Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6
{ Modern grandmasters clearly prefer this move, but of course 8...Bb4 is playable. We are keeping some pressure on the d4 pawn but sometimes this bishop can become very bad so you need to be aware of this. }
9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be3 f5
{ @@StartBracket@@10...Bg4 is much more popular, but I think this continuation is at least as promising for Black. @@EndBracket@@ Our idea is to simply push ...f4 and if White takes en passant he exchanges his strong e5 pawn. }
11. exf6 { The most popular move, yet a non-critical one. } 11... Rxf6
{ Taking with a queen is not good because  d5  is hanging however you may consider  11...Nxc3  12.bxc3  Qxf6  .   The most popular is  11...Nxf6  , actually all these options were played by some grandmasters.   Taking with the rook is the most accurate, but you have sensible alternatives. }
12. Nxe4
{ This hasn't been tried but of course we need to check this forcing move. }
12... dxe4 13. Ng5 Qe8
{ Not an obvious move especially that it may seem we can lose a piece after White pushes d5. However it works tactically and we really want to stop Qh5.   Perfectly playable is more natural  13...Qe7  but after  14.Bc4  Kh8  15.Qh5  Bf5  16.Nf7+  White has no better choice than to go for the repetition. }
14. Qb3+ { 14.d5  just doesn't work due to  14...Bxe3  15.fxe3  Qe5  . } 14...
Kh8 15. O-O
{ 15.d5  again doesn't win a piece. Black has  15...Ba5+  16.Kf1  a6  . } 15...
Qg6 { Black is the one who is pressing. } *

