1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the oldest openings in chess. It was developed in the 16th and 17th centuries by famous Italian masters Damiano, Polerio and Greco. It has always been frequently seen in beginners' and amateurs' games but its popularity among strong players gradually ceased in favor of the Ruy Lopez, which was considered a better try for an advantage until very recently. However, things have changed dramatically in recent years. Due to the futility of their attempts against the Berlin Defence, top players have started seeking ways to pose Black problems in the long-forgotten Italian. As a result of the trend set by Carlsen, Anand, Caruana, Karjakin, Vachier- Lagrave, Giri and other strong players it has suddenly become more popular than the Ruy Lopez and its theory has grown enormously. Unlike just a few years ago, Black is nowadays required to know the nuances of different lines and move orders to obtain a good position out of the opening. }
3... Bc5 4. c3
{ In this chapter we will focus on the most straightforward 5.d4. In the next one we will cover 5.d3 while 4.0-0 will be seen in later chapters. }
4... Nf6 5. d4
{ Going for the d4 break immediately is the old way of playing the Italian. Nowadays it is seen mostly at lower levels, because it has long been known not to give White any realistic hopes for an advantage. }
5... exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nc3
{ This move was established as unpromising a long time ago and nothing has changed since then. In fact, White does not even equalize. }
7... Nxe4 8. O-O Bxc3
{ @@StartBracket@@The most promising although possible is 8...Nxc3 9.bxc3 d5! but not 9...Bxc3 10.Ba3 when Black's king can be killed very quickly.@@EndBracket@@ }
9. d5 Bf6 { It is more important to preserve the bishop than the knight. } 10.
Re1 Ne7 11. Rxe4 d6
{ @@StartBracket@@11...0-0 12.d6 is less comfortable for us.@@EndBracket@@ }
12. Bg5 Bxg5 13. Nxg5 h6 14. Qe2
{ One of the rare instances in chess theory, when the overwhelmingly most popular move is clearly bad. }
14... hxg5
{ There is no point in playing  14...Bf5  because as we will see  15.Re3  White's rook would be better placed here. }
15. Re1 Be6 { An obvious reply, which completely refutes White's play. } 16.
dxe6 f6 17. Re3 { Almost everyone played this. White is preparing Rh3. } 17...
c6 18. Rh3
{ The whole line is very amateurish. White shatters his pawn structure irreparably to create a one-move threat of Qh5+. Needless to say, Black has never fallen for it. }
18... Rxh3 19. gxh3 g6
{ After parrying White's silly threats, Black is a clear pawn up and close to winning. }
