[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Italian Game - 4.c3 with 5.d3"]
[Black "Italian Game 4.c3 & 5.d3 & 6.Bg5 #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the oldest openings in chess. It was developed in the 16th and 17th centuries by famous Italian masters Damiano, Polerio and Greco. It has always been frequently seen in begginers' and ammateurs' games but its popularity among strong players gradually ceased in favor of the Ruy Lopez, which was considered a better try for an advantage until very recently. However, things have changed dramatically in recent years. Due to a futility of their attempts against the Berlin Defence, top players have started seeking ways to pose Black problems in the long-forgotten Italian. As a result of the trend set by Carlsen, Anand, Caruana, Karjakin, Vachier- Lagrave, Giri and other strong players it has suddenly become more popular than the Ruy Lopez and its theory has grown enormously. Unlike just a few years ago, Black is nowadays required to know the nuances of different lines and move orders to obtain a good position out of the opening. }
3... Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 O-O
{ The position is very likely to transpose to one of the lines of the 4.0-0 Nf6 5.d3 0-0 6.c3 move order. However, there are a few lines of independent value. }
6. Bg5
{ Usually this pin is not comfortable once we played ...d6. Here however we can easily unpin as we will see. }
6... h6
{ We want to play ...Be7 breaking the pin but throwing ... h6 in first is generally a useful thing to do. }
7. Bh4 Be7
{ A typical way to play. Now there is no pin and we will try to exchange dark squared bishops via ...Nh5.   7...g5  8.Bg3  d6  transposes to some lines out of our recommended repertoire. }
8. Nbd2 d6 9. Bg3 Na5
{ A typical maneuver. We are gaining time by attacking the bishop and we want to push ...c5 bringing more pawns to the centre.   Also removing our knight from  c6  is useful. Note that  9...Nh5  is strategically fine but here it fails tactically to  10.Nxe5  Nxg3  11.Nxc6! }
10. Bb5 c5 11. Ba4 Nh5
{ With a bishop pair and a plenty of space, Black is at least not worse. But you don't have to rush with taking on g3. }
