7. Bh4 Be7
{ A typical way to play. Now there is no pin and we will try to exchange dark squared bishops via ...Nh5. @@StartBracket@@7...g5 8.Bg3 d6 transposes to some lines out of our recommended repertoire.@@EndBracket@@ }
8. Nbd2 d6 9. Bb3 Na5
{ Again the same idea. But here  9...Nh5  works as well. } 10. Bc2 c5 11. O-O
{ A quick mention that we are not afraid of any  11.Bxf6  because none of White's pieces is controlling d5 square. }
11... Nh5
{ We are happy to either trade the bishops or gain the bishop pair if White goes Bg3. But you don't have to rush with taking on g3. }
