[White "19. Italian Game - 4.0-0 Intro & Modern 8.a4"]
[Black "Italian Game 4.0-0 & 6.h3 #04"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the oldest openings in chess. It was developed in the 16th and 17th centuries by famous Italian masters Damiano, Polerio and Greco. It has always been frequently seen in begginers' and ammateurs' games but its popularity among strong players gradually ceased in favor of the Ruy Lopez, which was considered a better try for an advantage until very recently. However, things have changed dramatically in recent years. Due to a futility of their attempts against the Berlin Defence, top players have started seeking ways to pose Black problems in the long-forgotten Italian. As a result of the trend set by Carlsen, Anand, Caruana, Karjakin, Vachier- Lagrave, Giri and other strong players it has suddenly become more popular than the Ruy Lopez and its theory has grown enormously. Unlike just a few years ago, Black is nowadays required to know the nuances of different lines and move orders to obtain a good position out of the opening. }
3... Bc5 4. O-O
{ With 4.c3 we saw White either playing for a quick d4 or he delayed castling but the natural 4.0-0 is the more popular way of playing the Italian. }
4... Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. h3
{ White postpones c3 in order to discourage ...d5, but Black is doing fine after this thematic break anyway! }
6... d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Re1 Be6
{ Usually we play 8...Nb6 9. Bb3 a5 but after 10.a4 we are missing ... Bg4 move. Once White lost a tempo for h3 we can develop the bishop this way. Note that the pawn on e5 is not hanging now due to ...Bxf2 trick as we will see while we are not afraid of Ng5-e6 as opening of the f-file gives us great attack on f2. }
9. c3 Bb6
{ A useful move stepping out of not only b4-b5 with a tempo but also Nd2-e4. Actually now 10.Nbd2 is met by Nf4 with slight edge. }
10. Bb3
{ This position was reached in Karjakin-Aronian, Wijk an Zee 2017 and Black blundered a piece with  10...f6??  , allowing  11.c4!  and  12.c5  , which, shockingly, Karjakin also missed. }
10... Re8 11. Na3 Qf6
{ A novelty. The queen is safe here once White's knight is far from e4. Black will play ...h6, ...Rad8 and think about ...Nf4.   Note that  11...f6  is positionally not a bad idea but it fails tactically to  12.d4  exd4  13.c4!  as in Volokitin-Shirov, Berlin @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Italian Game - 4.0-0 Intro & Modern 8.a4"]
[Black "Italian Game 4.0-0 & 6.Re1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the oldest openings in chess. It was developed in the 16th and 17th centuries by famous Italian masters Damiano, Polerio and Greco. It has always been frequently seen in begginers' and ammateurs' games but its popularity among strong players gradually ceased in favor of the Ruy Lopez, which was considered a better try for an advantage until very recently. However, things have changed dramatically in recent years. Due to a futility of their attempts against the Berlin Defence, top players have started seeking ways to pose Black problems in the long-forgotten Italian. As a result of the trend set by Carlsen, Anand, Caruana, Karjakin, Vachier- Lagrave, Giri and other strong players it has suddenly become more popular than the Ruy Lopez and its theory has grown enormously. Unlike just a few years ago, Black is nowadays required to know the nuances of different lines and move orders to obtain a good position out of the opening. }
3... Bc5 4. O-O
{ With 4.c3 we saw White either playing for a quick d4 or he delayed castling but the natural 4.0-0 is the more popular way of playing the Italian. }
4... Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. Re1
{ A tricky move aimed at discouraging ..d5. However, White pays the price of allowing the following continuation: }
6... Ng4 7. Re2 Nd4
{ It is very useful to exchange the weaker c6 knight which obstructs the c-pawn. }
8. Nxd4 Bxd4 9. h3 Nf6 10. Nd2 d6
{ We would love to play ...c6 and ...d5 but we can't do it now. We need to build up slowly. }
11. a4
{ This is all recommended by Larry Kaufman in 'Kaufman's New Repertoire for Black and White' @@StartBracket@@New In Chess 2019@@EndBracket@@, but now he misses a standard reply: }
11... a5 { Not allowing White to grab too much space. } 12. Nf3 Bb6 13. Be3 c6
{ The position is close to a symmetry. If White has any edge, it is merely cosmetic. One possible continuation goes }
14. d4 Nxe4 15. dxe5 d5 16. Bd3 Bxe3 17. Rxe3 f5 18. exf6 Qxf6
{ Black has a totally fine, active position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Italian Game - 4.0-0 Intro & Modern 8.a4"]
[Black "Italian Game 4.0-0 & 6.c3 & 8.a4 #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the oldest openings in chess. It was developed in the 16th and 17th centuries by famous Italian masters Damiano, Polerio and Greco. It has always been frequently seen in begginers' and ammateurs' games but its popularity among strong players gradually ceased in favor of the Ruy Lopez, which was considered a better try for an advantage until very recently. However, things have changed dramatically in recent years. Due to a futility of their attempts against the Berlin Defence, top players have started seeking ways to pose Black problems in the long-forgotten Italian. As a result of the trend set by Carlsen, Anand, Caruana, Karjakin, Vachier- Lagrave, Giri and other strong players it has suddenly become more popular than the Ruy Lopez and its theory has grown enormously. Unlike just a few years ago, Black is nowadays required to know the nuances of different lines and move orders to obtain a good position out of the opening. }
3... Bc5 4. O-O
{ With 4.c3 we saw White either playing for a quick d4 or he delayed castling but the natural 4.0-0 is the more popular way of playing the Italian. }
4... Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. c3 d5
{ The most active approach, reminiscent to the variation I recommend against 4.d3 anti-Berlin main line. }
7. exd5 Nxd5
{ We have reached one of the most important structures in this repertoire. White mainly plays against the e5-pawn and sometimes grabs space on the queenside. Black, on the other hand seeks counterplay against the d3-pawn and on the kingside, where he has the pawn majority. Typical continuations include ...Nb6, ...Bg4, ...Bd6 or ...f6 @@StartBracket@@after ...Nb6@@EndBracket@@. }
8. a4
{ The most challenging move, favored by elite players. The idea is quite cunning. After  8...Bg4  ,  White wants to stop the typical ...Nb6 resource by  9.a5! }
8... a5
{ Possible is  8...Nb6  9.Bb5  Ne7!  introduced by Wesley So. White light-squared bishop is such an important piece, that it is worth sacrificing a pawn to eliminate it. It's not a move one could come up with over the board. We just recommend a simpler approach. }
9. Nbd2 Nb6 10. Bb5 Bd6 { This should transpose to other lines. } 11. Ne4
{ 11.Re1  directly transposes to 9.Re1 } 11... Bg4
{ Also possible is forcing  11...Na7  12.d4  Nxb5  13.axb5  exd4  14.Nxd6  Qxd6  15.Qxd4  Bd7  with a drawish endgame. }
12. h3 Bh5
{ Whatever White plays,  13.Re1  f5  (see here)   or  13.Ng3  Bg6  (see here)  (we will transpose to lines covered in this repertoire.) }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Italian Game - 4.0-0 Intro & Modern 8.a4"]
[Black "Italian Game 4.0-0 & 6.c3 & 8.a4 #02"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the oldest openings in chess. It was developed in the 16th and 17th centuries by famous Italian masters Damiano, Polerio and Greco. It has always been frequently seen in begginers' and ammateurs' games but its popularity among strong players gradually ceased in favor of the Ruy Lopez, which was considered a better try for an advantage until very recently. However, things have changed dramatically in recent years. Due to a futility of their attempts against the Berlin Defence, top players have started seeking ways to pose Black problems in the long-forgotten Italian. As a result of the trend set by Carlsen, Anand, Caruana, Karjakin, Vachier- Lagrave, Giri and other strong players it has suddenly become more popular than the Ruy Lopez and its theory has grown enormously. Unlike just a few years ago, Black is nowadays required to know the nuances of different lines and move orders to obtain a good position out of the opening. }
3... Bc5 4. O-O
{ With 4.c3 we saw White either playing for a quick d4 or he delayed castling but the natural 4.0-0 is the more popular way of playing the Italian. }
4... Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. c3 d5
{ The most active approach, reminiscent to the variation I recommend against 4.d3 anti-Berlin main line. }
7. exd5 Nxd5
{ We have reached one of the most important structures in this repertoire. White mainly plays against the e5-pawn and sometimes grabs space on the queenside. Black, on the other hand seeks counterplay against the d3-pawn and on the kingside, where he has the pawn majority. Typical continuations include ...Nb6, ...Bg4, ...Bd6 or ...f6 @@StartBracket@@after ...Nb6@@EndBracket@@. }
8. a4
{ The most challenging move, favored by elite players. The idea is quite cunning. After  8...Bg4  ,  White wants to stop the typical ...Nb6 resource by  9.a5! }
8... a5
{ Possible is  8...Nb6  9.Bb5  Ne7!  introduced by Wesley So. White light-squared bishop is such an important piece, that it is worth sacrificing a pawn to eliminate it. It's not a move one could come up with over the board. We just recommend a simpler approach. }
9. Re1 { The most natural move targetting the e5 pawn. } 9... Nb6 10. Bb5 Bd6
{ This is our typical move, while  10...Bg4  11.h3  Bh5  loses to  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.Rxe5 }
11. Nbd2 Bg4
{ This logical move wasn't considered by Karsten Muller and Georgios Souleidis in 'Winning with the Slow @@StartBracket@@but Venomous!@@EndBracket@@ Italian' @@StartBracket@@New In Chess 2016@@EndBracket@@. They mention only  11...Na7  and  11...Bf5  which are playable but we prefer this natural move, it's a standard setup for us in this system. }
12. Ne4 Na7
{ Going after the light squared bishop. Now, White is obliged to take immediate action if he wants to fight for the advantage. Note that with the inclusion of a4 and ...a5 we can't play   12...f5  because  13.Nxd6  cxd6  14.Qb3+  Kh8  15.Ng5  and now the desired  15...Qf6  runs into  16.Bxc6  and the loose knight on  b6  drops. }
13. h3 Bh5 14. d4
{ The only challenging move after which there are a lot of exchanges. We are going to reach an endgame which we analyzed carefully and the conclusion is it's fine for us. }
14... exd4 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. Qxd4 Bxf3 { It's all forced. } 17. Qxd6 cxd6 18.
gxf3 Nxb5 19. axb5 a4
{ Fixing the b2 pawn. The arising endgame was asessed as favourable for White by Martyn Kravtsiv in the second volume of 'The Italian Renaissance' @@StartBracket@@Quality Chess 2020@@EndBracket@@. However, our extensive analysis lead to the conclusion that it's equal and both sides need to be quite precise here. }
20. Re7 Rfb8 21. Rc7
{ The only move which poses some problems and not an easy one to find. White stops ...Nc4 and prepares c4 on his own. }
21... d5 22. Bf4 d4
{ While defending we should always look for tactical opportunities. } 23. c4 f6
{ A generally useful move to give a luft to our king and restrict White's bishop. The inclusion of this move actually is critical in some of the lines. }
24. Kf1 Rc8 25. Rc1
{ Covering c4 is the only try. Now White threatens Rxb7 Nxc4 Rc7. } 25... a3
{ Activating our rook turns out to be essential. } 26. bxa3 Rxa3
{ Don't forget that we also have a passed pawn. The position is objectively equal. }
*

