1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the oldest openings in chess. It was developed in the 16th and 17th centuries by famous Italian masters Damiano, Polerio and Greco. It has always been frequently seen in beginners' and amateurs' games but its popularity among strong players gradually ceased in favor of the Ruy Lopez, which was considered a better try for an advantage until very recently. However, things have changed dramatically in recent years. Due to a futility of their attempts against the Berlin Defence, top players have started seeking ways to pose Black problems in the long-forgotten Italian. As a result of the trend set by Carlsen, Anand, Caruana, Karjakin, Vachier- Lagrave, Giri and other strong players it has suddenly become more popular than the Ruy Lopez and its theory has grown enormously. Unlike just a few years ago, Black is nowadays required to know the nuances of different lines and move orders to obtain a good position out of the opening. }
3... Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. c3 d5
{ The most active approach, reminiscent to the variation I recommend against 4.d3 anti-Berlin main line. }
7. exd5 Nxd5
{ We have reached one of the most important structures in this repertoire. White mainly plays against the e5-pawn and sometimes grabs space on the queenside. Black, on the other hand seeks counterplay against the d3-pawn and on the kingside, where he has the pawn majority. Typical continuations include ...Nb6, ...Bg4, ...Bd6 or ...f6 @@StartBracket@@after ...Nb6@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Re1
{ The most often played move, which, however fails to address Black's main ideas, ...Bg4 and ...Nb6 effectively. }
8... Bg4 9. h3 { 9.Nbd2  Nb6  10.h3  Bh5  transposes. } 9... Bh5 10. Nbd2 Nb6
11. Ne4 { This is just harmless. } 11... Nxc4 12. Nxc5 Nd6 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nxe5
{ This is not even winning a pawn as we will quickly regain it with interest. }
14... Nxe5 15. Rxe5 b6 16. Nb3
{ The engine prefers   16.Na6  but after  16...f5  Black had a clear edge in Bellia-Kobo, Barcelona 2015. }
16... Nc4 17. Re1 Qxd3 18. Qxd3 Bxd3
{ We got our pawn back and it is White who still needs to be accurate. } *

