1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the oldest openings in chess. It was developed in the 16th and 17th centuries by famous Italian masters Damiano, Polerio and Greco. It has always been frequently seen in beginners' and amateurs' games but its popularity among strong players gradually ceased in favor of the Ruy Lopez, which was considered a better try for an advantage until very recently. However, things have changed dramatically in recent years. Due to a futility of their attempts against the Berlin Defence, top players have started seeking ways to pose Black problems in the long-forgotten Italian. As a result of the trend set by Carlsen, Anand, Caruana, Karjakin, Vachier- Lagrave, Giri and other strong players it has suddenly become more popular than the Ruy Lopez and its theory has grown enormously. Unlike just a few years ago, Black is nowadays required to know the nuances of different lines and move orders to obtain a good position out of the opening. }
3... Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. c3 d5
{ The most active approach, reminiscent to the variation I recommend against 4.d3 anti-Berlin main line. }
7. exd5 Nxd5
{ We have reached one of the most important structures in this repertoire. White mainly plays against the e5-pawn and sometimes grabs space on the queenside. Black, on the other hand seeks counterplay against the d3-pawn and on the kingside, where he has the pawn majority. Typical continuations include ...Nb6, ...Bg4, ...Bd6 or ...f6 @@StartBracket@@after ...Nb6@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Re1
{ The most often played move, which, however fails to address Black's main ideas, ...Bg4 and ...Nb6 effectively. }
8... Bg4 9. h3 { 9.Nbd2  Nb6  10.h3  Bh5  transposes. } 9... Bh5 10. Nbd2 Nb6
11. Bb3 { This surprising move is a new trend. } 11... Qxd3 12. Nxe5 Qf5 13.
Nef3 Rad8
{ At first sight it looks like nothing is happening but in fact things are bit tricky, so let's see further. }
14. Qe2 Qc8
{ Preparing ...Rfe8 and stepping off g4. Immediate 14...Rfe8 15.Qxe8 Rxe8 16.Rxe8 Bf8 is probably playable but with two rooks for a queen White has better control over the position. Nothing immediate is happening but in a long run it is Black who needs to constantly react to White's action. At the same time it's difficult to create own play because there are no weaknesses in White's camp. }
15. Qb5 { Trying to disrupt Black's piece coordination. } 15... Nd7 16. Nh4
{ The critical move, preparing Ne4 by stepping out of ...Bxf3. This hasn't been tried in practice yet. }
16... a6 17. Qf1 Nf6 18. Ndf3 { Or   18.Nc4  Rfe8  with equality. } 18... Rde8
{ The more natural looking   18...Rfe8  runs into  19.Bg5  with quite annoying pin. }
19. Bf4 Ne4 20. Re2 Kh8 { Preparing ...f5 with a good game. A sample line is: }
21. Rae1 f5 22. Bc2 g5 23. Nxg5 Bxe2 24. Rxe2 Nxg5 25. Bxg5 Be7
{ White has enough compensation for the exchange, but no more, e.g. } 26. Qc1
Bxg5 27. Qxg5 Qd8 28. Ng6+ Kg7 29. Ne7+ Kh8 30. Ng6+ { with a repetition. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21.Evans Gambit"]
[Black "Evans Gambit 6.0-0 d6 7.Qb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans gambit essentially belongs to the 19th century, but White players still try it occasionally, hoping to surprise Black, so it is important to be prepared. I found a great way to obtain a promising position without having to remember a lot of lines. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. O-O
{ This slow continuation gives Black time to comfortably develop his forces. }
6... d6 7. Qb3 Nh6
{ We need to finish the development as fast as possible. We won't be afraid of any Bxh6 because White won't be able to make use of those weaknesses while he'd part with his bishop pair.   Also note that  7...Qe7  8.d4  is a bit problematic once we played ...d6 because d5 followed by Qa4 with a check is a threat. }
8. d4 O-O 9. Bg5 Qe8 10. Nbd2 Kh8
{ Preparing ...f5 or ...Ng8-e7. White will have a hard time trying to demonstrate full compensation for the pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21.Evans Gambit"]
[Black "Evans Gambit 6.0-0 d6 7.d4 #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans gambit essentially belongs to the 19th century, but White players still try it occasionally, hoping to surprise Black, so it is important to be prepared. I found a great way to obtain a promising position without having to remember a lot of lines. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. O-O
{ This slow continuation gives Black time to comfortably develop his forces. }
6... d6 7. d4 Bg4
{ 7...Nf6  is less clear because  8.dxe5  Nxe5  9.Nxe5  dxe5  10.Qb3  O-O  11.Ba3  wins the exchange. }
8. Qa4 { This activity is just over optimistic. } 8... Bxf3 9. gxf3 exd4 10.
cxd4 a6
{ A key move preparing a crucial offensive and defensive idea of ...b5 } 11.
Bd5 Ne7 12. Bxc6+ Nxc6 13. d5 b5 { Without this move we would be in trouble. }
14. Qa3 Nd4 15. Qxa5
{ White still won a piece but now Black develops an irresistible attack. }
15... Qf6 16. Qa3
{ This was played in Chigorin -Steinitz, World Championship 1892 but now Black erred with  16...Nc2  - then  17.Qd3  Nxa1  18.Qe2  is great for White because the knight on a1 will be lost. Instead, he is winning after: }
16... b4 17. Qb2
{ This saves a Rook on a1 but loses the game in a different way.   17.Qxb4  Nxf3  is mate in 8 }
17... Nxf3+ 18. Kg2 Nh4+ 19. Kh3 Qf3+ 20. Kxh4 Qg2
{ Black either wins the rook on f1 or mates White. One way or the other the king on h4 will not be able to survive long. }
*

