[Black "Evans Gambit 6.0-0 d6 7.d4 #02"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans gambit essentially belongs to the 19th century, but White players still try it occasionally, hoping to surprise Black, so it is important to be prepared. I found a great way to obtain a promising position without having to remember a lot of lines. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. O-O
{ This slow continuation gives Black time to comfortably develop his forces. }
6... d6 7. d4 Bg4
{ 7...Nf6 is less clear because 8.dxe5 Nxe5 9.Nxe5 dxe5 10.Qb3 O-O 11.Ba3 wins the exchange. }
8. Qa4 { This activity is just over optimistic. } 8... Bxf3 9. gxf3 exd4 10.
cxd4 a6
{ A key move preparing a crucial offensive and defensive idea of ...b5 } 11.
Bd5 Ne7 12. Bxc6+ Nxc6 13. d5 b5 { Without this move we would be in trouble. }
14. Qa3 Nd4 15. Qxa5
{ White still won a piece but now Black develops an irresistible attack. }
15... Qf6 16. Qa3
{ This was played in Chigorin -Steinitz, World Championship 1892 but now Black erred with 16....Nc2 Instead, he is winning after: }
16... b4 17. Qa4+ Kf8 18. Nd2 Ne2+ 19. Kg2 Qxa1
{ Suddenly Black is even some material up. The line is quite long but forcing. It's nice to remember it but if you feel the dynamic well you have a good chance to find the best moves even if you forget something. }
20. Qc6 Ra7 21. Nb3 Qc3 22. Qd7 Ra8 23. Bd2 Qf6 24. Qxc7 h5
{ Intending to include the rook into play via h6. Black is a sound exchange up and should win. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21.Evans Gambit"]
[Black "Evans Gambit 6.0-0 d6 7.d4 #03"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans gambit essentially belongs to the 19th century, but White players still try it occasionally, hoping to surprise Black, so it is important to be prepared. I found a great way to obtain a promising position without having to remember a lot of lines. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. O-O
{ This slow continuation gives Black time to comfortably develop his forces. }
6... d6 7. d4 Bg4
{ 7...Nf6 is less clear because 8.dxe5 Nxe5 9.Nxe5 dxe5 10.Qb3 O-O 11.Ba3 wins the exchange. }
8. Bb5
{ Threatening Qa4 but after Black's simple reply White is not in time to generate real threats. }
8... exd4
{ Note that  8...Nge7  9.Qa4  is problematic. After  9...exd4  there is  10.Qxa5   while in the line  8...Nge7  9.Qa4  Bxf3  10.gxf3  a6  11.Bxc6  Nxc6  12.d5  b5  13.Qa3  we are missing an important  ...Nd4  resource. That's the reason we take on  d4  at this point. }
9. cxd4 Ne7
{ This has been played by correspondence players. In four Chigorin-Steinitz encounters Black played rather weak  9...Bd7 }
10. d5
{ 10.Qa4  doesn't work.  10...Bxf3  11.gxf3  a6  12.Bxc6+  Nxc6  13.d5  b5!  actually transposes to 8.Qa4 line where Black is much better. }
10... a6 11. Ba4 b5 12. dxc6 bxa4 13. Qxa4
{ White regains a pawn but ends up in a worse position. } 13... Bxf3 14. gxf3
Bb6 15. Nc3 O-O { Black has a better structure and a safer king. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21.Evans Gambit"]
[Black "Evans Gambit 6.0-0 d6 7.d4 #04"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans gambit essentially belongs to the 19th century, but White players still try it occasionally, hoping to surprise Black, so it is important to be prepared. I found a great way to obtain a promising position without having to remember a lot of lines. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. O-O
{ This slow continuation gives Black time to comfortably develop his forces. }
6... d6 7. d4 Bg4
{ 7...Nf6 is less clear because 8.dxe5 Nxe5 9.Nxe5 dxe5 10.Qb3 O-O 11.Ba3 wins the exchange. }
8. Qb3
{ Just hitting f7 and b7. This is in the spirit of this opening and the best move in the position. }
8... Bxf3
{ We don't have time to protect f7 but it's not like we have to. There are other important factors in the position. }
9. Bxf7+ Kf8 10. gxf3 exd4
{ At the moment White is still a pawn down and there is no way to do anything against black's king. White's best is to restore the material balance. }
11. Qxb7 Nge7 12. Bb3 a6 { Threatening ...Ra7 } 13. Bg5
{ The only way to save White who needs to be accurate for a few more moves. }
13... h6 { Also  13...Qe8  is interesting. } 14. Bxe7+ Nxe7 15. Bd5
{ The only move that prevents ...Bb6 and ...Ra7 } 15... c6
{ A nice way to improve our rook and get a stronger c-pawn @@StartBracket@@we get c3 pawn instead of c7!@@EndBracket@@.   15...Rb8  16.Qxa6  is not so clear. }
16. Bxc6 Rc8 17. Ba4 dxc3 18. Na3 h5
{ A crafty move, introducing the least active piece into the game via h6. Black is pressing but objectively with the best play White can keep the balance. Sample line of best play is: }
19. Qxa6 Rh6 20. Bb3 d5 21. Qd3 Qd7 22. f4 Qd6 23. Nc2 Qxf4
{ It's still a mess, but perhaps easier to play for Black. The c-pawn seems to be quite annoying. }
*

