[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans gambit essentially belongs to the 19th century, but White players still try it occasionally, hoping to surprise Black, so it is important to be prepared. I found a great way to obtain a promising position without having to remember a lot of lines. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. Qb3
{ In this position it's just a one move threat and as the analysis proves, Black gets a big advantage. }
6... Qe7
{ Here  6...Nh6  is less accurate because without ...d6 the e5 pawn might be hanging.  For example  7.d4  O-O  8.d5 }
7. d4 Nf6 8. Ba3
{ This was suggested by Jan Pinski in 'Italian Game and Evans Gambit' @@StartBracket@@Everymanchess 2005@@EndBracket@@ but it doesn't help White. }
8... d6 9. d5 Nd4 10. Qa4+
{ Pinski suggested  10.Nxd4  exd4  11.Qa4+  but he didn't mention  10...Bd7  after which  12.Qxa5  Qxe4+  13.Kd1  O-O  is completely winning for Black. Still, you may want to have a look with the engine but it's around  -4. }
10... Bd7 11. Qxa5 Nc2+ 12. Kd1 Nxa1 13. Nbd2 Ng4
{ Black starts active kingside play before White takes the knight. } 14. Rf1 f5
{ Black has excellent and easy play. } *

