[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21.Evans Gambit"]
[Black "Evans Gambit 6.d4 #04"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans gambit essentially belongs to the 19th century, but White players still try it occasionally, hoping to surprise Black, so it is important to be prepared. I found a great way to obtain a promising position without having to remember a lot of lines. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 b5
{ I believe this is a great practical choice. Black not only effortlessly achieves at least an equality, he also has a chance of throwing White completely off preparation, due to the rareness of this move. All that at a cost of returning the sacrificed pawn, which Black does in many other lines anyway. }
7. Bxb5 Nxd4
{ The point. This move would not be possible with the bishop on c4, due to Nxe5. }
8. Nxd4 exd4 9. O-O Ne7 10. cxd4 O-O
{ is just around equal. White temporarily controls the centre but it can be later challenged by Black's ... d5. }
11. Ba3
{ This was suggested by Krykun, but I don't think it's such a big deal. } 11...
Re8 { The simplest. Black walks out of the pin. } 12. Nd2 Rb8
{ Be careful.  12...Bc3?  13.Rc1  Bxd4  14.Nf3!  Bb6  15.Ne5  is lost for Black. }
13. Bc4 d5
{ This thematic break works despite it being an apparent pawn sacrifice. } 14.
Bxe7 Rxe7 15. Bxd5 Ba6 16. Nf3
{ 16.Re1?!  c6!  is worse for White in view of  17.Bxc6?  Rc7!  18.Bd5  Rb2!  , winning. This exchange sacrifice is the right way to go. }
16... Bxf1 17. Qxf1 Qe8
{ Black prepares to return the exchange for a pawn, which is the most reliable choice. }
18. Ne5 Rxe5 19. dxe5 c6 20. Bb3 Qxe5
{ White's bishop targeting f7 looks strong, but Black will soon target f2 himself. }
*

