[White "22. Halloween, Goring & other gambits after 2.Nf3"]
[Black "Scotch Gambit #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ In this chapter we will focus on early gambits starting from this position. }
3. d4
{ This position is covered in the chapters about the Scotch, but here we will have a look at some Gambit tries. }
3... exd4 4. Bc4 { This is called a Scotch Gambit. } 4... Bc5
{ 4...Nf6  is possible but that would trick us into a line of the Italian which is out of the scope of this repertoire. }
5. O-O { 5.c3  Nf6  transposes to the Italian Game } 5... d6
{ The most accurate preparing ...Bg4 and stopping any e4-e5 in case we play ...Nf6.   Immediate  5...Nf6  6.e5  actually transposes to the Max Lange Attack. }
6. c3 Bg4
{ 6...dxc3  7.Nxc3  allows White to develop freely. Let's just develop ourselves. }
7. Qb3 Bxf3 8. Bxf7+
{ Nobody likes to lose the f7 pawn with a check but that's not a problem. White is undeveloped and will be left with some weaknesses. }
8... Kf8 9. gxf3
{ 9.Bxg8?  Rxg8  10.gxf3  g5!  -+ Black's kingside attack is irresistible. }
9... Nf6 { Our king is very safe and look at White's development. } 10. Bc4 Qe8
11. Bb5
{ 11.Qxb7  is problematic for White as his queen might get trapped. This position was reached in three correspondence games. I offer a strong novelty: }
11... g5
{ Black prepares ...Rg8 and immediately goes for the kingside attack. His chances are better, e.g. }
12. Rd1 d3
{ We couldn't protect d4 so let's give the pawn but preserve control over the g1-a7 diagonal. }
13. Rxd3 Nd7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Halloween, Goring & other gambits after 2.Nf3"]
[Black "Scotch Gambit #02"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ In this chapter we will focus on early gambits starting from this position. }
3. d4
{ This position is covered in the chapters about the Scotch, but here we will have a look at some Gambit tries. }
3... exd4 4. Bc4 { This is called a Scotch Gambit. } 4... Bc5
{ 4...Nf6 is possible but that would trick us into a line of the Italian which is out of the scope of this repertoire. }
5. Ng5 { A very direct attempt and much better than 5. O-O. } 5... Nh6 6. Nxf7
{ or  6.Bxf7+  but not  6.Qh5  Qf6  and White didn't manage to deprive us from castling rights. }
6... Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+
{ With this trick White regains the sacrificed piece. } 8... g6 9. Qxc5 d5
{ Our king is a bit weak but we have a lead in the development so we try to open the game. }
10. O-O
{ 10.Qxd5?  is just bad.  10...Qxd5  11.exd5  Nb4  with a big advantage. }
10... dxe4 11. c3
{ White needs to open the game somehow.  11.Bf4  stops ...Qd6 but we have  11...Qe7 }
11... Qd6
{ Not the only move but let's try to exchange queens so that weakness of our king won't be felt. }
12. Qxd6
{ 12.Qb5  a6  , probably there are no good squares for White's queen. } 12...
cxd6 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Nc3
{ White is currently pawn down but things are really tricky and we shouldn't try to hold on to that extra pawn. }
14... Bg4
{ Playing for the activity. Note that surprisingly after  14...Re8  15.Be3  Black is busted. For instance  15...Nc2  16.Rac1  Nxe3  17.fxe3+  Kg7  18.Nd5  White is dominating and objectively winning. }
15. Nxe4 Nc2
{ Black is about to win the exchange as  16.Rb1  is met by  16...Be2  - White can get a pawn on  d6  in return and objectively it might be equal but probably it is White who needs to prove it. }
*

