1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ In this chapter we will focus on early gambits starting from this position. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ This is the Four Knights but here we will look at the Belgrade and Halloween Gambits. }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5
{ The Belgrade Gambit, which is one of the weirdest opening ideas I have seen- what are the benefits of plonking the knight on d5? I found a great antidote to this line. }
5... Nb4
{ A very concrete reply, which promises Black a slight edge in many lines. } 6.
Nxf6+ Qxf6 7. Bc4
{ That's the most popular but isn't enough to show any compensation for the missing pawn. }
7... Bc5 8. O-O d6 9. e5
{ The only way to try and justify White's play, but it doesn't work. } 9...
dxe5 10. a3
{ 10.Ng5  fails to  10...Bf5   or  10...O-O  11.a3  Na6  is good enough too  while  10.Bg5  Qf5  11.Re1  Bd6  12.c3  O-O  13.cxb4  e4  is just better for Black. }
10... Nc6 11. Ng5 h6
{ An important move. Unfortunately  11...O-O  12.Ne4  Qe7  13.Bg5  wins a piece. Now, White regains one pawn even with a check, but still he will be a one pawn down. }
12. Bxf7+ Kd8 13. Ne4 Qxf7 14. Nxc5 a5
{ Stopping any b4-counterplay. The king is safe on d8 and White has absolutely no compensation for the pawn. }
