1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ In this chapter we will focus on early gambits starting from this position. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ This is the Four Knights but here we will look at the Belgrade and Halloween Gambits. }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5
{ The Belgrade Gambit, which is one of the weirdest opening ideas I have seen- what are the benefits of plonking the knight on d5? I found a great antidote to this line. }
5... Nb4
{ A very concrete reply, which promises Black a slight edge in many lines. } 6.
Nxf6+ Qxf6 7. a3 Nc6 8. Bd3
{ Now in case of ...Bc5 White has the b4 move, so Black has to be more modest. }
8... Be7 9. O-O d6 10. Bg5 Qe6 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Bb5 Bg4
{ Black has no problems at all. We just play natural moves while White needs to be accurate. }
13. h3
{ Dubious is  13.Qxd4  Bxf3  14.Bxc6+  bxc6  15.gxf3  O-O  with slight advantage. Black has the safer king and the open b-file. }
13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 a6 15. Bxc6+ bxc6
{ We are very comfortable here. White still has to prove compensation for the pawn. }
