1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ In this chapter we will focus on early gambits starting from this position. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ This is the Four Knights but here we will look at the Belgrade and Halloween Gambits. }
4. Nxe5
{ The so-called Halloween Gambit, which is hardly an opening suited for a serious game. The sacrifice is obviously unsound and Black should be winning quite easily. }
4... Nxe5 5. d4 Ng6 6. e5 Ng8
{ It looks ugly but we don't want to give our piece back. We only suffer for one move which is a low price for a piece. }
7. Bc4 d5 { Sacrificing a pawn to fasten the piece development. } 8. Bxd5 N8e7
9. Bg5 { White also develops fast but he is far from creating a real threat. }
9... c6 10. Bb3 h6 11. Ne4 hxg5 12. Nd6+ Kd7 13. Nxf7 Qa5+
{ 13...Qe8  also wins. } 14. c3 Rh6
{ Not the only move but this is the strongest. If White takes on h6 our structure gets improved. Our plan is ...Kc7 and some ...Bf5, we are just too much material up. }
