1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ In this chapter we will focus on early gambits starting from this position. }
3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4
{ An attempt to transpose into the Max Lange Attack after 5...exd4 6.e5. However, Black can simply capture the pawn with the bishop, achieving a better game. }
5... Bxd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4
{ It is important not to fall into White's trap: 8...g5? 9.f4! } 8... d6 9. f4
Bg4 { Black initiates a forcing sequence. } 10. Bxf6 Bxd1 11. Bxd8 Rxd8 12.
Rxd1 Nxc2 { All forced. } 13. Nc3 Nxa1 14. Rxa1
{ We have a rook and two pawns for two minor pieces. That's generally more less an equivalent, but we are isolating White's e-pawn and his minor pieces don't have great outposts. }
14... exf4 15. Nd5 Kd7 { just preparing ...Rhe8 to attack e4. } 16. Nxf4 Rhe8
17. Bd3 Re5
{ Black is a bit better but of course with the best play White can hold. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Halloween, Goring & other gambits after 2.Nf3"]
[Black "Max Lange attempt #04"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ In this chapter we will focus on early gambits starting from this position. }
3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4
{ An attempt to transpose into the Max Lange Attack after 5...exd4 6.e5. However, Black can simply capture the pawn with the bishop, achieving a better game. }
5... Bxd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. f4
{ That's the most popular, but probably not so good. } 7... d6 8. fxe5 dxe5 9.
Bg5
{ White's play may be appealing at first, but the compensation is not enough for a full pawn. }
9... Qe7
{ Black threatens ...Qc5 and prepares a long castle.   Less accurate is  9...Qd6  because of  10.c3  and exchange of queens. }
10. c3 { Forcing the issues is counterproductive. } 10... Ne6 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12.
Na3 Nf4 { a great place for our knight. } 13. Kh1 h5
{ Preparing 14...h4, cementing the knight on f4. Then Black can follow with ...Bd7 and ...0-0-0. White not only doesn't have a compensation but his position is miserable. }
*

