1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ In this chapter we will focus on early gambits starting from this position. }
3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4
{ An attempt to transpose into the Max Lange Attack after 5...exd4 6.e5. However, Black can simply capture the pawn with the bishop, achieving a better game. }
5... Bxd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. f4
{ That's the most popular, but probably not so good. } 7... d6 8. fxe5 dxe5 9.
Bg5
{ White's play may be appealing at first, but the compensation is not enough for a full pawn. }
9... Qe7
{ Black threatens ...Qc5 and prepares a long castle. Less accurate is 9...Qd6 because of 10.c3 and exchange of queens. }
10. Na3 Rg8 { Preparing to occupy the g-file after an eventual Bxf6. } 11. Qd3
Bd7 12. Qg3 Qc5
{ An important move with a tempo @@StartBracket@@threat ...Ne2+@@EndBracket@@ to protect e5 from the side.   To understand this better let's see what happens after  12...O-O-O  13.c3  - now desirable move  13...Ne6  drops the pawn  14.Qxe5  and  13...Nc6  14.Qh4  allows White to come close to equality. }
13. Kh1 O-O-O 14. Bxf7 Rgf8
{ White restored material equilibrium but his position is much worse, mainly due to terribly placed knight on a3. Sample game went: }
15. Bd5 c6 16. Bxf6 Rxf6 17. Rxf6 gxf6 18. Bb3 Nxb3 19. axb3 Qd4 20. Nc4 Be6
21. Ne3 Qxe4 22. Rxa7 Qd4 23. Ra8+ Kc7 24. Rxd8 Kxd8 25. Qf2 Ke7 26. c3 Qe4
{ Black retained a big edge in the endgame in Tucci-Lounek, email 2009 } *

