1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ In this chapter we will focus on early gambits starting from this position. }
3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4
{ An attempt to transpose into the Max Lange Attack after 5...exd4 6.e5. However, Black can simply capture the pawn with the bishop, achieving a better game. }
5... Bxd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. f4
{ That's the most popular, but probably not so good. } 7... d6 8. fxe5 dxe5 9.
Bg5
{ White's play may be appealing at first, but the compensation is not enough for a full pawn. }
9... Qe7
{ Black threatens ...Qc5 and prepares a long castle. Less accurate is 9...Qd6 because of 10.c3 and exchange of queens. }
10. Na3 Rg8 { Preparing to occupy the g-file after an eventual Bxf6. } 11. Kh1
{ The most popular move. } 11... Bd7 12. Qe1 O-O-O 13. Qf2
{ White is about to regain the pawn but it's not enough to equalize. } 13...
Be6
{ Making an active move once we are coordinated. As you are going to see it works very well for us. }
14. c3
{ If  14.Bxf6  gxf6  15.Qxf6  Qxf6  16.Rxf6  Rg4  works great for Black too. }
14... Nc6 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Qxf6 Qxf6 17. Rxf6
{ Black doesn't have time for any ...Rd2 but there is something much stronger. }
17... Bxc4 18. Nxc4 Rg4
{ Black will take on e4 and has undeniable initiative in the endgame. Sample line is: }
19. Kg1
{ First of all  19.Re1  Rxe4!  and  19.Rxf7  Rxe4  20.b3  b5  21.Na3  a6  Black threatens  ...Rd2  or  ...Rd3  with a huge advantage. }
19... Rxe4 20. b3 Rd3 21. Rc1
{ 21.Rxf7  b5  22.Na3  a6  and with rooks coming to the 2nd rank Black has a devastating attack. }
21... Nd8 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Ponziani Opening"]
[Black "Ponziani Opening 4.Bb5 #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This is the Ponziani Opening, one of the oldest chess openings. White just wants to build a strong centre with d4, but of course we will try to stop it. }
3... d5
{ A logical continuation fighting for the centre. As we will see, some of the lines are quite sharp and forcing but these usually are objectively very good for us. }
4. Bb5
{ Surprisingly enough, this bad move is White's second most popular try. Black should be more than happy to see it appear on the board. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe5 Qg5
{ The kingside attack is more important than White's pin. } 6. d4 Qxg2 7. Rf1
Bd6 { It's important to know White's not winning a piece here. } 8. Nxc6 Bd7 9.
Nxa7 c6 { Black not only regains a piece but White's position is in ruins. } *

