1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This is the Ponziani Opening, one of the oldest chess openings. White just wants to build a strong centre with d4, but of course we will try to stop it. }
3... d5
{ A logical continuation fighting for the centre. As we will see, some of the lines are quite sharp and forcing but these usually are objectively very good for us. }
4. Bb5
{ Surprisingly enough, this bad move is White's second most popular try. Black should be more than happy to see it appear on the board. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe5 Qg5
{ The kingside attack is more important than White's pin. } 6. Qa4 Qxg2 7.
Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Qxc6+ Kd8 9. Rf1
{ All forced and Black is winning but he has to allow White to capture on a8 with a check. }
9... Bh3 { Once we take on f1 White's position is collapsing. } 10. Qxa8+ Ke7
{ There is no way to protect f1. } 11. Kd1
{ 11.Nc6  can be met by  11...Kd6  or just  11...Kf6  12.Qd8+  Kg6!  when White doesn't have good checks and the rook on  f1  falls }
11... Qxf1+ 12. Kc2 Nh6
{ Preparing ...f6 or ...Kf6. Both moves wouldn't be good right away because of b3 and Qxf8 respectively. Black is winning. The critical variation runs as follows: }
13. Qc6 f6 14. Qxc7+ Ke6 15. d4 fxe5 16. Qxe5+ Kf7 17. Bxh6 Qd3+ 18. Kc1 gxh6
19. Qh5+ Kf6 20. Qe5+ Kg6 21. Qxh8 Qf1+ 22. Kc2 Qxf2+ 23. Nd2 e3 24. Rg1+ Kh5
25. Qe5+ Bf5+ 26. Kb3 exd2 27. Rd1 Kg6 *

