1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This is the Ponziani Opening, one of the oldest chess openings. White just wants to build a strong centre with d4, but of course we will try to stop it. }
3... d5
{ A logical continuation fighting for the centre. As we will see, some of the lines are quite sharp and forcing but these usually are objectively very good for us. }
4. exd5 Qxd5
{ Like in the Sicilian Alapin, White can't gain a tempo with Nc3. } 5. d4 Nf6
{ Black enjoys free development and only White can be worried about his position. }
6. Be3 Bf5 { It will be clear soon why the bishop is good on f5. } 7. Be2
{ Now White is ready for dxe5. } 7... exd4 8. cxd4 Bxb1
{ Taking the chance to deprive White from castling rights. } 9. Qxb1 Bb4+ 10.
Kf1 O-O-O { White's king is misplaced and his isolated pawn hurts. } *

