4. Qa4 { The main move. } 4... f6
{ That looks ugly but there was no convenient way to protect e5. } 5. d3
{ This passive move gives Black a free hand to comfortably deploy his forces. However it's not that bad and can lead to original play with chances for both sides. }
5... Be6 6. Be2 Ne7 7. O-O a6
{ A nice little flexible move that discourages Nbd2-b3 as we have ...b5. Black will continue with ...Qd7 @@StartBracket@@or ...Qd6 in some cases!@@EndBracket@@, ...0-0-0 and also pushing pawns on the starting with ...g5 is an idea. This position has been tested in correspondence play and the conclusion is clear: White has to be more accurate to maintain equality. Black player does not need to know much, as the position is very easy to play. }
8. Rd1 d4
{ Taking control of more space and rendering the d1-rook passive. The position is equal. Sample line goes: }
9. cxd4 exd4 10. a3 Ng6 11. b4 Be7 12. Nbd2 O-O *

