1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This is the Ponziani Opening, one of the oldest chess openings. White just wants to build a strong centre with d4, but of course we will try to stop it. }
3... d5
{ A logical continuation fighting for the centre. As we will see, some of the lines are quite sharp and forcing but these usually are objectively very good for us. }
4. Qa4 { The main move. } 4... f6
{ That looks ugly but there was no convenient way to protect e5. } 5. Bb5
{ White is playing only for tricks. } 5... Ne7 6. exd5 Qxd5 7. d4 e4 8. c4
{ That's probably bad but the objectively stronger  8.Ng1  doesn't make much sense. }
8... Qh5
{ By analogy with the main line, this retreat sets White difficult problems }
9. Ng1 a6 10. Ne2 axb5 { A powerful temporary exchange sacrifice. } 11. Qxa8
Nb4
{ Objectively Black is much better, maybe even winning but of course it might be quite challenging to find the best moves over the board. Still, you shouldn't try to remember long lines in rare systems. Illustrative line goes: }
12. Nf4 Qf5 13. O-O Nc2 14. Na3 Nxa1 15. Nxb5 { 15.Be3  Ng6!  -+ } 15... Kf7
16. d5 Nc2 17. Qa4 Ng6 18. Ne6 Nb4 19. Nxf8 Nh4 20. Ne6 Qg4 21. g3 Nf3+ 22. Kg2
Nd3 *

