1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This is the Ponziani Opening, one of the oldest chess openings. White just wants to build a strong centre with d4, but of course we will try to stop it. }
3... d5
{ A logical continuation fighting for the centre. As we will see, some of the lines are quite sharp and forcing but these usually are objectively very good for us. }
4. Qa4 { The main move. } 4... f6
{ That looks ugly but there was no convenient way to protect e5. } 5. Bb5
{ White is playing only for tricks. } 5... Ne7 6. exd5 Qxd5 7. O-O
{ This whole line is just objectively bad but that's how people play. } 7... e4
8. c4
{ Surprisingly, this natural move already turns out to be a decisive mistake. }
8... Qh5 { The least popular of queen retreats, but also the best one! } 9. Re1
{ This was White's idea all long. However, a computer analysis proves it to be completely mistaken. }
9... exf3
{ This is weak according to D.Taylor & K.Hayward - 'Play the Ponziani' @@StartBracket@@Everymanchess 2009@@EndBracket@@, but analysis prove White is lost here. }
10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qxc6+ Kd8 12. Qxa8 c6
{ Cutting off the queen and threatening ...Qg4. Black wins by force in all variations. }
13. Re3 Nf5 14. Qxc6 Nd4 15. Rd3 Bc5 16. Na3 Re8
{ All Black's pieces are joining the party. } 17. Nc2 Qg6
{ A powerful sequence. We give up the strong pawn on f3 but once we hide our king the attack will be irresistible. }
18. Qxf3 Kc7 19. Qf4+ Re5 20. Rxd4 Qxc2
{ White is virtually playing without his bishop and a rook sitting on the first rank. }
21. h4 g5 { opening files before cashing in. } 22. hxg5 Bxd4 23. Qxd4
{ This leads to a forced mate but otherwise we are just some material up and winning anyway. }
23... Qd1+ 24. Kh2 Qh5+ 25. Kg3 Rxg5+ *

