1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit was the most popular opening of the Romantic Era of chess. Nearly all the best players of the 19th century played it with both colours, producing a number of highly interesting and spectacular games. However, since the positional school chess came to the fore, its popularity has been steadily declining. In the recent decade, modern computers dealt an additional blow to the King's Gambit's reputation, showing that White's compensation is hardly sufficient when faced with precise play from Black. White will struggle to even equalize. Nevertheless, one will occasionally face a King's Gambit aficionado or an opponent trying to use the opening as a surprise weapon, so it is important to be at least basically prepared for it. }
2... exf4 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Schallop Defence, which is the fifth most popular of Black's replies. The basis for this recommendation is simple. Compared to 3.... g5 or 3....d6 Black does not need to learn many variations here and still achieves an excellent position in all of the lines. }
4. e5 Nh5
{ The knight may seem awkward on h5, but plays an important role defending the f4 pawn, and, as we will see, after ...g5 it can be transferred via g7 to very good squares, namely e6 or f5. }
5. d4 d5
{ 5...d6 is also fully playable and it's even hard to tell which one is better. One way or the other Black emerges with a better position out of the opening. Note that in the line 5.Be2 g5 6.O-O h6 7.d4 we preferred 7...d6 but now White is less developed so 6.c4 will be less dangerous. }
6. c4
{ White has to play very energetically not to end up a pawn down for nothing. }
6... g5 7. g4 { The only move keeping White afloat. } 7... Ng7
{ The pawn is poisoned for now:  7...Bxg4?  8.Rg1  and White takes over the initiative. }
8. Nc3 dxc4
{ We would prefer to make this move after the white bishop moves, but the pressure on d5 forces us to take immediately. }
9. Bxc4 Bxg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. h4
{ Again, White stays in the game only by playing a very accurate sequence. }
11... Nc6 { Attacking the weak d4-point. } 12. Nd5 Be7 13. hxg5 Bg4
{ The bishop was unstable on h5. } 14. Bxf4 Qd7
{ Black is ready to attack White's overextended centre with ... 0-0-0, ...Ne6 etc. }
