{ This move, according to John Shaw, an author of a massive book on the King's Gambit, is the refutation of the Bishop's Gambit. By 'refutation' he doesn't mean that Black wins, but that he achieves a better position in all variations. I think he is right in principle, but many of the specific lines he included in his book can be improved upon. }
4. Nf3
{ It's difficult to say that already this natural move is dubious but in fact this is the case. Black has a relatively simple way to obtain a really big advantage. }
4... g5 5. O-O Bg7 6. d4 d6 7. c3 h6 8. g3
{ This is based on one trick which just doesn't work. } 8... fxg3
{ 8...Bh3  is also good, but unnecessary. } 9. Bxf7+
{ This sacrifice may seem tempting, but it simply loses by force. } 9... Kxf7
10. Ne5+ Ke7 { Of course not  10....Ke8??  11.Qh5+  and mate. } 11. Rf7+ Ke8
12. Qh5
{ It all looks dangerous but you shouldn't be afraid if it's just winning for Black. }
12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Bg4 { the key trick which allows the king to escape. } 14.
Qg6 Ne7 15. Qxg7 gxh2+
{ Don't forget to take the pawn with a check! This move could have been inserted earlier too. }
16. Kxh2 Kd7 { White is busted. } *

