1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit was the most popular opening of the Romantic Era of chess. Nearly all the best players of the 19th century played it with both colours, producing a number of highly interesting and spectacular games. However, since the positional school chess came to the fore, its popularity has been steadily declining. In the recent decade, modern computers dealt additional blow to the King's Gambit's reputation, showing that White's compensation is hardly sufficient and faced with precise Black's play, White will struggle to even equalize. Nevertheless, one will occasionally face a King's Gambit aficionado or an opponent trying to use the opening as a surprise weapon, so it is important to be at least basically prepared for it. }
2... exf4 3. Qf3
{ This is too provocative. Black will get a lot of tempi attacking the queen. }
3... Nc6 4. Qxf4 Bd6 5. Qe3 Nf6 6. d4 O-O 7. Bd3
{ Of course White's position will collapse after  7.e5  Re8 } 7... Ng4
{ Black's huge lead in development allows him to play a series of strong tempo moves. }
8. Qh3 Bb4+ { Unblocking the d-pawn in order to develop more pieces. } 9. c3 d5
{ A good illustration of the importance of dynamics in chess. Black brings one piece after another into the attack, not giving White the time to gain material. }
10. exd5 { 10.cxb4  loses simply to  10...Nf2 } 10... Nf6 11. Qh4 Qxd5
{ Now g2 is hanging and White again doesn't have time to capture the bishop. }
12. Ne2 Bf5
{ The key move of the whole variation. Black disables castling for White. Needless to say  12...Qxg2?  13.Rg1  is wrong. }
13. Bxf5 Qxf5 14. Qf2 { After  14.cxb4?  Nxb4  White has no defence. } 14...
Qxf2+ 15. Kxf2 Bd6
{ It may seem that White has succeeded in simplifying to a holdable queenless middlegame, but in fact he still faces serious problems due to his lag in development and the exposed position of his king, e.g. }
16. Bf4 Rae8 17. Bxd6 Ne4+ 18. Kf3 cxd6
{ Black takes back with the pawn to keep the d2-square under control. } *

