[Black "King's Gambit 3.d4 #02"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit was the most popular opening of the Romantic Era of chess. Nearly all the best players of the 19th century played it with both colours, producing a number of highly interesting and spectacular games. However, since the positional school chess came to the fore, its popularity has been steadily declining. In the recent decade, modern computers dealt additional blow to the King's Gambit's reputation, showing that White's compensation is hardly sufficient and faced with precise Black's play, White will struggle to even equalize. Nevertheless, one will occasionally face a King's Gambit aficionado or an opponent trying to use the opening as a surprise weapon, so it is important to be at least basically prepared for it. }
2... exf4 3. d4 { Another dodgy idea. } 3... Qh4+
{ Of course, Black should grab the opportunity to dislocate White's king, especially as he is forced to go to the tragically bad e2-square. }
4. Ke2
{ Obviously 4.g3 fxg3 5.Nf3 g2 wins for Black, but in the early days of European chess there was an interesting rule that the king move like a knight once a game. So this was in fact a curious gambit 5...g2 could be met by 6.Kxg2 and 5...Qxe4 was also met by 6.Kg2! Fortunately, this rule was abandoned long time ago. }
4... Qe7 5. Kf2
{ This is actually White's best move but obviously Black is better. } 5... d5
{ Black immediately opens the position in order to exploit the weak position of White's king. }
6. exd5 Qh4+ 7. Ke2 Bg4+ 8. Nf3 Nd7 9. Bxf4
{ For the better or worse, White has to take this pawn. Now a sequence of forcing moves follows: }
9... Bxf3+ 10. Kxf3 Bd6 11. Qe2+ Ne7 12. Bxd6 cxd6 13. Qe4
{ Understandably, White wants to exchange queens, to which Black is obviously opposed due to the weak position of the white king. }
13... Qh5+ 14. Qg4 Qxd5+ 15. Qe4 Qh5+ 16. Qg4 Qa5
{ Not the best square, but declining the queen exchange is worth it. } 17. Nc3
h5 18. Qe4 Rh6
{ The rook lift along the 6th rank smells like trouble for White. } *

