[White "27. Bishop's Opening (2.Bc4)"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening 4.Nf3 #03"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ The Bishop's Opening has recently been gaining in popularity, mainly as a means of avoiding the Petroff Defence. }
2... Nf6 3. d3 c6
{ I believe Black should take the opportunity to grab space in the centre. This way, he can fight for more than equality. }
4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 a5 { Softening up the bishop on b3. } 6. a4 Bb4+
{ This provokes 7.c3 and Black is arguing that this extra move is actually counterproductive as he can't develop the knight to c3. 6...Bd6 is playable but 7.exd5 cxd5 8.Bg5 Be6 9.Nc3 is maybe equal but somehow easier for White. }
7. c3
{ 7.Nc3 d4 loses a piece and moves like 7.Nbd2 or 7. Bd2 don't pose any problems. Black has a good development and nice centre. No further knowledge is required in this case. }
7... Bd6 8. exd5 cxd5 9. Bg5 Be6 10. Na3
{ Thanks to 6...Bb4+ as we can see, White can't put more pressure on d5 with Nc3. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nb5 Bb8
{ The bishop might look strange on b8 but it doesn't even block the rook which can be developed via 6th rank. }
12. d4
{ This move is recommended By Alexander Delchev in 'Bc4 against the Open Games' @@StartBracket@@New In Chess 2018@@EndBracket@@. }
12... e4 13. Nd2 h6 14. Bh4 Bf4
{ We put the bishop on the optimal square and we don't castle yet because we are not sure if we want to play ...g5, ...Kf8 and ...Kg7 in some lines.   Still,  14...O-O  is not a bad move of course. }
15. Nf1 g5 16. Bg3 Kf8
{ A complicated battle lies ahead, in which both sides' chances are approximately equal, e.g. }
17. Bxf4 gxf4 18. Qd2 Nh5 19. g3 Nb6
{ is totally fine, e.g.  20.O-O-O  Bd7!  with better prospects. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Bishop's Opening (2.Bc4)"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening 4.Nf3 #04"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ The Bishop's Opening has recently been gaining in popularity, mainly as a means of avoiding the Petroff Defence. }
2... Nf6 3. d3 c6
{ I believe Black should take the opportunity to grab space in the centre. This way, he can fight for more than equality. }
4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 a5 { Softening up the bishop on b3. } 6. a4 Bb4+
{ This provokes 7.c3 and Black is arguing that this extra move is actually counterproductive as he can't develop the knight to c3. 6...Bd6 is playable but 7.exd5 cxd5 8.Bg5 Be6 9.Nc3 is maybe equal but somehow easier for White. }
7. c3
{ 7.Nc3 d4 loses a piece and moves like 7.Nbd2 or 7. Bd2 don't pose any problems. Black has a good development and nice centre. No further knowledge is required in this case. }
7... Bd6 8. exd5 cxd5 9. Bg5 Be6 10. Na3
{ Thanks to 6...Bb4+ as we can see, White can't put more pressure on d5 with Nc3. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nb5 Bb8
{ The bishop might look strange on b8 but it doesn't even block the rook which can be developed via 6th rank. }
12. d4
{ This move is recommended By Alexander Delchev in 'Bc4 against the Open Games' @@StartBracket@@New In Chess 2018@@EndBracket@@. }
12... e4 13. Nd2 h6 14. Bh4 Bf4
{ We put the bishop on the optimal square and we don't castle yet because we are not sure if we want to play ...g5, ...Kf8 and ...Kg7 in some lines. Still, 14...0-0 is not a bad move of course. }
15. Nf1 g5 16. Bg3 Kf8
{ A complicated battle lies ahead, in which both sides' chances are approximately equal, e.g. }
17. Bxf4 gxf4 18. Qd2 Nh5 19. Bd1 Ndf6 20. g3 Ra6 21. c4
{ Kravtsiv cites a game Williamson-Riccio, email 2018, which I couldn't find. Nevertheless, Black is more than fine after }
21... Rc6 22. c5 Bh3
{ Black has stabilized the centre and has nice kingside prospects. Nd6 is always met by a strong exchange sacrifice. }
*

