[White "27. Bishop's Opening (2.Bc4)"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening 4.Nf3 #08"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ The Bishop's Opening has recently been gaining in popularity, mainly as a means of avoiding the Petroff Defence. }
2... Nf6 3. d3 c6
{ I believe Black should take the opportunity to grab space in the centre. This way, he can fight for more than equality. }
4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 a5 { Softening up the bishop on b3. } 6. a4 Bb4+
{ This provokes 7.c3 and Black is arguing that this extra move is actually counterproductive as he can't develop the knight to c3. 6...Bd6 is playable but 7.exd5 cxd5 8.Bg5 Be6 9.Nc3 is maybe equal but somehow easier for White. }
7. c3
{ 7.Nc3 d4 loses a piece and moves like 7.Nbd2 or 7. Bd2 don't pose any problems. Black has a good development and nice centre. No further knowledge is required in this case. }
7... Bd6 8. exd5 cxd5 9. Bg5 Be6 10. Na3
{ Thanks to 6...Bb4+ as we can see, White can't put more pressure on d5 with Nc3. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nb5 Bb8
{ The bishop might look strange on b8 but it doesn't even block the rook which can be developed via 6th rank. }
12. O-O O-O 13. Re1 h6 14. Bh4 Re8 15. Nd2
{ This White's critical idea, planning 16.d4 e4 17.c4. After other moves Black can continue strengthening his centre 15...Ra6, with no problems whatsoever. }
15... Ra6 { The rook needs to be activated via the 6th rank. } 16. d4 e4 17. c4
dxc4 18. Bxc4 Bxc4 19. Nxc4 Nb6
{ We need to untangle and either exchange some pieces or play ...Nbd5 to improve our position. }
20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21. Ne3
{ This position was reached only once over the board, in Wang Yue-Yu Yangyi, Shenzen 2016. The correct path for Black has been established in correspondence play: }
21... Qg6
{ Planning ...f5 and expanding on the kingside where we have more pawns. } 22.
Rc1 { 22.Qb3  Kh7  23.Rac1  f5  transposes. } 22... f5
{ Black has nice attacking prospects. } 23. Qb3+ Kh7 24. g3 f4 25. Ng2 Nd7 26.
Nc7 Rb6 27. Qd5 fxg3 28. fxg3 Bxc7 29. Rxc7 Rd6 30. Qxb7 Qf6 31. Rxe4 Rb6 32.
Qd5 Rd6 { The game ends in a repetition. } *

