[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28. Vienna, Glek etc. (2.Nc3)"]
[Black "Delayed Bishop's Opening #01"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ This is the starting point of this chapter. With the 2.Nc3 White can opt for three different setups: 1@@EndBracket@@ Some kind of delayed Bishop's Opening with Bc4 2@@EndBracket@@ The Glek Opening with g3 3@@EndBracket@@ Vienna Gambit with f4. }
2... Nc6
{ 2...Nf6  is much more popular but we want to have ...f5 move against the Glek Opening. }
3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3
{ The only independent try. Much more popular 4.Nf3 just transposes to Four Knights with 4.Bc4. }
4... Na5 { Just going for the important bishop. } 5. Bb3 Nxb3 6. axb3 d5 7. Bg5
{ It may seem White puts some pressure but it is Black who takes over the initiative. }
7... d4 8. Nd5 Qd6 { Forcing White to capture on f6. } 9. Nxf6+
{ 9.Bxf6  gxf6  10.Qf3  f5  is much better for Black but it's quite messy.   From theoretical point of view there is no point in analysing such lines in details as they are not likely to occur and also the best moves can be worked out over the board. Still, it might be entertaining as well as educative to analyse it further. }
9... gxf6 10. Bh4 Rg8
{ The pawn on g2 is not hanging @@StartBracket@@our rook could be trapped by Bg3@@EndBracket@@ but it's still a useful move. }
11. Nf3 Bg4
{ With ...a6 and long castle. Black is just better with more space and White's bishop is very bad. }
*

