{ The only independent try. Much more popular 4.Nf3 just transposes to Four Knights with 4.Bc4. }
4... Na5 { Just going for the important bishop. } 5. Qf3
{ Amateur's looking attempt but it was favored by many excellent players @@StartBracket@@although mainly in faster time controls@@EndBracket@@. Once our knight went to a5 we can't play ...Nd4 so there is some logic behind it. }
5... Be7 { Let's just finish our development. } 6. Nge2 O-O 7. O-O d6 8. h3
Nxc4
{ We just take the bishop but note that not in all lines we actually do this. }
9. dxc4 Be6 10. b3
{ 10.Nd5  Nxd5  11.cxd5  Bd7  White's structure has been improved but with the bishop pair and possible  ...f5  we have a good game. }
10... Nd7 11. Ng3 Bg5
{ We are lacking some space so we are happy to trade more pieces. Compared to 5.Nge2 the plan of ...g6 and ...f5 gains in strength because with the queen on f3 White lacks the f4 counter resource. Also note that if White omits castling he would have a dangerous plan of Bxg5 Qxg5 h4 followed by kingside aggression. }
*

