1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ This is the starting point of this chapter. With the 2.Nc3 White can opt for three different setups: 1@@EndBracket@@ Some kind of delayed Bishop's Opening with Bc4 2@@EndBracket@@ The Glek Opening with g3 3@@EndBracket@@ Vienna Gambit with f4. }
2... Nc6
{ 2...Nf6 is much more popular but we want to have ...f5 move against the Glek Opening. }
3. f4
{ This looks like a version of the King's Gambit but it's actually called the Vienna Gambit. It's probably objectively a dodgy line and Black can come out on top. }
3... exf4 4. d4 Qh4+ 5. Ke2 f5
{ My novelty. Black immediately strikes at White's centre, posing him unpleasant problems. }
6. Nf3 Qe7 7. e5 d6
{ Let's just open some lines. Playing 7...g5 would be too much. } 8. Nd5 Qf7 9.
Nxf4 dxe5 10. dxe5 Bd7
{ We are planning to castle long. The position is still messy and White has a way to force issues but it's not like you have to remember everything. You need to know the position is good and think over the board. Especially in rare lines we can't check and memorize too much. The illustrative forcing line goes: }
11. e6
{ The best move. Otherwise Black would be much better after 11...0-0-0. Now a long forcing sequence begins: }
11... Bxe6 12. Ng5 Bc4+ 13. Kf3 Ne5+ 14. Kf2 Bc5+ 15. Ke1 Qe7 16. Bxc4 Nxc4+
17. Nfe6 h6 18. Qe2 hxg5 19. Bxg5 Nf6 20. Qxc4 Kf7 21. Bxf6 Qxe6+ 22. Qxe6+
Kxe6
{ The tactical skirmish results in an endgame where Black keeps a serious initiative. }
*

