[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29. Centre Game (2.d4) & Others"]
[Black "Scholar's Mate attempt"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Qh5
{ Of course, when you face a move like this, this is most likely a psychological trick by your opponent. Don't fall for it and try to punish him immediately. Just apply common sense. }
2... Nc6 3. Bc4 g6 { Don't fall for the Scholar's Mate with  3...Nf6  4.Qxf7 }
4. Qf3 Nf6 5. Ne2 Bg7
{ Black has a nice development but 2. Qh5 is not all that terrible. We equalize comfortably but unlike in many other strange systems we don't have advantage yet. Sample variation you may want to look at: }
6. d3 d6 7. Nbc3 Nb4
{ This immediate action is just one of many ways to continue. } 8. Bb3 Bg4 9.
Qg3 Be6 10. a3 Bxb3 11. axb4 Bxc2 12. Ra3
{ Stopping ...Bb3. This is White's only move. } 12... a5 13. bxa5 b5 14. axb6
c6
{ Black should soon regain the pawn. Note that any Be3 to protect it falls into ...Bxd3. }
*

