1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4
{ Centre Game is a strange opening choice. White loses an important tempo in the opening and develops his pieces awkwardly. Black can successfully fight for more than equality. }
3... Nc6 4. Qe3 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 { Just developing actively. } 6. Bd2 O-O 7.
O-O-O Re8 8. Qg3
{ White gets out of the pin and if he manages to play f3 his position is actually quite nice. We have to accept the sacrifice. }
8... Nxe4 9. Nxe4 Rxe4 10. c3 { This is just bad. } 10... Be7 11. f4
{ Better is  11.Bd3  Bh4  12.Qf3  Re8  but White has no compensation for the pawn. }
11... d5 12. Bd3 Bf5
{ This strong exchange sacrifice basically refutes White's whole concept of play. }
13. Nf3 Qd7 14. Bxe4 Bxe4 15. Be3 Na5
{ Black is not only dominating the light squares but there is a serious attack coming against White's king. Sample game went: }
16. Bd4 Bf8 17. b3 Qb5 18. Kb2 c5 19. Be5 Nc4+ 20. Ka1 Ne3
{ Black soon won in Rudd-Avrukh, 2010 } *

