[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Sutovsky, Emil vs. Malakhov, Vladimir"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Be7
{ We are at the starting position of the Rio de Janeiro Variation of the Berlin Defense. The origin of the name is mysterious, since in databases you will find only one game in this line played in the Brazilian city more than 100 years after the variation's birth @@StartBracket@@Tal-Panno, 1987@@EndBracket@@. In fact, it is one of the oldest variations known in chess and was upheld by such household names as Steinitz, Anderssen, Lasker, Tarrasch, Pilsburry, Reti, Smyslov, Spassky and others. However, in the 21th century, following the trend set by Kasparov-Kramnik 2000 World Championship match it has given way to l'Hermit Variation: 5...Nd6, leading to the famous Berlin Endgame @@StartBracket@@also called 'Berlin Wall'@@EndBracket@@ Thanks to an overwhelming popularity of 5....Nd6 nowadays, it is very probable that your fifth move: 5... Be7 will already come as a surprise to a majority of White players. If you are already a mainstream Berlin player, it can serve as a great alternative line. However, this line is not only an excellent surprise weapon. After analysing it thoroughly, I am confident that it is solid enough to be used as a main weapon even against high-level opposition. }
6. Qe2 Nd6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. dxe5 Nb7
{ This is the main position of the Rio de Janeiro Variation, which has been established as White's best chance for an advantage. White has numerous tries here and before examining them, it is important to understand the general features of the position. In my view, the key to its understanding lies in realization that Black's light square bishop is the most important piece on the board. While temporarily buried on c8, it has the potential to become a powerful piece, if developed along the b1-h7 or h1-a8 diagonal. If Black deploys it comfortably, in conjunction with putting his knight on an excellent e6 square, his pieces will enjoy remarkable harmony and he will hardly ever be worse. On the contrary, he will acquire great chances of taking over the initiative. If, however, White succeeds in restricting its development, he will be able to develop play against Black's structural weaknesses and force him to passive defence.    Having understood this, it is easy to predict both sides' plans. Black will try to play ...d5 with further ...Bf5 or ...Bb7 and .. .c5 on the cards. White's main idea will be to deny his opponent this possibility and he has 3 main ways to do so: early Re1, intending exd6 after .. .d5, forcing an undesirable ...Bxd6 due to an attack on the e7 bishop; early Nd4, putting c6 under attack; or early c4, intending to take control of the d5 square with Nc3 and Rd1. However, I believe Black has enough resources to meet any of these plans and achieve a fair share of chances. Enough of this lengthy introduction, let's study concrete variations! }
9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 d5 11. c4 Nc5 12. Nc3
{ 12.Rd1  This is the critical move, after which my recommendation is  12...Qe8!  13.cxd5  cxd5  14.Rxd5  Ba6  15.Qe3  Ne6=∞  with great compensation. }
12... dxc4 13. Rfd1
{ 13.bxc4  runs into  13...Qd3!   13.Rad1  Qe8  14.bxc4  f5!  15.Ba3  It is advisable for White to exchange the dark-squared bishops, because otherwise he would be just worse after ...Ne6.  15...Ne6  16.Bxe7  Qxe7= }
13... Qe8 14. Qxc4 Ba6
{ 14...a5  would transpose to the position I recommended for Black after 12.Rd1 Qe8 13. Nc3 - see here. However, the text move also leads to a perfectly fine play for Black. }
15. Qg4 f5 { A thematic strike. } 16. exf6
{ 16.Qb4  would lead to an interesting play.  16...Nd3  17.Qa5  Nxb2  18.Rdb1  Bb7  19.Rxb2  c5!  Black sacrifices a pawn in order to weaken White's king's position.  20.Qxc7  Bxf3  21.gxf3  Qg6+  22.Kh1  Qh5  23.Qc6  Rab8  Black has adequate compensation for the pawn, e.g.  24.Rd1  Kh8  25.f4  Rb4  26.Rd7  Re4!  27.Nxe4  Qf3+  28.Kg1  fxe4  29.Rxe7  Qd1+  30.Kg2  Qf3+= }
16... Bxf6 17. Rab1 h5
{ 17...Nd3  18.Ba1  Rb8⩱  threatening ...Rb4 would have offered Black slightly better chances. }
18. Qf5 Nd3
{ If he had wanted to, Black could have forced a draw:   18...Bxc3  19.Qxc5  Bxb2  20.Rxb2  Rxf3  21.gxf3  Qg6+  22.Kh1  Qf6  23.Kg1  Qg6+= }
19. Qa5 Qc8 20. Bc1 Bxc3 21. Qxc3 Qf5
{ Black could have sacrificed an exchange, with a probable draw, e.g.   21...Rxf3  22.gxf3  Qe6  23.Be3  Rd8  24.Qa5  c5  25.Qxc7  Rd6  26.h4  Ne5  27.Qxd6  Nxf3+  28.Kg2  Nxh4+  29.Kg1  Nf3+= }
22. Be3 c5 23. b4 cxb4 24. Qc6
{ this move only forces the black bishop to a better square and White starts experiencing problems. }
24... Bb5 25. Qxc7 Rf7 26. Qg3 Ba4 27. Rd2
{ A blunder.  It was necessary to play   27.Rf1  a5∓  Black is much better, but White stays in the game. }
27... Nxf2 28. Rxb4 Ne4 29. Rb8+ Rf8 30. Rxa8 Rxa8 31. Qc7 Nxd2 32. Bxd2 Qb1+
33. Kf2 Qb6+ { 33...Qxa2  would have led to a much simpler win. } 34. Qxb6 axb6
35. Be3 Bc6 36. Bxb6 Rxa2+ 37. Kg3 Ra3 { Black missed a clean win:   37...g5! }
38. Kf4 Bxf3 { An impatient exchange. } 39. gxf3 Kf7 40. h4 g6 41. Bd8
{ And suddenly it turns out that White has a fortress. } 41... Rd3 42. Bg5 Ke6
43. Kg3 Ke5 44. Kf2 Rb3 45. Ke2 Kd4 46. Bf6+ Kc4 47. Bg5 Rd3 48. Bh6 Kc3 49.
