O-O O-O 9. Nbd2 a5 10. Qe2 Bd6 11. a4
{ 11.Ne4  is covered in the theoretical section } 11... h6
{ A reasonable move, preventing Ng5 and preparing ...Re8. } 12. Re1 Re8 13. Bb5
Bg4 14. h3 Bh5 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. dxe4 { 16.Qxe4  Bg6  17.Qg4  Qc8= } 16... Rf8
{ This move is not bad, but it is unnecessarily passive.  It was advisable to play   16...f5!  e.g.  17.Bd2  f4=  and Black, having gained space on the kingside, has excellent chances. }
17. Bc4 Qe7 18. g4 Bg6 19. h4 Nd8 20. h5 Bh7 21. Nh2
{ 21.g5  could be well met by  21...Kh8!  22.gxh6  gxh6  23.Bxh6  Rg8+  24.Kh2  Qf6  25.Qe3   25.Bd2  Rg4!  The point. A forcing sequence ensues:  26.Rg1  Bxe4!  27.Bg5!  Qf5!  28.Nh4!  Rxh4+  29.Bxh4  Bf3!  30.Qe3  e4+  31.Rg3  Bxg3+  32.fxg3  Qxh5∓  Bxe4  26.Qxe4  Qxh6  27.Rg1  Qxh5+  28.Qh4  Qxh4+  29.Nxh4  Ne6⩱  Black is a pawn up, although White should hold a draw. }
21... Ne6 22. Nf1 Qf6 23. Ng3 Nf4 24. Bxf4 Qxf4
{ Both sides are very solid. From this moment on, both sides play natural moves and a draw is a logical outcome. }
