1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d5 7. exd5 Nxd5
{ We have reached one of the most important structures in this repertoire. White mainly plays against the e5-pawn and sometimes grabs space on the queenside. Black, on the other hand seeks counterplay against the d3-pawn and on the kingside, where he has the pawn majority. Typical continuations include ...Nb6, ...Bg4, ...Bd6 or ...f6 @@StartBracket@@after ...Nb6@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Nbd2 Nb6 9. Bb5 Bd6 10. Re1 Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. Ne4 f5 13. Ng3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3
Qd7
{ Up to this point we were following the line covered in our theoretical section - see here }
15. a4 a6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. c4
{ Taking d5 under control, so that 18.a5 will force the knight back to c8. However, this is not a great inconvenience for Black. }
17... Rab8 18. a5 Nc8 19. c5
{ 19.Rb1  c5⩱  intending ...Ne7-c6 or ... Ne7-g6, Black is more comfortable. }
19... Bxc5 20. Rxe5 Bd4 21. Re1 Nd6 22. Ne2 Rfe8 23. Bf4
{ After this move White loses a pawn for no compensation.  White should have played   23.Rb1  Bf6  24.Be3  Compared to the game, this is a much healthier way of sacrificing the pawn.  24...Bxb2  25.Nd4  Bxd4  26.Rxb8  Rxb8  27.Bxd4=  With a bishop posted actively on d4, White has enough compensation for the pawn. }
23... Bxb2 24. Rab1 Nb5 25. Ng3 Bc3 26. Rxe8+ Rxe8 27. Be3 g6 28. Qd1 Bxa5 29.
Ra1 Bb6
{ Black missed a clean way to win:   29...f4!  30.Qb3+  Qd5  31.Qxd5+  cxd5  32.Rxa5  fxe3  33.Ne2  exf2+  34.Kxf2  Re6-+  Being two pawns up in an endgame, Black should win easily. }
30. Bxb6 cxb6 31. Rxa6 f4 32. Ne2 f3 33. Nf4
{ A losing blunder. The knight is very unstable here, which causes White's downfall.  After   33.Ng3  White was fine:  33...Nd4   33...fxg2  34.Qb3+  Qf7  35.Qxf7+  Kxf7  36.Rxb6=  34.Rxb6  Qc7  35.Rb1= }
33... Nd4 34. Ra1 Rf8
{ White has no way to defend the knight, so he resigned. } *

