1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. c3 d5 7. exd5 Nxd5
{ We have reached one of the most important structures in this repertoire. White mainly plays against the e5-pawn and sometimes grabs space on the queenside. Black, on the other hand seeks counterplay against the d3-pawn and on the kingside, where he has the pawn majority. Typical continuations include ...Nb6, ...Bg4, ...Bd6 or ...f6 @@StartBracket@@after ...Nb6@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Re1 Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. Nbd2 Nb6 11. Bb5 Bd6 12. Bxc6
{ For  12.Ne4  see here } 12... bxc6 13. Ne4 Re8
{ A cautious aproach to the position.  It was perfectly fine to play   13...f5  14.Ng3  Bxf3  15.Qxf3  Qd7=  with a promising position, in analogy to the main line after 12.Ne4. }
14. c4 Nd7 15. Bd2 c5 16. Ng3 Bg6 17. Bc3 f6
{ This unnecessarily allows Nh4.  It was better to continue building up the position in the centre with   17...Re6⩱ }
18. Nh4 Bf7 19. Nhf5 Bf8 20. Qe2
{ Around here White loses the thread of the game.  He should have played   20.Qd2  preventing ...g6 in view of Nh6+ and preparing f2-f4. }
20... a5
{ Black should have taken the opportunity to chase the knight away:   20...g6!  21.Ne3  f5  22.Ngf1  Bg7  23.Nd2  Nf8⩱ }
21. b3
{ Giving Black's a pawn a target.  It was still advisable to play   21.Qd2 }
21... a4 22. Qc2 { Another weak move, after which White is busted. } 22... Nb8
{ The knight rerouts to b4 with a powerful effect. } 23. Ne4 Nc6 24. Nfg3 Nb4
25. Bxb4 cxb4
{ Black has a bishop pair and strong play along the a file and against the weak d3 pawn, which gives him a decisive advantage. }
26. Rad1 Qd7 27. Nd2 axb3 28. axb3 Bc5 29. Nf3 Ra3 30. Ne4 Bd4 31. Rb1 Rea8 32.
Nxd4 Qxd4 33. Qd2 Ra2 34. Qe3
{ In case of   34.Qxb4?  Black would win with  34...f5!  35.Nd2  Rd8  36.Rbc1  e4-+  However, after the game continuation White is also lost. }
34... Qxe3 35. fxe3 Bg6 36. Nf2 R8a3 37. e4 Rc2 38. Ra1 Rb2 39. g4 Rbxb3 40.
