1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 b5 7. Bxb5 Nxd4 8.
Nxd4 exd4 9. Qxd4 Qf6 10. O-O Bb6 11. Qb4
{ A move of questionable value.   11.Qd3  This is the most natural and best retreat, considered as the main line. }
11... Ne7 12. Ba3
{ White tries to stop Black from castling, but Black has a simple and effective response at his disposal. }
12... a5 13. Qa4 O-O 14. Bxd7
{ This is way too greedy.  For better or worse, White should have settled on   14.Nd2  when after  14...d6  he has a nice equalizer:  15.e5!  Qxe5  16.Nc4  Qg5  17.h4!   17.Nxb6  Bb7!  An important intermezzo.  18.f3  Qe3+  19.Kh1  Qxb6⩱  White lacks enough compensation for the pawn.  Qf6  18.Nxb6  cxb6  19.Rfd1  Nf5  20.Rab1=  White prepares 21.Bd3. The position is dynamically balanced. }
14... Bxd7 15. Qxd7 Rfd8 16. Qb5
{ Obviously, White cannot take the knight:   16.Qxe7??  Qxf2+!  17.Rxf2  Rd1 }
16... Ng6 17. Bc1
{ A sad necessity, as otherwise White could not develop his knight. } 17... Nf4
{ 17...Ne5!  offered Black much better chances:  18.Qe2  Rab8∓  Preapring to invade down the b file in case of  19.Be3  Bxe3  20.Qxe3  Rb2! }
18. Bxf4
{ After   18.e5  Black has an explosive opportunity:  18...Nh3+!  19.gxh3  Qg6+  20.Kh1  Bxf2!  21.Nd2   21.Qb7  c6!  22.Nd2  Rab8  23.Qxb8  Rxb8  24.Rxf2  Qc2∓   21.Rxf2  Rd1+  22.Rf1  Qe4+  23.Kg1  Rxc1  24.Rxc1  Qe3+  25.Kg2  Qxc1∓  Rxd2  22.Qb7  Rdd8  23.Bf4  Bh4∓ }
18... Qxf4 19. Na3
{ It was more advisable to defend with   19.Qe2  e.g.  19...h5  20.Na3  Rd2  21.Qe1  h4  22.Nc4  Rd3  23.Nxb6  cxb6  24.Rd1  Rxd1  25.Qxd1  Qxe4  26.Re1  Qc4  27.Qc2= }
19... Rd2 20. Nc4 Rxf2
{ After this move the game fizzles out to a draw.   20...Bxf2+  21.Kh1  Re2  offered Black great winning chances, e.g.  22.Nd6  Rc2  23.Qc6  Rf8  24.Qxc7  Qg4  25.e5  Be3  26.Qc6  Bf4  27.Qe4  Re2  28.Qf3  Qxf3  29.Rxf3  Bxe5∓ }
21. Nxb6 Rxf1+ 22. Rxf1 Qe3+ 23. Kh1 cxb6 24. Qd5 Rf8 25. c4 h6 26. e5 Qe2 27.
